Slackblast: 
Steaming Hot in March (Downrange Q!)
DATE: 2023-03-02
AO: <#C017KB6LEP7>
Q: <@U048GCZ7GBY>
PAX: <@U048GCZ7GBY> 
FNGs: F3 Houston: Happy, Fabuloso, Pappy, Shortstop, Kane, Yoda, Rocky Top, Sagat, Carpool, Fair Weather, Ladybug, Big Money
COUNT: 13
Broomstick on Q from F3 Plainfield 

WARMUP: Arm Circles, Tappy Taps (Grass Grabbers here), Abe Vigodas, Imperial Walkers, Motivators

THE THANG: 

o Thang 1 – all PAX in a circle, assigned a specific exercise. One PAX in the middle doing 
25 WW2 sit ups (or bog boys is fine). PAX do their assigned exercise during those 25 
WW2 situps, then everyone rotates one spot and does that exercise until all exercises 
are done. OK to have multiple PAX at a station if there is more PAX then exercises. 
Exercises are:
1. Curls
2. Merkins
3. Air Squats
4. Chest Press
5. Dips (assign to someone near the ledge to the grass)
6. SSH
7. Air Squats
8. Skull Crushers
9. Burpees
10. Lawnmowers
11. Lunges In Place
12. Overhead Press
13. The 25 situps in the middle (WWII or Big Boys)

Thang 2 – Pearls on a yo-yo. Scout team runs out first (faster runners, led by Q). Turns 
around at a point and heads back to the pack. Where they meet they do an exercise. 
Rinse & Repeat for each exercise. Get back to flags by 6:10 am for Mary
:black_small_square: 15 each: Carolina Dry Docks/Bobby Hurleys
:black_small_square: 15 each: Gradycorns / Bonnie Blairs
:black_small_square: 15 each: Merkins / SSH

MARY: LBCs, Heel Touches, Big Boys, Hammers, Freddy Mercury, Plank

ANNOUNCEMENTS: Local

COT: I wanted to do something team-based because since Halloween when I was FNG, I feel 
like I’m part of a new team, F3. This organization has all the characteristics of a high-performing team – a vision, a common goal, interdependencies, trust, diversity. And 
every team member is here because they want to be and choose to be. There aren’t 
any other teams that I’m a part of that truly have all of those characteristics. What I 
think is amazing and different about this team is that it’s everywhere, all over the 
country. If you haven’t done any downrange posts you should. Let’s remember to keep 
giving this gift away, and that with some people it can take a long time!

Floridian Flamingos
(1 minute under tension)
Setup: Start in a tall standing position.
Cue 1: Anchor your heel to your butt with the same-side hand, balancing on the ground with one foot.
Cue 2: Slightly bend the knee that is in contact with the ground.
Cue 3: Hinging at the hips and keeping your back as straight as an arrow, reach down and tap the foot. Reset. Repeat with the opposite side. (30 seconds each side)

Regular Burpees
(1 minute)

Board the plane

Japanese Sumo Burpees
Set Up: Start in a tall standing position with your feet just outside of your shoulders and your hands placed high overhead.
Cue 1: Lower your hips. Do your best to meet or break parallel to the ground. Reset
Cue 2: Lift your left knee as high as you can and slowly bring it out and over to a super-wide (sumo) squat position. Keep your hands overhead throughout. Once your foot makes contact with the floor, go into another overhead squat. Reset. Repeat with the right side.

Mongolian MOAB
Cue 1: Complete a Leonidas burpee (two push-ups at the bottom)
Cue 2: After completing your second push-up, kick the left foot up to the left hand. Release the left hand from the floor as you kick the right foot through.
Cue 3: Transition and kick through with the left foot.
Cue 4: Kick the feet back into the top of a push-up position. Complete another push-up.
Cue 5: Jump your feet back in toward your hands. Stand up and jump.

CoT:
Mostly we accelerate. Whether you've just started and you are in your first few weeks or you just completed your VQ or celebrated one year. Sometimes we hit a wall and plateau. Things become routine, be revert back to Sad Clown life to a degree,  not totally, but we're checking boxes, I wake up early, I work out (not really pushing myself to the max.), Queen starts to get the better of me and once in awhile we fall down. Fart sack a workout or two, diet completely goes to shit. "Falling and getting back up is what brings you success."

Whatever you need to get back up, do it. Maybe it's adding something to the routine to shake things up like EC runs or an EC Ruck or two a week. It could be traveling to other AOs, in Naperville,  Chicago,  Wheaton, Batavia. What about Qing once a week. Mud races, Ruck events.  

"If you're going through hell, keep going" - Winston Churchill 

“Success is not final, failure is not fatal: it is the courage to continue that counts.” – Winston Churchill

Prayer
Moment of silence and strong prayers for Foundation who just lost his dad

Naked Man Moleskin 
We did a ton of running for a boot camp beatdown, lots of Indian Runs. I kept yelling at the PAX to slow the IR down and quicken the sprints. It fell on deaf ears. The pace was definitely out of my comfort zone. I definitely didn't want to fall behind since I was QIC. These men pushed me outside my comfort zone to a higher level. No this wasn't a RC, but felt like one

·      Run Back to lot completing the loop

Mary:

CoT:
You have heard the analogy strength in numbers & you have probably heard the old adage that you can easily break a single match stick but try breaking multiple match sticks & it cannot be done. Over the last 18 months I have learned that the power of a group doing something can push you beyond your boundaries then what you can do alone. I started probably running 10 years ago off & on & have completed a couple half marathons throughout my life. During that time I trained by myself & THOUGHT I was pushing myself to my max effort hitting just under 9 min miles at my personal bests. When I first started my training with my Ragnar brothers, especially Team Dingo, I realized how wrong I was. Running together with these men having them push me has made me a stronger runner & accomplishing things I never thought I could do. I have done 5ks under 8:30 mile pace & under 8:45 for 10ks, numbers I never thought were possible. This goes for anything in life men it is harder to do it alone then it is to do it with people you care for & care for you weather it is fitness, fellowship, or faith. Don’t be the single match that can be easily broken find your other matches to make you stronger overall.
 
“Two are better than one, because they have a good reward for their toil. For if they fall, one will lift up his fellow. But woe to him who is alone when he falls and has not another to lift him up!” Ecclesiastes 4:9-12

CoT:
·       This week we talked about consistency in Q-source & the importance of simplicity to create that consistency or I like to refer to as “simplicity being the kryptonite to complexity”. What does all that mean. There is chaos & flux in our everyday lives & we are challenged to make decisions in that chaos & flux at a moments notice not to mention the chaos that happens in times of severe stress & limited visibility in our lives. So how do you deal with that complexity when it comes, easy simplify the things you can control. Lay the bricks in your life or positive habits that join to make guardrails or routines in your life. If you simplify the easy things in your life by creating routines you can spend more time being prepared & solving for the flux that comes up. Today is my 493rd post in a little over 2 years. As I approach my 500th post I think about the little bricks like setting my alarm, setting my clothes out the night before, filling up my water to put in the fridge before I go to bed as all little habits that I have created to make posting with F3 a routine. Things I don’t even realize I do anymore but are all little bricks that have helped lay the guardrails to get me up in the morning. Ultimately those bricks that have formed my workout routine are second nature now & has allowed me to get right to be prepared & deal with the flux of my life I know is coming where I can spend my efforts there. So my challenge to all of you is find those opportunities to simplify the little things so they are the kryptonite to the complexity that is your life. AYE!!

IPC Week 4 - MaryAnne's Mayhem
WoR 5:00 AM, begin workout at 5:07, Finish at 6:00.

Rep-based workout
Set the timer for 52 minutes 30 seconds
Measure out 25 yards
The Thang
Exercises are to be done in sets of 25 reps. After completing 25 reps, run to the cone that is 25 yards away and do 3 burpees. After the 3 burpees, run back and continue with exercise.
Exercises
200 curls
175 squats
150 Overhead Press
125 Kettlebell Swings
100 Merkins
75 Thrusters
50 Bonnie Blairs (right leg-left leg = 1 rep)
25 Blockees
If you finish all of the exercises, repeat in reverse order from the last time you just did it.
The burpees DO NOT count in your rep count.
900 reps is the total if you get through all of the exercises.
You absolutely need a :coupon: and the plan is to run the 25 yards in grass (unless there is dew again).

CoT/ Naked man Moleskin
Wreck-It had the most reps, I had 865 total reps with Happy Camper right there as well. Jellystone emptied the tank.

For CoT we had a discussion about the Olympiad, the state of the AO and that we need regulars to support it and brainstormed ideas on how to get momentum going again. We not only need to encourage the newer PAX but make sure men do not burn out after 1-2-3+ years. If you have ideas, share them with LT.

Prayer and Flag picture - Numbers were low today but the effort was mighty. We also recognized a Disco Ball fartsack.

I wanted to talk a little about a topic that we discussed at Q-source yesterday.  Contentment.  We talked about the difference between joy and happiness.  Happiness is more of an instant gratification and obtaining individual things where as joy is an internal thing and doesn’t require anything external.  Joy seekers are not reliant on anything to make them happy.  They obtain joy through getting right and living right.  A joy seeker sees challenges as opportunities to grow stronger.
Reflect on something that you think you might want to get lately.  Will it bring you joy or simply make you happy for the moment?  We control our joy.  No one else has that power over us.  No object has that power either.
My challenge to you is to try and be cognizant of this idea that nothing has the power to make us joy filled other than what is within ourselves.

COT: 
Our mission is to plant, grow and serve small workout groups for men for the invigoration of male community leadership

Leadership is a skill that a person must learn and master during their lifetime rather than an attribute of their character with which they are born. As a skill, it is like learning to play the piano. If it were an attribute, it would be like having blue eyes or a square jaw.

Because it is a skill, a person must commit to learning to lead in the same way that they would learn to play the piano. The degree to which they will ultimately master it will depend both upon their natural ability and their willingness to practice. 

Because we are all born with some leadership ability, even a man with very little natural skill can still be an effective leader if he is willing to practice hard. But a man who will not practice at all will never master the skill even if he is born with the heart of a lion. The decision to become an effective leader is volitional. No one else can make it for you.

F3 was born on January 1, 2011. Its initial purpose was to give men a way to improve their lives by exercising together as part of a workout community. While that worked, we quickly realized that the members of F3 needed more than just physical fitness to improve their lives. They also needed help in mastering their leadership skills. Their families, their workplaces and their neighborhoods were all communities that needed leadership just as much as the F3 workout community did. 

From this need, F3’s mission of the invigoration of male community leadership evolved.

To help the men of F3 learn and master leadership we began to develop a body of practices that we drew from the timeless principles of leadership and their effective application in our workout community. Initially, these leadership practices were transmitted between us verbally, like a set of oral traditions passed around a campfire.
As F3 grew, and the limits of this rudimeawere internally integrated and were as useful to our group in Seattle as they were to the men in Savannah.
From this search, the QSource was born. It is the integrated expression of F3’s leadership philosophy. It is our leadership manual. As such, it is designed to be used by F3 members to improve their leadership skills for the benefit of their families, workplaces and neighborhoods. However, because it is based on timeless principles, it is also useful for any group that wants to improve the leadership skills of its members.

I have been in a management position for 4 years, company for 15. Put a lot of pressure on myself, way too much. Forgot who I was that got me  to that position. Forgot that work needs to be positive, fulfilling and fun. As a leader of 24 men at work, I needed to focus on my teams growth, not me carrying the burden of everything on my shoulders. You can't lead if you aren't "right".
Best thing I did was apply for a  new job with a different organization. Bottom line, we are only 1 man, we can only do so much. Focus on what's important in life and work, don't be like me and super stressed.  I will NEVER let that happen again and neither should any of us. 
AYE?

COT:

December is a time when we begin to reflect on the last year and begin to prep for the upcoming year. I will leave you with these 5 questions to ponder as we begin to close out 2021 and prepare for 2022.

What is the most important goal I achieved this year? 
Financial I have made huge strides in getting some previous debt under better control(except for this free workout group)

In what area do I feel I've made my biggest improvements? 
Reconnecting with all Members of my family and giving both my M and each 2.0 the time and attention they each deserve.

What was the most challenging part of this year for me? 
Recovering from my broken tibia and Fibula. 7 months of rehab to return to the gloom was the hardest thing I have ever done both mentally and physically.

Who were my most valuable relationships with? 
Outside of my family it has been my F3 Brothers who have always been by my side.

What's the biggest mistake of the year, and the lesson learned as a result? 
Breaking my leg and realizing that I may be getting to old to relive my glory days! Joking of course. My biggest mistake was professionally allowing things at work to be brought home and disrupt my attitude and time with my family last school year. This school year I made a point and a goal to disengage from all work once I left for the day. No checking emails, no texts to or from co-workers about work. Once I left work it was about the time with my family. I have found that it has made me a happier person in both environments as I am not constantly trying to be present in both worlds.

Ended with prayers for Abby Glassman, Boston Butts M, and the community in Michigan. Followed by a moment of silence for unspoken prayers in our hearts.

A teams mission is a course of action taken to achieve a particular purpose.  Dilly Dilly led a great discussion a few weeks ago on how it is important for individuals to have a mission and the idea that instead of New Year’s resolutions that we reflect and come up with one word that embodies our goals for the upcoming year.  Then, share this word and the reason behind it that makes it meaningful to you to with at least one person that will help hold you accountable.
So, today I share my word for 2022.  Live.  I have spent a good portion of my life holding back.  Being held back by my anxiety and lack of self confidence and self doubt.  I heard myself saying no to everything.  Always making excuses.  No, I can’t go meet up and play some golf with friends because I was afraid that would make my ex’s upset.  It was always no, no, no and I can’t or I’m not good enough.  I say f_ck that. 
2022 is supposed to be the Chinese year of the Tiger.  I say 2022 is going to be the year of the Foundation.  
I challenge you to reflect and come up with your word that will embody your mission for 2022.
Aye? 
Ended with prayer

COT: 
I've been reading Michael Easter's book, _The Comfort Crisis_, recently and came to see an oft repeated COT thing in a different way. We often remind each other that "No one is guaranteed tomorrow", a good thing to remember. There is another truth that this alludes to: Someday, not very long from now in the grand scheme of things, it is guaranteed that YOU WILL DIE. Not only that, but everyone you know will die. Everything you have will decay to dust, even this planet will one day cease to exist. That can feel a bit heavy to think about. But, if you give some time to remember this unavoidable truth you may find that you approach the rest of your day a little differently. That thing you know you want to do "someday" may now be the thing you take concrete steps toward. That moment where you might have nodded your had, or been a little bothered by the demands of your family may be the moment you appreciate them a little more and hold them a little closer. In short:

Remember you will die.

Proceed accordingly.

THE THANG: Ran through the subdivision but Foundation missed a turn and we got lost.  Ended up running an extra mile or more before finding our way back to the track.

When looking to improve our running times basically increasing the rhythm speed and in turn controlling the pace of the run.  One very easy way to improve your distance running times is to have a faster foot turnover.  Turnover is the number of times your feet push off during each minute of running.  We set into a cadence that feels comfortable and today we will look at helping to improve.  
For this we will use the straightaways on each side of the track for working on our foot turnover.  I have lights at the beginning and end of each straightaway.  Its 100 meters and you will count to yourself how many times your right foot pushes off between the lights and then multiply by two.  Slow mosey the curve and then try to better on the next straightaway.

MARY:  Bigboys 52, stretches and high planks
ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: For my COT today, I wanted to talk about happiness.  I reflected on it, studied reading books about it and tried to figure out this deep topic for years.  How do you become happy?  
What I found out at least for me is that happiness doesn’t come from anything or anyone.  The source of happiness is within you.  You alone have the source of happiness within you.  It is a sum of a bunch of little things.  For me, my key to finally reaching happiness was a bunch of things like finally letting go of the resentment towards my ex wife and her actions, being appreciative of the gifts in my life and thankful for what I have, developing my self confidence to levels that it has never been at, trying to think about helping others instead of focusing on what I may not have and many other little things.  I don’t worry about things I can not control.  It was simple and has taken me years to finally figure out how to implement.
I can finally say that I am happy.  But like our fitness, we can never stop accelerating and I keep working on all of the little things that led me to this wonderful place.  
My challenge to you today is reflect on your level of happiness.  If you are not there, I challenge you to reflect on what are the little things in your life that might be getting in the way and work on your mindset with them?  Is it jealousy of some material good like my house isn’t as big as his or something like that?  Or why don’t they want to hang out with me?  Or Why don’t I get a raise or promotion at work?   
Pick one thing and reflect on why you feel the way you do and try and come to a level of contentment.  You slowly peel these things off and eventually you will have taken a lot of clutter off your “emotional plate”.  
Aye?
F3 is not a religious organization but we will end in a prayer.  You’re welcome to join or take a minute to connect with your sky Q.  Are there an intentions we can acknowledge? 

Thanks to Toby for having my 6 and to Jellystone, Bob Villa and Boston Butt for coming out and joining me this morning.

After some recent encounters over the past month, I thought I’d repeat a previous COT message.  

Vulnerable meaning capable of being physically or emotionally wounded.   Open to attack or damage.   A state of emotional exposure that comes with a certain degree of uncertainty. It involves a person's willingness to accept the emotional risk that comes from being open and willing to love and be loved.  

Being vulnerable means there’s  a risk of you feeling some sort of pain.  As humans we are built to avoid pain.  This is not abnormal, it’s part of our DNA, it’s how we were made.

Being vulnerable means there’s a chance people will find out who we really are.  You know as men, we are not very good at being vulnerable.  I can certainly attest to that in my own life. I tend to hold things in.  I try and portray that I’m  strong and that very little bothers me. I tend to not want to burden others with my issues.  I believe I can deal with things internally.  I stray away from the touchy/feely things.  You know what is so ironic  and crazy about all this…most of you likely do some of the same things.  Why? because it’s how we are all built.  

All too often FEAR keeps us from being vulnerable.  FEAR of pain, FEAR of uncertainty, FEAR of the unknown, FEAR of what people will think of us, FEAR of being raw and letting people see who we really are. 

Don’t let FEAR control you.  Don’t let the FEAR of pain be an obstacle. Rather be raw, be real, show us men whom all workout together in the gloom who you really are.  Tell us men what you’re really going through.  We all have “stuff” so we can all empathize with each other.  I know for a fact that some of the “stuff” I’m going through or have gone through is some of the same “stuff” that this guy and that guy has gone through or is going through right this very minute.  We may not be able to fix everything or anything for that matter, but we can certainly put our hand on each others shoulder, we can listen, we can empathize, we can pray, and we can walk with each other and be there for each other, BUT (and you’ve heard the saying nothing matters before the BUT) 

WE FIRST NEED TO BE VULNERABLE!  Being vulnerable engenders Trust.  Look at that dude next to you…..Do you trust HIM!   It’s okay to be vulnerable.  Aye!

TAPS (Thoughts and Prayers). Amen!

COT: Since joining F3 back in November I have really tried to embrace what F3 is and become a better leader and all around person. I have focused on being positive as much as possible and finding the good in every situation. But no one is on 10 all day every day. 

Toxic positivity can be defined as disregarding
unpleasant emotions and offering false
assurances in place of empathy. It comes from
feeling uncomfortable and responding to
someone in distress with an uplifting, "everything
will be okay" speech.
Toxic positivity is bad because it dismisses the
importance of negative emotions, contributes to
feelings of disconnection, and can ultimately lead
to more distress.
I fear that many people are so afraid of negativity
that they have created a society that only accepts
positive comments and praises. This is a problem
because it shields people from the real world and
prevents them from developing their skills to deal
with difficult situations.
Toxic positivity indicates that only positive
emotions and experiences are valid and that any
negative feelings or experiences should be
suppressed. Unfortunately, this can lead to
people pretending everything is okay when it's
not, which can ultimately be harmful.
On the other hand, healthy support is about
providing people with the space to express their
positive or negative emotions. It's about listening
with empathy and offering genuine help and
encouragement based on the other person's
experience.

What I took from that is that it’s ok to not be ok or over the top positive. We should try to keep things in perspective and maintain positivity whenever possible. As leaders we can check in on people, empathize, and be the influence of support and leadership that we have come to know through F3. 

Ended in prayer with special prayers for Tommy Bartletts wife and corningstones daughter.

COT:  
For my COT today, I want to start with a quote “Do it now. Sometimes later becomes never.”
Life is short.  There is only one today Friday April 8, 2022.  Make the most of it.  Don’t put off to tomorrow what you should do today.  We have many things that we can do today but how many of them are really important?  What are the things that we should do today?  Which things are so important that we should not wait to get them done?
My Dad passed away while working actually operating the equipment just before his 80th birthday.  He worked long hours for his whole life putting so much effort into his excavating business.  He missed a lot of the activities that my siblings and I participated in as kids.  In his last few years, he started making a point to attend most of the activities that my daughters participated in.  He wanted to meet up for coffee on my way to work.  I would make the time no how busy my day was.  I look back at those short 15 minute talks we had over a cup of Dunkin’ coffee for most of the last year or two and hold them very dear to my heart.  For the last several years he would tell me that was going to take a week or two off next winter and take my Mom on a nice vacation.  He even told me that during our last few mornings of having coffee before he died.  He didn’t go on that trip with Mom.
The old saying “No one on their deathbed ever said they wished they had worked more.”  Losing Dad last year really got my attention.  But hitting bottom losing him and going through the divorce was the final catalyst of me making sure to have my priorities straight.  Reflecting on my priorities over the last several month have led me to the following conclusions:
•	I love my daughters dearly.  I would die to protect them.  I have finally let go of the petty bullshit with my 1st ex wife (their Mom) try to take a step back and do what I feel is the best route to least impact them negatively when she does things to try and hurt me or assert dominance over me.  I have kept to this over the last 6 months even if it unfairly negatively affects me.  My girls well being is most important. 
•	I don’t enjoy my work.  I do it because I was told by my parents that I would be an engineer.  It’s simply a paycheck.  That’s a tough one because at this junction of my life post divorce I can not take a pay cut.  I have begun working towards my personal trainer certification though.  That is a passion of mine for so long.
•	What are my hobbies?  This one always stumped me for the past 15+ years.  I’ve been told working out isn’t a hobby. My reflection has left me with this conclusion.  Those people are full of shit.  I enjoy doing it.  My hobbies are working out, running, lifting, playing the piano (my 2nd Ex wife told me that you don’t seem to like the piano – again she was full of shit – I really enjoy it), reading, and doing activities outside such as fishing, hiking, working on home and yard improvement projects.
I wonder what my Dad would have done if he was given the opportunity to do one more thing…

COT: Since one of the missions of F3 is to invigorate male leadership and since today is Good Friday I discussed 5 leadership qualities that we can learn from the teachings of Jesus. 

1. Look at the potential in people, don’t seek perfection. The 12 disciples were all flawed men; one was even a traitor. Jesus picked them instead of those who had their stuff together. He saw the potential that was in those he called. And those broken, flawed men answered that call. 

2. Practice forgiveness. This one is self-explanatory. But in all the terrible events of Jesus’ life, he was still able to forgive. This one is definitely not easy, but it is freeing. 

3. Ask questions. When the religious leaders and disciples tried to question Jesus he, many times, answered with a question back at them. He wasn’t always trying to teach, but sometimes he would ask questions instead. As a leader, be inquisitive. 

4. Serve others. Again, his example of servant leadership cannot be topper. As a leader and a man always be willing to serve others. 

5. Lead with grace and accountability. Those who encountered Jesus were at many times at their worst. Jesus would sit with them and extend grace to them and their circumstances.  But many times he would tell them “sin no more.” He expected them to be accountable for the change that happened in their lives as a result of his grace. As leaders we must lead with grace, but also be willing to keep those we lead accountable to their actions.

COT:
At F3 we talk about picking up the six, helping those that are struggling, encouraging them to keep going, to help push them to do more, go that extra step, move beyond their “limits”…this motto has implications beyond F3 though. There are members of my family that struggle with depression and for the longest time I struggled with understanding how to help, what to do.. not having this affect me personally I didn’t know what they were feeling and how to deal with it. At times I would forget their struggles and get somewhat angry that they didn’t want to go out, be with friends, do something… then a few months ago it hit me, pick up the 6…we say that at F3 all the time. Go back help those that need help to move forward, become better, stronger, healthier…. why was I not applying that in my life at home? Someone I love is struggling and it’s my responsibility to pick them up, pick up the six! It was moment I will not forget, the light bulb went off and my life will never be the same.  Men, F3 is a lot more than a workout. While I heard the term pick up the six at workouts it wasn’t until I started reading and attending Q source that the pieces of the puzzle began forming in the entire picture Dredd envisioned when he began F3. Men, we are called by our creator to be more than we can imagine, to help those that need help, whether that be at a work out,  in our family, at work or at the store… be that someone that helps others.  Pick up the six! AYE!

Prayer: Ringo, Sparklers family, Toby and healing… for those in our hearts, those struggling with medical issues, God walk along side those today, give them strength to push through, and help us to pick up the six for those in our lives that need help. Amen.

CoT: For today’s circle of trust, I want to start with a quote
“It is never too late to be what you might have been.”
We all came to our first post for some reason.  I know that I wanted to get in better shape and lose some weight.  Maybe try out a different type of workout.  You guys probably had similar type goals.  I remember barely making it through that first 45 minutes.  Modifying, laying there panting on the ground while Boston Butt lead Mary for 4 more minutes.    But I came back and did a little better the next time and then another and another until I’ve posted over 70 times.  My point is that the hardest accomplishments are the most satisfying.  Think of a goal that you have.  Maybe losing a certain amount of weight, running a certain distance, I don’t know.  Just focus on that goal and keep working at it.  Every time you come out, every merkin that you do, it all gets you a little closer to reaching that goal.  It may seem way out of reach at first but you are getting a small bit closer with each try.  
 
Here's a story about a kid.  He was the chubby kid who the other kids picked on.  He went to the tryouts for the track team his freshman year of high school and wanted to run.  The coach told him that he would be better suited to try throwing shotput and discus instead of running.  But the kid was insistent that he wanted to be a runner.  The coach finally agreed to let the kid practice with the runners and couldn’t promise about letting him run at the track meets competively.  The kid went on a diet and busted his ass at every practice and was way behind all of the other runners especially at the beginning.  The first time he ran the 800 or half mile, he was lapped which is unheard of for that short of a distance race.  The other kids made fun of him but he kept his focus on his goals.  By the end of that season, he shaved off more than a minute off of his half mile time and lost 50 pounds.  He was regularly competing in the last couple of track meets and he continued on his training in the off season kept improving.  
I was that chubby kid.  I’ll tell you what.  I ended up as the captain of the team and almost qualified for state my senior year.  I could have let myself listen to and start believing that crap that I couldn’t and wouldn’t ever be able to do it.    
I look around and see some of the faces from my first workout and new faces too.  There are faces that I haven’t seen in months because those people are listening to their self doubt or maybe think that its too hard or that they can’t do it and will fail.  You can not fail if you just try and do not give up.  I challenge you to try to get closer to your goals be it fitness, work or personal life.  Or if you don’t have some clear goals then set some.  
I want to finish with a quote from Confucius, “It does not matter how slowly you go so long as you do not stop.”
Aye?
Ended w prayer

COT:
> Do what you can, 
> With what you have,
> Where you are.
It's pretty easy to get caught up in all that's going on around us these days. And it's natural, human and good to be concerned for the trouble in the world and the tragedies we see on the nightly news. However, our feelings about things, our empathy for those suffering half a world away doesn't DO anything. We have to remember to look around us and take up the resources at our disposal and the opportunities we have where we are to actually DO anything. Our empathy is wasted, our energies frittered away when we give them over wholly to problems that we do not have proximity with. If we use what we have at our disposal to take advantage of those opportunities that are right there where we are, we also may find that those opportunities and resources grow, and problems that once were well beyond our purview come further into our grasp. So, bring your focus back to what's in front of you, and if enough people do just that, we may find that those big insurmountable issues on the news, are really just the sum of the little things that each of us do everyday. We either get busy living or dying, and we're either making the world a better place or letting it slide into apathy and cruelty. Go do something good today.

CoT:
Talked about my recent experience with work.  The plant that I worked at in Tuscola, IL is closing down.  The site manager has moved on to a different job and I am backfilling him to help safely shut down the plant and help the people there.  The site is almost 70 years old.  At its peak, it employed over 1500 people.  To put that in perspective the current population of Tuscola, IL is around 4500.  Over time, units became unprofitable and they were shut down.  For the last 15 years or so there are only two running units with about 85 employees.  The threat of closing the entire plant has always been rumored but they were always able to do enough to keep things going.  Two weeks ago though, the company announced the closure of the plant.  You can imagine the impact on both the employees and the community (tax $'s).

As stated above, my mission is to make sure everything is done safely and we are able to help our folks find their next place of employment.  The site was my first opportunity to be a manager within my company and it holds a special place in my heart.  Although being away from my family during the week for the next 3 months or so isn't ideal, I feel fortunate to be able to give back to the people and the site.

Finished by reminding people to not take their current employment for granted.  Work is work but it is how we provide for our families.  Be sure to make sure you continue to develop yourself and build transferable skills because you never know when a change is around the corner.

CoT:
September is Suicide Awareness month, how many of you have been affected by a suicide? Most if not all PAX raised their hands. Suicide is more prevalent now than in any time in our nations history.  So many people are dealing with mental health issues, problems related to work, relationships, jobs, you name it, life is hard and even harder when people feel alone. Sometimes when a person cuts you off on the road, or is rude at the store, or seems to be putting their self before others, our initial response might be to judge them..“what an ass”, “who does he think he is”… but we have no idea what is going on in their lives. Maybe they just lost a loved one and are just barely getting through the day, maybe they lost their job, their home… you name there are a million things that could be going on in someones life and yet we sometimes judge them for their actions without knowing them. My M and I enjoy watching Ted Lasso, we were watching it last night with my daughter and he said something that stuck with me, ” Be curious not judgemental”.  Imagine how the world would be if we all kept that thought at the forefront of our minds. The next time someone cuts you off, puts themselves first, offends you try to think “I wonder what is going on with them.  What are they dealing with?“.  If nothing else it helps put your mind in the right place. Reach out to someone you know that is dealing with something, let them know your thinking about them, that you care, offer to talk about whatever it is they are dealing with, it could make a life changing difference. AYE!

CoT:

For today’s COT, I wanted to start with a quote that I saw the other day,
“There are friends, there is family, and then there are friends that become family.”
I have experienced a lot in my personal life over the past 6 weeks.  My marriage had gotten to a point where the constant fights and struggles left me feeling completely hopeless.  I remember at my lowest point when leaving work one day, standing at the balcony by the elevators at work and wondered if I would feel any pain if I ended it at that moment.  After standing there for about 10 to 15 seconds, I made a decision.  Nothing is that bad.  Obstacles can and will be overcome.  My daughters need me.  My family needs me.  
I talked to my Dad about that moment the next morning over a cup of coffee on the way to work.  He listened and I was able to talk getting some things off my chest as I normally could with him.  That was about a week before the final fight and I began the divorce proceedings which was about 5 weeks ago.  As I began moving through the process of the divorce, the support from my family, in particular my Dad, and many of you have been amazing.  I remember calling Scott (Bob Villa) the morning that first day of the divorce process while I was driving to meet a client or Toby when we did an EC run the next morning and we talked about it.  The outpouring of support from so many of you has been key to my holding it together during my divorce.  Another example was that first week when like 12-15 guys showed up to an impromptu 2nd F event at Taphouse to give me support.  
Sleeping on the couch at times and living out of Rubbermaid containers of a handful of my clothes, basically living like a homeless man in my own house, has been stressful.  But I have managed and coped with the support network I have.  Many nights, I end up staring at the ceiling contemplating what the future holds.  The unknown future for my girls and I, but I knew that my parents and family were there.  I would talk to my Dad on the way to and from work every day and we would meet up for coffee on the way to work or a quick lunch.  
Wednesday August 25, I took a day off from work to meet with a realtor with my wife.  We were finishing up signing the contract to list the house which would be the final phase of the divorce.  I called my Dad after we finished around 11:30-noon to talk to him about it.  He never answered.  He had passed away around 11am that morning.
The blur of the past week could have pushed me to my limits again.  But no, I am stepping up to be the person that my family needs me to be.  Taking on the role that Dad always took for us for my whole life.  I have found the words at the right moments to provide comfort and strength for my family.  I have stepped up to take action and make decisions at times when it has been needed.
A positive that has come out of the past week has been that my wife came over that first night and gave me her condolences and asked if we might be able to work together on the finishing up of the divorce and moving.  She came to the wake to pay her respects.  I will not forget her acts of kindness.  
I didn’t think that I could have gotten any more support than I had received from everyone out here during the divorce.  But the outpouring of support over the past week has left me in tears at times.  So many people have and continue to text and message me through slack seeing how I’m doing or come over while out here to ask if I’m ok.  Tuesday and Wednesday of this week has shown me what the true meaning of the 2nd and 3rd F stand for:
Tuesday - The day of the wake and the close to 50 F3 guys that came out to be there for me and my family really touched me and I have never witnessed anything like that before.  My Mom and siblings were touched as well.  They have told me a few times since then that they are so happy that I have such a great support group of friends.  They have been worried for me and keep telling me that I need to take care of myself and that I keep worrying too much for all of them.   They have said that you all are amazing and that they are thankful that I have you in my life.
Wednesday – The funeral lunch at Mistwood that 5-Putt, Fish Sticks, Corningstone and Cyclone put on was so awesome.  The food was incredible and even more so was Dan (5-Putt) coming up several times during it to see how I was doing and he personally was out there clearing plates and checking on food.  My family and I will never, I mean never, forget that ultimate selflessness and act of caring.  And when I was the last one getting ready to leave with my youngest daughter in my Dad’s work truck, Nickelback came over to give support and his condolences.
So, as I stand here today I know that even though I don’t have my Dad here as my unwavering support and basically my best friend, I know that I don’t have to face my uncertain future as I move and finalize the divorce alone.  I have a huge family which includes all of you, my F3 brothers.  I didn’t truly understand that when we call ourselves brothers out here what it meant to me.  I now really know what the true meaning of F3 is.  I love you all and I am so grateful and thankful for having you in my life.
Aye?
<@U020A3PMS14>  ended with a nice prayer for me and my family

Wanted to talk about the mind set of you vs you. With iron pax starting last week I  found myself after week zero comparing my time to others and thinking how the hell did they do that so fast, they must have cut a corner or cheated somehow. Instead of having the mindset of pushing myself to do my best and pushing my fellow pax to push themselves. I reflected on that mindset over the weekend at the lake house that F3 is about each one of us pushing ourselves to get better and pushing each other to get better. The competitive side got to me in week 0 and I had to change my mindset for this week. Just finishing an iron pax workout is an accomplishment and knowing I gave it my all is all I can ask of myself. Coming back from a horrific injury has made me realize that it’s not about what others can do, or how fast they do things. I post each day for me to get better and for me to push myself to do the best I can do. Our fellow pax are here to help each of us push ourselves to be the best we can be!

Naked Moleskin
For this of your that have not yet joined in some EC runs this is an excellent way to get warmed up before a beatdown, but it also helps to build your endurance up and will help you kick ass during a beatdown. Tons of pax are doing ec each day and it’s about getting out, enjoying some mumblechatter before a beatdown and getting ready to start your day. Do not be scared off thinking you have to run a sub 8 minute mile. If you commit to the EC runs there will be pax there to support you as you push to get better!

Talked about my 12 year old son that just started tackle football.  I think many of us who played football can relate to this.  When you start tackle football I think for most people (at least for me it was the case) it takes a while for the switch to flip and for them to be very aggressive in blocking and tackling.  I didn't start playing tackle football until freshman year in high school and I can say it took until the middle of my sophomore year.  You can tell that Zach is definitely in this mode.  I was proud of him though.  In his second game, he got his first tackle.  Unfortunately he brought the other person down by their facemask which resulted in a 15 yard penalty!  All I can say is that its a start.  My message is that trying anything new is a process.  If you are around individuals who are trying something new be encouraging and make sure you point out the positive steps that they are taking.  AYE!

The Thang:
This was a frankenstein mashup of stuff I borrowed from some Tacfit warmup I've seen with F3 Naperville's Face Plant, <https://gmb.io/|GMB Fitness>, and Ashtanga yoga. It looked something like this:

Side to side neck rotations
Up and down neck movement
Up and back and side to side (not circles--half circles)
Arm stretches (roll across front and back T’s)
Spine circles
Circle Squats (TacFit Squats)
Down dog/up dog push ups

Sun salutations

Low squat stretch
Low squat sidway shop (right foot to left hand, back to center and left foot to right hand)
Kong from down dog, bend knees then jump feet forward and the back and then forward
Quad press (back parallel with ground elbows and knees out at 45 touch knee to ground and push back up to elbow lockout
Lunge stretches
Leg kick throughs

<https://youtu.be/NG9qbvAN3gQ|Hip mobility>
Thread the needle, move it around and then give it a push after about 10 in and outs
Piriformis stretch (cross legs, and pull the top knee across)
Butterfly stretch (hand behind to keep but forward, and push knees down put both hands behind to work on shoulders too)
Frog - lower legs out to the side (horse on the ground) and sit back into it
Kneeling lunge (pull back leg up if you need more of a stretch)
Traveling butterfly - go from staff pose to butterfly by pushing hips forward with hands on the ground
Squat with internal rotations
Pigeon (can start with back knee up by front foot and work leg back for more challenge)

CoT:
I don't generally get too nervous about a Q anymore, but I've been sitting on the idea of doing something like this for awhile because I was nervous about my ability to pull it off and lead it effectively. Definitely felt challenged to have the patience to slow down and not rush through things in a frantic effort to fill the space with movement. In a boot camp burner you can always fill space (and take the attention off yourself) by having the pax do something horrible with burpees and running. I knew it would be hard/impossible to hide a lack of planning with this Q.

So I did what I had to. I put it up on the Q sheet and gave myself a deadline. I still didn't come up with the perfect plan that I wanted, but I came up with something better, a plan that got executed. Don't wait around for the perfect moment or the perfect plan. They aren't coming. Appreciate the moment you have, embrace the suck, and do something with no holding back. Even, maybe especially, if that means slowing down a bit, and being in the now, rather than striving for the next.

COT: For today’s COT, an article that I read online recently.  10 keys to happier living.
1. Doing things for others – Helping other people is not only good for them and is a great thing to do, it also makes us happier and healier too.
2. Connect with people – People with strong social relationships are happier, healthier and live longer.  
3. Take care of your body – Our body and mind are connected.  Being active makes us happier as well as being good for our physical health.
4. Live life mindfully – learn to be more aware and mindful of our life in front of us and quit dwelling on the past
5. Keep learning new things – Learning exposes us to new ideas and helps stay curious and also gives us a sense of accomplishment and helps boost self confidence.
6. Have goals to look forward to – This motivates us and helps to keep us excited with life
7. Find ways to bounce back – How we respond to major setbacks, stress and loss in our life has a huge impact on our well being.
8. Look for whats good – regularly experiencing positive emotions such as gratitude, contentment and pride help to boost our mood
9. Be comfortable with who you are – don’t dwell on your flaws or compare to others.  
10. Be part of something bigger – people who have meaning and purpose in their lives fell more in control and get more out of what they do.
Reflecting on these items, I found that I have been able to actively do at least 6 or 7 of these regularly through my involvement in F3 over the past year.  I challenge you to reflect on things in your life that you are grateful for on your drive home after the workout.  That’s an easier step to a happier self.
Aye?

COT: Today I wanted to talk about an area that sometimes is overlooked or forgotten about in relationships.  Compromise.  It can be with an M, a co-worker or a friend.
In order for people to work together when they disagree, they may have to compromise.  This means each person has to give up part of what they want so together they can avoid conflict, accomplish things together and both feel satisfied.
It is very important for a couple to be able to compromise.  Good compromises help you both grow together as a team.  They help build trust, accountability, consistency and security in your relationship.  A compromise shows that you have a common goal in mind rather than just your own happiness at heart.
It is important for our 2.0’s to witness their parents working through disagreements and the act of compromising.  That way they learn that there will be disagreements in any relationship but it can be worked through in a healthy, productive way.
My challenge to you is to think of a recent argument that you had with your M.  Could you have handled it differently?  If so, then keep this in mind the next time a disagreement comes up.

COT:
Spoke about Leadership and the Life of Colin Powell.  I highly recommend his book "It Worked for Me"  In the heart of his book he mentions his 13 rules.  These Rules formed the basis of his leadership principles.  They are as follows:
1. Its not as bad as you think and it will look better in the morning
2. Get mad, Get over it
3. Avoid having your ego so close to your position that if your position falls your ego goes with it
4. IT CAN BE DONE
5. Careful what you choose, you just might get it
6. Dont let adverse facts stand in the way of a good decision
7. You cant make someone elses choices, dont let them make yours
8. Check all the small things
9. Share Credit
10. Remain calm and be kind
11. Have a vision, be demanding
12. Dont take counsel of your fears or naysayers
13. Perpetual optimism is a force multiplier
The challenge of Leadership is to create change and facilitate growth.  Nobody achieves great things by giving minimal effort.

You do the exercises and then run to the center and do the exercises then run out to the next station going clockwise.  You always run back to the center like spokes on a wheel. COT: For my COT today, I wanted to start with a quote “You can do anything.  You can be anything you want to be.  As long as you believe in yourself and work hard.”
When I started out in the gloom in August 2020, I didn’t know what to expect.  I could run a 5K in about 30 minutes that first day.  I remember coming out and running short 0.5 mile EC runs by myself once or twice a week to try and improve.  After a few weeks it turned into 1 mile and 2 or 3 times a week.  Eventually, I was doing the short EC runs everyday and mixing in once a week doing a 1.5 mile run with other guys.  Now, I have been doing 1.5 -2 mile EC runs 6 days a week and I ran a 25 minute 5K at the beginning of September.  I have a vision of where I want to be and it may be a slow long journey but I will get there and am having a blast with you all along the way.  For those of you starting out and might be the 6 a lot.  Don’t be discouraged.  Envision and set a goal.  I like setting several smaller goals along the way.  Never be complacent and definitely never give up.  You can do it and you will do it if you just believe in yourself.  Look at that dude in the mirror when you are getting ready today.  He can do some great stuff if you just let him.  
My challenge in to set a fitness goal for yourself today.  It doesn’t have to be earthshattering.  Maybe, its doing 100 merkins a day for a month.  Or Running a PR time for 2 or 3 miles that is a 15 second pace faster by 4 weeks from now.  Just set one and work towards it and never stop believing in that awesome person looking back at you in the mirror. 
Aye?
Ended with prayer

"Now here we are. November 11, 2021. Veterans Day. And as is right, we once again pause to acknowledge the sacrifice and offer our gratitude to all who have served or are currently serving in the armed forces. Today we give honor to whom it’s due – to all military veterans.

The official ceremony takes place at Arlington National Cemetery at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier. A color guard representing all the branches of the military will execute "Present Arms" at the tomb, a Presidential wreath will be placed on the tomb, and a bugler will play "Taps."

At 11:00 this morning, Americans are encouraged to observe a moment of silence to remember those who fought for freedom. I would encourage you to take it a step farther.

Take time to pause and pray for our veterans and their families. Many of them have been heavily traumatized by war.  Ask God to heal their memories.  Others of them were terribly wounded.  Ask God to strengthen their bodies.

Finally, ask God to draw these men and women to Himself, the One who can give them ultimate peace.

ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT:  Gentlemen, it has been great to see everyones hard work and effort this week.  Reindeer games always seems to bring out the best in us.  I think this competition provides us with an opportunity to learn a lot about ourselves and each other. That being said, I want to remind everyone that six weeks is a long time and its very important to listen to our bodies when they speak. My goal today is to hopefully provide you with some keys to self preservation of our minds, bodies and spirits during this time period leading up to the holidays.  I believe there are 4 keys in helping us do so. 
 
The physical part- Stay mindful, Your body speaks to you, so be wise and listen to it.  Get adequate amount of sleep. This will determine how well our body metabolise.  Eat properly with a balanced diet. Eat foods that give us power and allow our bodies to heal, reenergize and allow our bodies to do what there supposed to do. 

The Mental part- Take the time to mindfully disengage. Even if its only 10 minutes, find the time to take a mental vacation and always remember why you do what you do.  

The emotional part- For the sake of your well being, emotions need to be released and expressed.  Scream, Cry, yell, Sing, Laugh.  All these things are therapeutic.  Remember that this is a marathon and not a sprint. Set realistic and achievable goals and stay on track. It is not required to set yourself on fire to keep others warm.  

The support part-  Find your peace!!!  Ask your self what gives you peace and where do I find it.  Its important to verbalize your wants, needs and things you are grateful for through prayer or some other means.  Commune with your M or significant other and find your center. I read the passage “Paradox of our Time”

The paradox of our time in history is that we have taller buildings but shorter tempers, wider freeways, but narrower viewpoints. We spend more, but have less, we buy more, but enjoy less. We have bigger houses and smaller families, more conveniences, but less time. We have more degrees but less sense, more knowledge, but less judgment, more experts, yet more problems, more medicine, but less wellness.

We drink too much, smoke too much, spend too recklessly, laugh too little, drive too fast, get too angry, stay up too late, get up too tired, read too little, watch TV too much, and pray too seldom. We have multiplied our possessions, but reduced our values. We talk too much, love too seldom, and hate too often.

We've learned how to make a living, but not a life. We've added years to life not life to years. We've been all the way to the moon and back, but have trouble crossing the street to meet a new neighbour. We conquered outer space but not inner space.

We've done larger things, but not better things. We've cleaned up the air, but polluted the soul. We've conquered the atom, but not our prejudice. We write more, but learn less. We plan more, but accomplish less. We've learned to rush, but not to wait. We build more computers to hold more information, to produce more copies than ever, but we communicate less and less.

These are the times of fast foods and slow digestion, big men and small character, steep profits and shallow relationships. These are the days of two incomes but more divorce, fancier houses, but broken homes. These are days of quick trips, disposable diapers, throwaway morality, one night stands, overweight bodies, and pills that do everything from cheer, to quiet, to kill. It is a time when there is much in the showroom window and nothing in the stockroom. 

Remember, spend some time with your loved ones, because they are not going to be around forever. Remember, say a kind word to someone who looks up to you in awe, because that little person soon will grow up and leave your side.
Remember, to give a warm hug to the one next to you, because that is the only treasure you can give with your heart and it doesn't cost a cent.
Remember, to say, "I love you" to your partner and your loved ones, but most of all mean it. A kiss and an embrace will mend hurt when it comes from deep inside of you. Remember to hold hands and cherish the moment, for someday that person will not be there again. Give time to love, give time to speak, and give time to share the precious thoughts in your mind. And always remember, life is not measured by the number of breaths we take, but by those moments that take our breath away.

ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: For today’s circle of trust, I want to talk about ways to be selfless in a selfish world.  Today’s world seems to be filled with self-promotion, a sense of entitlement and just plain selfishness.  So many people get so wrapped up in what they want or what they deserve or jealous of something that a friend got that they want.  It’s easy to see this in kids especially around birthday or Christmas time.  Getting them to sit and do their homework for a half hour can be a fight sometimes but I’ve witnessed my kids spend longer than that on making up a several page Christmas list of things that they swear that they need.  Or have you heard about a friend moving into a new house or just went on a nice vacation and have a twinge of jealousy thinking about it.
Society views happiness in having material goods or instant gratification and people keep getting caught up in having a certain new car or going on the super vacation that max’s out the credit card.  Does keeping up with the Jones make you truly happy?  I know that it doesn’t make me feel great after that initial aw this is cool phase wears off.  I don’t have any deep fixes out there for you today but just wanted to mention a few simple ways to be more selfless and less selfish:
•	Perform random acts of kindness – This one is easy.  We feel good when we do something nice for someone without wanting something in return.  At home, it can be something as little as doing a chore that you typically might not do or like to do to help out the M.   An example of this might be a self starter and do some cleaning that you typically might not do or get a few of the things off your “honey do” list when the M is out.   Another example might be to get the M some flowers with a kind note as a surprise when there is not an occasion.  You could also take dinner over for someone when they are sick.  I have taken dinner over to a friend’s house when they were sick so they didn’t have to cook.
•	Listen more – Just the simple act of keeping your mouth closed and letting someone talk to you can allow you to understand them better or know what they are going through.  Maybe you can help them feel a little bit better by relieving some stress when they talk and get it off their chest.
•	Volunteer/donate to less fortunate – Taking the focus away from what I want or need helps us to really appreciate what we have and finding the positive things in our life

COT:
November 16 marked the 20th anniversary of my M and I being together.  We have been together since high school have gotten to the point of being able to interpret even the slightest facial expression or mannerism.  This was not built quickly or even intentionally but developed organically over time.  I believe there are two main characteristics to every strong relationship regardless if it is a marriage, friendship or partnership and those are communication and trust.  When my wife and I started dating we would periodically have what we called a “relationship analysis”.   This is a deliberate conversation to discuss the trajectory of our relationship, discuss high points and yes even concerns.  Concerns could be anything from personal issues to external forces i.e. a new job or friendship that one feels is negatively impacting the relationship and / or family.  This was always done with the understanding that no hard feelings were to remain, we could be upset or frustrated with what each other said but we would always discuss a plan of action to reach an agreed upon resolution.  The second main piece of advise is something my M really pushed and that was never go to bed angry.  It did not matter how upset, mad or pissed we were area other we always ended the night with a kiss and an I love you to each other.  Even if the issue had not been resolved that simple act would reset our emotions and was a commitment to each other that our relationship is strong and this obstacle is temporary.

COT:  
How much does a 8 oz glass of water weigh?  How long will your be able to hold it?  There is no incorrect answer to the either question.  Just understand that the weight it not the most important factor…. It’s how long you need to hold it that matters.  If the glass of water weighs 1 pound eventually it will be to much for you to hold, it might take couple hours to half half a day but eventually you will start feeling sore, numb and tired.  Stress has the same affect on your body.  Regardless of the amount, if kept bundled inside it will negatively impact you.   Obviously the goal is to eliminate the stress but for many of us we cannot completely get rid of it.  But what we can do is reach out to family, friends and just talk.   It seems such simple thing to do but for many if us the act of reaching out for help is self interpreted as weakness or being a failure.  That is a stigma that is completely false and deeply rooted in masculinity.  A man should know their limits and know when to act for help.  Since being a FNG I have seen first hand the benefit of the this group, especially the emotional support.

I was supposed to post at the Olympiad, so I got up at 3:30, got ready and went down to make my coffee.  As it was brewing I heard my daughters bedroom door open.  I figured she woke up and was gonna go lay down in my bed with my M.  Once the coffee was made, I grabbed it and went to check on her, no sooner had I rounded the corner than I saw her coming down the stairs 100% dressed ready to go.  She said "Daddy is it time to go see to school and see Santa?"  I said "No Honey, you have a few hours".  Well this girl was wide awake, and obviously not going back to bed.  I had two choices, wake my M up at 3:45am to watch her, or stay home with her.  So I said "Do you want to go watch Christmas Movies until its time to go to school"?  This made her very happy, so we grabbed a couple bowls of cinnamen toast crunch and watched Christmas movies.  She was so excited to do it, and I was floating on cloud 9 watching the excitement in her face.  I lost 9 points yesterday by not posting but I could give a Fk, I got to have a moment with my daughter that I would never have gotten otherwise, and that was way more rewarding!!!!

COT:  For those of you that don’t know for work I am an operations manager for Wells Fargo and I lead a team of over 200 people.  A big part of my job is driving efficiency within my team and our process.  At work I talk to people a lot about spending the majority of their time on their “Big Rocks” each day.  The things that are most important instead of wasting time on non-value added tasks.  There is a time management matrix I reference often that has 4 quadrants.  The top two quadrants are labeled Important, the bottom Not Important.  The first column is labeled Urgent and the next is Not Urgent.  Top left Quadrant 1 - Urgent and Important.  These are pressing problems and crisis or deadline driven tasks.  Daily Fire-Fighting.  Top right Quadrant 2 - Important but not urgent - relationship building, new opportunities, long term planning, preventative activities, continuous improvement activities.  Quadrant 3 - Not Important but Urgent - interruptions, emails, calls, pressing matters that aren’t important.  Quadrant 4 - Not important, not urgent.  These are anything that wastes your time like busy work, time wasters, some calls/emails, any time or effort you put into complaining.  My challenge to you is to FOCUS and spend the most time on Quadrant 2 on improvement activities at work, be good at Managing the Quadrant 1 the fires, Avoid interruptions and busy work, and Limit anything that wastes time in Quadrant 4.  Aye?

POSE Running Method

More efficient, faster, run longer distances, less stress on ligaments, injury avoidance

Concept

Running is falling, falling forward.  Use gravity.  Use body weight and body position 

Body alignment.  Keeping everything in same plane (head, shoulders, hips, feet) 

Springness- slight bend in knees, knees over toes, hips over balls of foot

All runners repeat the same thing in every stride

Pass through a Running Pose
Fall from support
Pull foot off the ground 

Invariable elements
Pose
Falling
Pulling 

Variable  elements unnecessary and make us inefficient 
Heel, mid foot, forefoot 
Paw back, Knee drive 
Push off/arm pumping 

Drills

Springness position-  body is in equilibrium 

Pull foot up under hip.  Relaxed ankle.  Do both sides

Now Bring knee down until both are even (hamstring tightness and out of balance) 

Now Bring knee up and level with hip.  (Quads now tight and your out of balance ) 

Running Pose

Focus on pulling the foot up versus raising your knee.  Relax ankle.  Use support leg as a guide.  Knee on  support leg is slightly bent.  Weight is in front of foot, but use heel for stability 

Two Leg Hop
-Rhythmic hops 
-Break contact with ground as little as possible
-Proper body alignment 
-Fall forward, hop for 10yds, then jog for 10 yds

Rinse/Repeat

Toes In/Out
-Toes forward, toes in, toes forward, toes out
-fall forward and continue for 10yds then jog it out 

Rinse/Repeat

Pony Drill-  
-Subtly pull heel off the ground.  
-Shift weight to other foot.  Slight bounce as you go foot to foot.  
-for 10 secs then fall forward and continue for 10yds then jog it out

Rinse/Repeat

Foot tapping (one leg at a time)
-Pull foot up under hip into running pose and then fall back to ground. 
-fall forward and continue for 10yds then jog it 

Rinse/Repeat

Timber drill
-Maintain proper body alignment while falling forward 
-Falls as far as possible before reaching your leg out 
-Let’s you feel full acceleration 

Rinse/Repeat

Jump Rope (demo)
In place
Fall forward and run while jumping 

Go practice running

Try and practice some of the things we drilled on, see if it feels any different.  Practice, practice, practice

COT: Every year gyms across the country bulk up on parking spaces, equipment & budgets. But there’s a catch. It’s only for January, February & March. The truth is they’re expecting to make a lot of money the first three months of the year. But, they already know that it’s not going to extend past March. This is because the majority of people who make New Year’s Resolutions quit before March. These gyms are taking a gamble on us failing. And the sad part is…we let them win. The key to beating the odds is small, steady gains. Adding a day to your workout. Taking away some foods. Not saying “no bread or alcohol for the rest of my life & 3 workouts every day until I die”. This is an unrealistic goal & this is the reason the gym wins in March. This year, let’s set obtainable goals. Let’s share our goals with each other & let’s hold each other accountable to those goals. Let’s show these gyms & other companies that are banking on our March failure that they don’t know who they’re dealing with.

COT: With a new year just around the corner. I thought I would touch on the subject of Personal Renewal.  We often talk about resolutions this time of year but we all know those are mostly wishful thinking.   Personal Renewal is something that needs to be constant and ever evolving.  When people dont take time for themselves, they stop being productive.  The reality is, without care and attention things start to breakdown.  Our bodies, our minds and our relationships.  As we start the new year we should find time to regularly renew ourselves.   Renewal has 4 dimensions. 

Physical Renewal -  Get regular exercise, take time to rest and relax, eat a balanced diet, do other activities that revitalize and give the body energy. 

Mental Renewal - Consider activities such as reading, keeping a journal, take up a new hobby or maybe continue your education.  Anything that broadens and strengthens your mind.  Mark Twain once stated "The man who doesnt read good books has no advantage over a man that cant read at all" 

Emotional Renewal - Find time for social activities. Friends, Family or whatever it may be. Listen with empathy, value the differences in others, forgive yourself and others.  Forgiveness is a powerful tool for increasing emotional capacity. To forgive is to set a prisoner free and discover the prisoner was you. 

Spiritual Renewal - Your spritual capacity is a powerful source of motivation, focus and resilience.  You can build your capacity by connecting with nature, living with integrity, listening to uplifting and power music and engaging in prayer. 

Look at it this way gentlemen.  We all live in houses with these four rooms.  We must go into these rooms often, even if it is just to air them out. 
Big Thanks to Happy Camper for leading us in prayer.

Preface this is not my experience, but this guys message struck a chord with me as a father with a son and I thought I’d share with the PAX
——————————————————-
Young men need fathers.
.
They need guidance, love, support, discipline and praise from their father.
.
I didn’t grow up with my father around. I had multiple “fathers” in men that took me under their wing. Men I’ll never forget. Men who’d show up to take me to scouts. Men who invited me hunting with their own sons. These men made an impression on me that’ll be with me until my last breath.
.
Our sons need a father. They need discipline. They need to feel the sting of loss and the pain of course correction. Our young men need to appreciate tenderness and empathy, and not fear the connection of human touch. Our sons need to see their father in times of turmoil, peace, creativity and war. If they don’t see us men in every situation how will they learn? What example and guide will they have? What benchmark and foundation will they build on? If young men never see us holding their mothers hand, how will they learn? If young men never see us lift until we puke or tenderly hold a baby how will they learn? If young men never see dad vulnerable or afraid, how will they ever learn to be brave?
.
My role of father is sacred. It’s not a secondary thought or a box on my to do list. I AM A FATHER. I created humans and it’s my privilege and duty to guide these little humans on their journey. To firmly correct while lovingly teach. To hold them and to push them. To cry with them and to smile with them.
.
Our young men need fathers. Our young men need EXAMPLES. Our young men need connection to MEN they can look up to, emulate and aspire to. Our young men need hero’s, and that hero should be DAD.
.
If we fathers lose the battle at home, our children will lose the war outside the walls of our home. If we fathers fail to guide these souls and show them truth, rawness, humility and the possibility in life, we fail our sacred duty as men, and we ultimately fail life itself.
.
Nothing can compensate for failure in our homes.
.
Nothing can compensate for failing our young men.
.
Nothing can or will compensate for failing our sacred duty of FATHER.

TAPS (Thoughts and Prayers) -  Amen!

FNGs: None
COUNT: 8
WARMUP: two sets of motivators, abe vigodas, and learning to fly
THE THANG: The stations were on a straight line in the farthest eastern drive aisle of the parking and entrance.  The starting station was adjacent to the normal flag location approx in the middle of the line.
We did 5 curls and shoulder press and ran to the most southern station which was over in line with the building and did this (every time here):
5 burpees, 10 leg raises, 15 air squats and 20 merkins
then ran back.  We rifle carried our coupon to the next station to the north which was one parking island away about 50 feet.  There we did 10 reps of curls and  shoulder presses and ran back to the most southerly station.  Did the same 5,10,15,20 exercises and ran back and rifle carried to the next station to the north and did 15 of each and ran back to the southerly station did the exercises and ran back.  We rifle carried to the last island to the north and did 20 this time.  We switched the exercises to skull crushers and bent over rows the next time we came back and then did the pattern in reverse.  It finished up right at time for Mary.  PAX had about 1.5-1.75 miles of running total.  

MARY: Monkey Crunchers, Pickle Pushers, Big Boys, held plank for 30 seconds to 6am
ANNOUNCEMENTS:
COT: For my COT, I wanted to start with a quote, “The night is always darkest before the dawn.”  For me, my night lasted a very long time actually a good part of two decades.  But I made it through the night to see the sunrise.  I still continue to have my struggles and fight my Jesters on a regular basis but I can say that the sunrise is awesome and knowing that helps me get through the tough dark days as they arise now.
I thought about this while I was driving back from a Plan Commission meeting for one of my projects the other day.  In the past, my Jesters of self confidence, self doubt and anxiety would win out and I feared going to these meetings where you typically have to answer questions about your projects from the officers on the Plan Commission.  I would silently hope that no one asked me any questions.  But the new me, Foundation, is learning how to keep my Jesters at check and this meeting I looked forward to it and actually took the lead to field the questions when I could have left them for the others present to answer.  And our project was approved.  
I also have been weening myself off my anxiety meds that I have been taking for the last several years and have not taken any for a week now. I’m doing ok.  
Thank you to all of you who have supported me in my journey.  And for those of you that have struggles that you are facing, I am here for you.  I have experienced some of the crap that the night has to offer and can empathize with a lot.  You are never alone.
I challenge those that may be going through their dark part of the night.  Reach out to someone and talk about it.  Sometimes getting it off your chest can help out a lot.  It can be me, another F3 brother, an M, a family member, it doesn’t matter.  What does matter is that you keep pushing forward and know that the dawn will come.  I love you guys.
Aye?
Ended with prayer
