THE THANG: 
Thang 1 - Pearls on a string with a few stops with 20 merkins at each stop - about 0.5 mile
Thang 2 Ladders
Starting station 10 merkins, 10 air squats and 20 LBCs
Station 1 - 20 curls and 20 skull crushers
Station 2 - 20 grady corns, 20 alternating leg lunges
Station 3 - 20 Carolina Dry Docks, 20 leg raises
Station 4 - 20 grady corns, 10 bobby hurleys
Did the exercises at start and ran to station 1 and then back to start then to station 2 then back to start then to station 3 and back to start and then to station 4 and back to start.  Then worked way back down to 1 and then back to 4.
MARY:  Monkey Crunchers, Big Boys, Pickle Pushers
ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: For my COT, I wanted to talk about a skill that is important to any relationship – a friend, an M, your 2.0’s, it doesn’t matter.  Listening.  I continually make a conscious effort to keep working on this area.  It is so easy to not truly listen and you end up limiting the open communication and miss out.  Truly listening involves not thinking about something else or multitasking when someone is talking to you or thinking up your response and what you want to say.  Truly listening involves stopping what you were doing and facing that person.  Make eye contact.  Your body language is huge also.  That other person is giving you the gift of sharing something with you. It is an opportunity to become closer with that person.  
My first ex wife would be on her smartphone a lot and would continue to troll through social media or playing games on it while I would be talking to her.  This happened a lot.  She would not face me, or make any eye contact and just keep playing Candy Crush on her phone or searching Facebook.  It communicated that our conversation wasn’t important to her.  It hurt.
My challenge to you is to make a conscious effort today to truly listen.  When someone is trying to talk to you.  Stop what you mlight have been doing and face them and give them your full attention.  Let them finish even if you want to add something about how you have a story just like that or it reminded you of something.  Wait until they are done talking and then say what you want to.  You will have more meaningful communication and will grow closer to that person.
Aye?
End with prayer

Each PAX will be required to complete the following exercises OYO focusing on form.  When you complete the reps you complete a lap around the parking lot.  Everybody pushed hard so there was no waiting on the 6 extra work:
•	SSH - 93 years ago he was born on Jan 15th 1929
•	Merkins - 74 years ago he graduated from Morehouse college in 1948 at 19
•	LBC’s - 69 years ago married to Coretta Scott
•	Squats - 65 years ago delivered his 1st national address in 1957 as a prayer at the Lincoln Memorial
•	Chest Press - 62 years ago was first arrested participating at a sit in demonstration in Atlanta in 1960
•	Curls - 59 years ago he delivered the “I have a Dream speech” 1963

•	Count-A-Rama; Announcements; Name-A-Rama
•	Dr. King represented so many strong values & qualities, but I wanted to point to 2 that I think are most relevant for the men of F3.
o	Passion
	Dr. King was passionate about what he wanted.  Not only for himself, his children, but for you & I.  Despite being jailed almost 30 times & hundreds of death threats he continued to blaze the trail.  Remain passionate about not only your health/fitness goals but all the goals in your life. Never give up on what you want to achieve. There will be obstacles, but nothing can truly stop you.  LIVE IT!
o	Give Back
	What would you do if you were given $54,123?  Dr. King donated his Nobel Peace Prize money to support the civil rights movement.  Make a conscious effort to build someone up.  Volunteer your time, write an uplifting message to someone, or pay for a stranger’s lunch/coffee.  Doesn’t matter what you do really, just do a selfless act for someone.
o	The ultimate measure of a man is not where he stands in moments of comfort & convenience but where he stands at times of challenge & controversy – Dr. King
•	Prayer Requests
•	Dear heavenly father thank you for the opportunity to be out here in the gloom with these amazing men.  Thank you for putting men on this earth like Dr. King who inspire us to be better & serve you every day.  Hold those in our spoken prayers & those in our hearts in your hands.  In your sons name.  Amen!

Clear out the negative mental habits because it conflicts with who we have been created to be. 
Unfortunately, we explode based on what has been built up and our tone can be toxic.
This baton is now passed on and cannot be changed. Example : when my 2.0 was teenager he was giving my M a ear full and was not giving up. After hearing him my temper got the best of me, stood up and back him against the refrigerator and yelled at him that if he says one more word I was going to put him through the frig. He shut up went to his room. I went up to his room explained that I was not the best version that I was created to be and that was not the best way to explain the situation. 
This was the baton that was past onto my dad and now I past it on to my 2.0. The only thing I can do from that point on was to pass on positive baton. 

Before you speak remember:
God is Love
God Loves You (you are already complete)
God loves them(now speak)

When I wrote this I was fine but when I spoke about the incident I snuck up on me and it was emotional. It one thing to think about it or forget about it and it is like it never happened but when you actually say it out loud it becomes reality and hits home.
This why F3 is so important it give you a platform to speak from the heart . 

Prayer
Father God thank you for this opportunity to spend time ITG and to become the best version of ourselves. We ask you to continue to speak to our hearts and help separate speak in love and to pass on that baton to our Family and friends. We lift all our unspoken prayers and the continued Covid issues that spread throughout our community including all the emotional issues that surrounds it. Please keep us happy healthy and safe throughout our travels today, in Jesus name Amen

COT: Bone Spur
Our mission as an F3 nation is to plant, grow and serve small workout groups for men for the invigoration of male community leadership.
 
How do we break this down.  What is growth….A majority of the fastest growing organisms are microscopic and naked to the human eye.  Given time these organisms grown into a force that cannot be stopped.  They can grow into trees taller than skyscrapers.  They can grown onto mountains that touch the highest peaks on our planet.
 
Why is this?  They don’t give up, they adapt.  These organisms realize there is no ‘comfort zone’.  There is only acceleration or deceleration.  To be the conquistador or be conquered?!  
 
I find this mission statement to be vital in multiple ways.  We as F3 are a living a breathing organism, just as we are ourselves.  We have to make the decision to Accelerate or Decelerate…I know this is not knew to most of you but think of the power of mind set is crutual…As David Goggins noted, “callus your mind, just as you callus your hands.”  I take that as there is no comfort zone, get your body used to pushing itself and craving it.  We talk about enjoying the suck…what does that mean?!
 
That means taking the leap to do an EC run before a boot camp, continuing to do perfect form on exercises and push for one more rep each time…break through the bearer and again and again and again…That is the only way you will grow as an organism.  
 
Think about your most challenging situations in life as well as the proudest moments in your life…I bet one led into the other.  Whether it was the day you finally gathered the courage to ask your wife to marry you, the day you decided to take the plunge and leave a steady job for something better, or the day your children were born and you became a father.  The day you were asked to be a Godfather or Guardian for someone’s child, in case something drastic would happen to them.
 
But it doesn’t have to be as drastic as the examples previously noted for those who have not faced those situations.  It could be the day you volunteered to the local food pantry to better someone else’s live, the day you were watch dawg for your kids school, the day you decided to be a coach for a little league team.
 
Even for us in F3 it could be the day you said I am going to be a Q and lead a work out, the day you committed to a Black Diamond, the day you committed to being a site Q, an AO Q, or an LT member.
 
Men, keep accelerating!  I am challenging you, to keep being a beacon. That is what I see as invigorating male community leadership.  So callus your mind to growth and accepting the challenge to lead because this community, country and world are looking for it.  Look at what we have become as a group at crossroads since July 2020. More exciting news to come, so lets keep growing.

One of the readings from church last week was 1 Corinthians 12, which states: “For as the body is one, and hath many members, and all the members of that one body, being many, are one body: so also is Christ.” This is similar to one of Aesop’s Fables. You have heard many of these before; The Boy Who Cried Wolf, The Tortoise and the Hare, etc. The fable similar to 1 Corinthians 12 is titled The Belly and Other Members. The moral of that story is the belly had all the food and the rest of the body rebelled and refused to work to get more. They soon relented as the whole body started to starve.

This reminded me of the state of society today. There is so much divisiveness and disagreement across the board. Wouldn’t it be nice if everyone realized we are all parts of one body, and that we all need each other? The same correlation holds true for F3. Each of us are members of one body, and we need each other. The strengths, weaknesses, and unique characteristics of each PAX makes us what we are as Crossroads collectively. When one of us is in pain or in need, the other members rally and assist however we can. We are stronger together!

COT: For my COT today, I wanted to talk about the first quadrant which we talk about in Q source which is Getting right.  The 4 quadrants are get right, live right, lead right and leave right.  Getting right involves your physical fitness but also involves other things such as eating right and getting control of your jesters which are the things that keep us from accelerating.  
I have made great strides in getting right but the battle against your Jesters is ongoing.  My main Jesters are self-confidence and anxiety.  I have to remain diligent in my fight against them or them creep back in and overwhelm me.  This happened most recently and let the thoughts of I’m not good enough and I’m always going to be alone and what woman would want someone like me.   I found myself basically moping and becoming depressed.  The other day at Q-source, our discussion helped me to grab ahold of myself and take control of my Jesters.  I am becoming better at this and am having less relapses.  I know I have good and bad things about me and eventually when I am ready, I will date again and may or may not find someone that truly can appreciate me who has good and bad traits.  I rushed after my first divorce back in 2017 and dated immediately because I didn’t understand my jesters and couldn’t stand to be alone.  I allowed myself to be controlled and manipulated while my jesters were in command of me.   I didn’t have F3 and the friendships in my life that I do now.  
I continue to rediscover who I truly am and how to control my Jesters and not let them hinder my acceleration in my life.  The 2nd F is such a large part of helping me gain control of my life again.  My friendships that I have forged in the gloom have helped me to win my war against my jesters of self-confidence and anxiety/depression.  I try setting up various 2nd F events ranging from lunches to card nights because I see the importance of these friendships in our battles against our jesters. 
My challenge to you is to do at least one 2nd F type thing over the next few days.  It can be as simple as talking to a friend over coffee or grabbing a beer or grabbing lunch.  It you can’t think of someone then ask me.  There is no maintaining in our journey through life.  If you aren’t accelerating then you are decelerating.  
Aye?
F3 is not a religious organization but we will end in a prayer.  You’re welcome to join or take a minute to connect with your sky Q.  Are there an intentions we can acknowledge?

COT: 
Pi recently reminded me of a speech by Admiral William H. McRaven delivered as the commencement address to the graduates of The University of Texas on May 17, 2014. Here are a few excerpts:
“Every day during SEAL training you were challenged with multiple physical events — long runs, long swims, obstacle courses, hours of calisthenics — something designed to test your mettle. Every event had standards — times you had to meet. If you failed to meet those standards your name was posted on a list, and at the end of the day those on the list were invited to a “circus.” A circus was two hours of additional calisthenics designed to wear you down, to break your spirit, to force you to quit.
No one wanted a circus.
A circus meant that for that day you didn't measure up. A circus meant more fatigue — and more fatigue meant that the following day would be more difficult — and more circuses were likely. But at some time during SEAL training, everyone — everyone — made the circus list.
But an interesting thing happened to those who were constantly on the list. Over time those students — who did two hours of extra calisthenics — got stronger and stronger. The pain of the circuses built inner strength, built physical resiliency.
Life is filled with circuses. You will fail. You will likely fail often. It will be painful. It will be discouraging. At times it will test you to your very core.
But if you want to change the world, don't be afraid of the circuses.”

He goes on to conclude...

“Start each day with a task completed. Find someone to help you through life. Respect everyone.
Know that life is not fair and that you will fail often. But if take you take some risks, step up when the times are toughest, face down the bullies, lift up the downtrodden and never, ever give up — if you do these things, then the next generation and the generations that follow will live in a world far better than the one we have today.
And what started here will indeed have changed the world — for the better.”

We go to our own sort of “circus” each time we post at an F3 workout. These workouts make us better than before we started. Let’s keep pushing ourselves, and each other, to get better every day.

COT:

On 2/18/21 I learned just how much more than a workout group this F3 thing was. Men I had never met from F3 Naperville rushed to my side along with my brothers from Crossroads as i laid on the ground in shock my leg hanging by a thread. Men lifted me on the stretcher so my leg did not shift and cause any additional pain so the paramedics could wheel me off the field. Men showed up at my driveway post surgery for coffee each Friday this was the best part of my week. We would hang out in the cold for an hour and literally block the street where the school bus could barely get by. Numerous messages came  through slack or text to see how I was and if I needed anything. The generosity shown with the gift cards given to me was second to none. The constant encouragement as I started the complete mind fuck of learning how to walk again. The phrase fall down 7 times get up 8 had a real meaning as my ass fell and I fell a lot. However each day I got up and got back at it. Softhands who some of you have met told me it would be 6 months until I’d be back to any sort of level fitness wise where I was before the injury. Well from that point forward the challenge was accepted and I busted my ass. I took everything he threw at me and asked for more. Never once did I complain or say that this hurt. F3 taught me I could do hard shit and that was just what I was going to do. He couldn’t believe that I was posting before PT which basically turned into three double taps a week. Run club post, you bet I rode my bike there, chased the Pax and back home. Lead a Q with a soft cast on? Yup we bear crawled the whole time as a modification. Each day and each post the men of crossroads gave me the strength to keep pushing to get back to my old self. Weeks turned to months, 1-2 posts a week became 3, then 4, and soon back to 6 packs.  I ended PT 19 weeks after I started which was about a month sooner than expected. I am forever grateful to each one of you that helped me on this journey. Site Qs you heard my life story numerous times and yet you still walked, jogged and eventually ran my ass back to the group. I was never left behind, always included and pushed to go further each post then I did the post before. Crossroads saved me when I could have said fuck it and gave up. There were ample opportunities to quit and give up. Shit got hard and believe me sometimes I questioned if it was worth it. I am the man I am today because of Crossroads and I am proud to be part of this region. I love each and every one of you and I am forever grateful for everything that has been done for me. I have a quote on my road id bracelet that says nothing is impossible. After this past year I truly believe this. I can truly say I am better today then I was yesterday and I will be better tomorrow then I was today.

As some of you know, the other day I went out on a date.  The first one since the divorce and the first one in several years.  I am in a much different place than I have ever been and have a clarity of thinking as I never have had and also have self-confidence. Things Happen For A Reason!

Tomorrow will be my sons 5th birthday 02/22/22. The road bringing him into this world wasn’t easy by any means.  We had children later in life and we quickly found out that it’s not as simple as some would have you believe.  Multiple miscarriages, ectopic pregnancy’s, lots of emotional roller coasters, M’s OCD challenges, significant marital stress, it’s not been an easy road for sure.  There were so many challenges along the way trying to have both of our children.  With our son we had all of that in addition to being told we had a 1% chance of having another child.  We tried IVF once and that didn’t work out and it’s costly.  So we just gave in to the mantra of if it’s meant to be it will be.  About 1.5 yrs later and having come to grips that we may only have one child (which would’ve been totally fine) we were blessed with our son.  I don’t pretend to understand why the road was filled with all the struggles to have children but I do believe things  happened for a reason.  We may not always know why things happen to us or when things do happen they may not always make sense, but know that there is a bigger plan for us . COT: 
Talked about real life lesson I learned from my M on compassion and helping others...
A couple weeks ago my M and I went to Chicago for a weekend getaway. After we brought our stuff up to the room and began to settle in I noticed two brown paper gift bags on the table. We were in a nice hotel on Michigan Ave so I thought they were welcoming gifts from the hotel. Instead, inside each were a new pair of gloves and socks, a hat, and some snacks. Clearly, I had not paid attention earlier because my M had packed these bags at home and brought them with us to hand out to someone in need. One bag to one person for each day we were there. I was amazed at her forethought and despite my hesitancy, and possibly a little fear, that’s exactly what we did. I must admit, it was heartwarming seeing the very confused, yet I believe, appreciative look on the faces of the people we gave the bags to. It also reminded me of three important truths I believe we can all heed. First, it’s important to recognize and understand when others can use a helping hand. In many cases, the needs are obvious but in other cases, they are more discreet. Second, it’s important to open our hearts and feel a calling to help those in need, whether they’re our family, closest friends, or distant strangers. Third, it’s important that, once our eyes see, our minds recognize, and our hearts are open, we act in whatever way is in our means to make an impact in someone’s life. Admittedly, these truths have often been difficult for me. Looking beyond my little bubble and getting out of my comfort zone to approach and offer help to a complete stranger is not easy. Without her knowing it, my M showed me that weekend that I have plenty of room for improvement in this area. I’d ask all of you to continuously find ways to exercise these three truths and not let opportunities to do so slip by. Aye?

Finished with prayers for several people dealing with health issues and for peace in Ukraine.

Running Thang

20 Meter FitnessGram PACER Test (BlueGill style)

The multi-stage fitness test (MSFT), also known as the beep test, bleep test, PACER (Progressive Aerobic Cardiovascular Endurance Run), PACER test, FitnessGram PACER test, or the 20 m Shuttle Run Test (20 m SRT), is a running test used to estimate an athlete's aerobic capacity (VO₂ max). The test requires participants to run 20 meters back and forth across a marked track keeping time with beeps. Every minute or so, the next level commences: the time between beeps gets shorter; participants must run faster. If a participant fails to reach the relevant marker in time, they get a caution and another attempt. A second caution ends the test for that runner. 

When the PAX fails to complete an interval twice, run a parking lot lap then jump into the next PACER test interval.    When the PAX fails an interval, resume running a lap.  At some point during this THANG (when all PAX had failed) the PACER Test was set to start from the beginning and the PAX continued the PACER test.  Rinse and repeat. With about 15 minutes left, the PACER test portion of the workout was terminated and we moved into a Recovery Run.  Rally at flags at 0555

Let's talk about consistency.

Calluses are formed by doing the same activity or movement over and over. And that goes into fitness.

ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: For my COT today, I want to start with a quote “Courage is resistance to fear, mastery of fear, not absence of fear.”
I was reflecting the other day on why people don’t step up to Q more.  I thought to myself, is it because they are afraid?  Afraid of what other people will think?  Afraid of failure? Afraid of the unknown?  Yeah, I get that.  I was there at first.   But pushing ourselves outside of our comfort zones helps us to grow and become stronger physically, emotionally and mentally.  I remember my first Q.  It was a tabata and I f’d up the cadence during warm-o-rama and Mary.  We didn’t run because I fell and sprained my ankle a few days before at a bootcamp.  It was kind of a $hitshow.  I was this fat overweight guy, deaf, couldn’t run and didn’t say much.  I could have easily said no but I signed up to Q again a few weeks later.  I went from posting 1 time a week to 2 then to 3 and Q’ing every 2-3 weeks.    After a few months, up to Qing once a week and posting 4 days a week.  Up to the last 6 months of posting 5-7 times a week and Q-ing twice a week.  Tell you what though, I still get some butterflies sometimes.  The fear never goes away, I’ve learned how to control it and master it.  This is in all aspects of our lives.  Not just in our fitness or leading a workout but in any area of our life where our fears hold us back.  My acceleration over the past year and a half has encompassed my whole life.  I’ve taken control of my personal life.  Fears of being alone, fear related to self-doubt, fear of acceptance for who I f_cking am and fear to stand up for myself.  I’ve spilled this mindset into my professional life.  Stop being afraid of the chance of not succeeding at a type of project that I haven’t worked on before, stop being scared to take out potential clients and meeting new ones, stop being afraid to take on more responsibility because I have never had that level of responsibility.  I’ve said hell yeah and stopped saying no or I can’t.  Now I say “Yes and” and welcome a challenge.  These areas of my life are accelerating.  I’m not held back by my fears.  I’m learning how to master the fears.
My challenge to you all today is to reflect on what fears do you have in the various areas of your life.  Is it a poor relationship with your M and you’ve been afraid to try and work it out with her?  Is it at work and you are afraid to try to take on more responsibility or try something different?  Is it out here and you might have only Q’d once or twice?  That last one is fairly easy to work on.  Just sign up.  Just do it and reach out for help if you need it.  There are some great f’ing guys out here.   We are stronger together.  We have each others backs.  I know from experience.  Hell, there are several of my Crossroads brothers out here that have helped me during my rough times more than they know.  Life is short.  Don’t wait – the ability to make change is inside you.  You are stronger than you can imagine.
Aye?
F3 is not a religious organization but we will end in a prayer.  You’re welcome to join or take a minute to connect with your sky Q.  Are there an intentions we can acknowledge?

Background: Dedicated to U.S. Sgt. Zachary D. Tellier, 31, of Charlotte, NC (USA) a combat infantryman with the 4th Squadron, 73rd Cavalry Regiment, 4th Brigade Combat Team, at Fort Bragg. He died Sept. 29, 2007, of wounds sustained while on a ground patrol in Afghanistan.

The previous April, Tellier’s unit was conducting a mounted patrol when one of its vehicles drove over and detonated a bomb, which set the vehicle on fire, according to a statement from the 82nd Airborne.

Tellier pulled two paratroopers out of the vehicle to safety, suffering severe burns to his hands. He was awarded the Bronze Star Medal with valor for his actions.

After he was burned, Tellier jumped up in the turret to return fire, said Sgt. Michael Layton, a member of Tellier’s unit. A lieutenant made Tellier get out of the vehicle because of his injuries, Layton said.

“Zachary Tellier has to be the biggest hero I’ve ever known or heard of, not just because of what he did, but because of his personality,” Layton said. “He came in the Army because he wanted to be around soldiers and serve his country, and he paid the ultimate sacrifice.”

Today I wanted to find balance.  To get faster, run with faster people.  Once you get fast are you trying to pay that forward.  Are you the faster guy now who has slower pax with you?  I found myself thinking selfish while helping someone from my shieldlock who wanted to accomplish his goal of a 10k.  We accomplished the 10k last Thursday with an EC and RC.  I was excited to see how my training has gotten me better at running.  The 9:30 pace was easy.  It got me thinking of how to pace for a half marathon.  I than thought my normal strava paces are low 8’s.  I wanted to speed up, push my time some more, than I took a step back to realize I was here this morning to support a pax by being the faster guy to help him accomplish a goal.  Its ok to not always have the faster time because it had a bigger purpose, to lead another PAX.  If you are the fast guy, help a slower PAX.  A slower PAX, once you get faster pay it forward.

it derives from the Latin language as restraint and moderation.  I think this word has a ton of significance right now in our society in that it doesn't feel like people of showing the correct level of temperance when dealing with others that differ with their personal views.
I'll share a story.  A man was travelling down a highway in his car when the semi-truck ahead of him loses a tire.  The man did his best to avoid it but he was unable.  The tire hit the windshield head on and it shattered.  The man was able to control the car though and safely park the car on the shoulder of the highway.  Once he was settled he picked up his cell phone and called his wife.  He told her about the tire and the broken windshield.  His wife was immediately concerned that he was badly cut from the glass.  He reassured her that he was fine because the glass was tempered.  When it broke it failed as designed into many small pieces instead of larger jagged pieces.  Tempered glass is glass that has been heat-treated to make it harder, break safely, and limit the potential injury.   Similar to tempered glass, if we as people employ temperance we are much less likely to inflict pain when we break.  Aye!

I shared a recent post made on the F3 Nation’s Slack Channel that is very applicable to the F3 brothers here at F3 Plainfield.  Enjoy!

In some places in the west, storms can be seen from miles and miles away. Cows and other animals see the storm, panic, and run in the opposite direction. Of course, the storm eventually catches up with them and they spend more time, not only worried about the impending storm, but more time in the storm/chaos/unpleasantness as it passes over them.

“What buffalo do on the other hand is very unique for the animal kingdom. Buffalo wait for the storm to cross right over the crest of the peak of the mountaintop and as the storm rolls over the ridge the buffalo turns and charges directly into the storm. By confronting the storm, buffaloes actually spend less time in the storm. They experience the same storm as the animals that run the opposite direction, but they get on the other side faster. 

This is what we do at F3 Plainfield.  Every morning we may confront injuries, less than ideal weather, and sometimes every legitimate personal excuse to avoid running. And yet we show up, run, and push ourselves to get faster, stronger, and better on the trail and road and in our lives. Great job today!  I hope you enjoyed your run.  Go be a buffalo!

Repeat Cot from early in the week regarding having the opportunity to watch my daughter compete in weekend long VB tournament. It was awesome seeing her become competitive, and trying her best. I seen her fail, succeed, laugh and cry. The only thing I could do I listen and be there for her. I also mentioned that as much as we as parents want our kids to win it is ok for her to lose. Another topic we mentioned is not to show disappointment and let our 2.0’s know that we are proud of there efforts. All we need to do is to ask them 2-3 things they were proud of and 1-2 things they could improve on so they come to there own conclusions. 
We are not a religious organization but we are faith based and believe in something greater than ourselves. We Ask for to comfort them during this time and to let them know you are close and they can turn to you while they try to manage life. We also lift up all our unspoken prayer and lay them at your feet. 
          We don’t know why things happen  they way they do but we do know that you are there in our triumphs and there to comfort us in our sorrows. With that being said :
Lord I thank you for today

Your peace is overwhelming in the moments
Your comfort in the hurting moments
Your strength in the weak moments
Your joy in the sweet moments
Please be with me as I sleep
Please renew my mind refresh my soul & Strengthen my heart for a new day ahead
You are my God and I love you you so very much. In Jesus name Amen

COT:

3AM Thoughts

I was woken up this morning around 3 am and couldn’t sleep. Usually this would get me really irritated and I would try to lay in bed for a while. But I realized that maybe this was God trying to get my attention. Today I felt that I should just get up. I decided to do something that I haven’t done in quite a while, write. I thought that I had something to discuss for my COT and then I decided to scrap that idea because something else was festering in my brain. I was thinking of an old audio recording (and by audio recording, I really mean a file that I downloaded on Amazon Music), that I have listened to a lot in the past, but haven’t thought about much lately. It is the idea about the power of our thoughts. The name of the recording is called The Strangest Secret and the author is Earl Nightingale. It was recorded back in 1956 and it is all about the power of our mindset and the fact that “we become what we think about.” I have always been fascinated about the power of our minds and what the right mindset can do for our lives. It is no wonder and no surprise that top athletes, business execs, and those who have found a great amount of success in their lives will at some point attribute their success to having the right mindset.

This time of year, springtime, seems to be a good time to talk about the power of our thoughts. See, if we think of our thoughts as seeds, and our minds as the soil, we can see the link between what we think and the “fruit” that is produced. Just like the ground, our minds do not care what we plant. You can plant a thorn bush, something poisonous, flowers, or even a massive tree. As long as the soil is fertile, the seed will grow. And oh, how fertile is the soil of the mind. The soil doesn’t care what is planted. Just like our minds, the thoughts we continue to harbor will grow, fester, and quickly take over. How many times have you felt like your mind was being over come by weeds? Thoughts of envy, lust, greed, and fear. If you’re like me, it seems that those weeds are always there. The dandelions of the mind. Their roots are deep and their seeds seem to spread with very little effort, and worst of all, they seem to just appear in abundance overnight.

But what if we, as the gardeners of our own lives, decided to put forth the effort of cultivating the soil of our minds? What if we intentionally, daily, choose what we planted? I find it no coincidence that in the book of Philippians, Paul tells us that “whatever is true, noble, right, pure, lovely, admirable, excellent, and praiseworthy….too THINK about these things. Also, the “fruits” of the Spirit. 9 qualities that I know I would love to cultivate into my life each and every day. Love, Joy, Peace, Patience, Kindness, Goodness, Faithfulness, Gentleness, and Self-Control.

finished with pickle pushers
ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: I want to start today’s COT with this quote, “Hope is being able to see that there is light despite all of the darkness.”
Life has its’ ups and downs.  At Q-source we talk about preparedness as a tool for helping make it through these ups and downs without straying too much from our course through life.  I strive in my preparedness on a daily basis.  I know first hand the effects on me when you aren’t right in your F’s aimlessly navigating each day as one of the saddest sad clowns ever.
I lost that idea of hope for years.  My marriage was a wreck, I had no self confidence in anything that I did which also in turn affected by professional life and career.  My anxiety was so high that it affected my decision making and my physical well being.  I was miserable and actually believed that there wasn’t anything I could do to change it and I felt extremely sorry for myself.
At one point in 2015, I decided to try to pull myself out of the spiral of hopelessness and started seeing a counselor to talk about my relationship problems with my first wife.  I explored so many areas of myself and finally begun to hope again for a better life.  It took 6 years to finally get myself right in my first and second F’s and am working on the third F still.  In the process of trying to work it out with the relationship troubles to my 2nd wife, I finally dealt with and worked through the deepseeded issues from my first marriage relationship.  The final catalyist for me was my involvement in F3 and my preparedness in my life.  
I now look at life differently.  Nothing is hopeless.  Bad things happen and bad situations will pass.  There are always solutions.  If I had not embraced and worked towards my preparedness, I honestly don’t think I would be alive today.  I would have succumbed to the darkness and ended it.
Hope is all around us in everything we do or come across.  I embrace it now and it gets me through the downs that I come across.
My challenge to you is to reflect on a down area of your life.   What can you do differently in your approach or mindset?  There is always a solution or a workable path.  This is the beauty behind preparedness.  You are more capable than you even know and can overcome any obstacle.  Now, take a step towards overcoming this down area in your life.  Say a little prayer.  Meditate.  Whatever you do.  Just never give up hope. Aye?
F3 is not a religious organization but we will end in a prayer.  You’re welcome to join or take a minute to connect with your sky Q.  Are there an intentions we can acknowledge?

I showed up to the AO 3 min early (that’s more like it) coming in hot from double tapping. Flags were moved North of the Wood in a school parking lot due to the festival that was going on. 

WoR: 

Good Mornings IC :10
Imperial Walkers IC: 10
Daisy Pickers: C/R/C/L/C

Thang 1: Ruck

We Rucked North across Route 52 and around the pond at the Shorewood Village Hall. Then head back to the Wood. 3.1 miles rucked and a whole lot of Mumblechatter. 

CoT:
I used the same CS Lewis quote as I did at my earlier Q because I felt that it resonated with this week perfectly. 

Imagine yourself as a living house. God comes in to rebuild that house. At first, perhaps, you can understand what He is doing. He is getting the drains right and stopping the leaks in the roof and so on; you knew that those jobs needed doing and so you are not surprised. But presently He starts knocking the house about in a way that hurts abominably and does not seem to make any sense. What on earth is He up to? The explanation is that He is building quite a different house from the one you thought of - throwing out a new wing here, putting on an extra floor there, running up towers, making courtyards. You thought you were being made into a decent little cottage: but He is building a palace. He intends to come and live in it Himself. 
-C. S. Lewis-

Crying, whining, moaning all day long. It hit a boiling point at dinner and continued through her bath. When I tucked her in for bed she had finally calmed down and we chatted about the day. She said she was frustrated all day, but now she realizes that it was unnecessary for her to be so upset. Then she said, “Dad, why don’t you ever get upset?” I was incredibly thankful for this for two reasons. First, it tells me that even though I might be boiling mad inside, I am doing a good job of keeping it together in front of my kids. Second, it shows that she is paying attention to my actions, and that I am modeling positive behavior for her. Our actions have effects, sometimes even greater effects than we can imagine because people are always watching—especially our children!

CoT:
For the COT today, I wanted to talk about patience.  I have had to remind myself about this area lately.  Here’s a story I heard recently and liked
Once there was a great king, who was traveling alone in a forest. Soon, he lost his way and was looking around from a hilltop but could not see any people or villages nearby.
It was becoming dark. After some time, he saw some kind of light at a long distance. He started walking in that direction and soon reached a hut.

Outside the hut, there was an old woman who was cleaning the place. After seeing the king, she welcomed him thinking that he was a soldier from King’s army.

She gave the king some water to clean himself and some water to drink. She then spread a mat for him to relax. King started relaxing.

After some time, she bought a plate of hot rice and carry and placed it before him. The king was so hungry that he quickly put his fingers on the hot food. The hot food burnt his” fingers and he spilled some rice on the floor during the process.

The old woman saw this and Said, “Oh, you seem too impatient and hasty like your king, that’s why you have burnt your fingers and lost some food”.

Hearing the old woman’s words, the king was surprised and asked her “why do you think our king is impatient and hasty?.”

The old woman smiled and begin to explain to him. “My dear son, our king is having a big dream of capturing all his enemy forts. During the process, he is ignoring all the small forts of his enemy and trying to capture only the big forts.”

The king interrupted the old woman and Said “That’s the good thing right. What’s the problem with that?”.

She smiled and replied, “Wait, my son. Like your impatience in eating the food, you burned your fingers and wasted some food, In the same way, the king’s impatience to defeat the enemies quickly, causing him the loss of men in his army as well as a worry to him.

So, instead, if you would have eaten the food at the edge of the plate which was cooler, and then at the center, You would not have burnt your fingers as well as not wasted your food.

Similarly, the king should target the small forts and strengthen his position. This will help him to capture the bigger forts without loss of men from his army”.

Hearing this, the king understood his mistake and realized that one should have patience and avoid making any haste in any situation.

Moral of the story:
When you want to achieve something in life, first understood the process of What it takes to achieve it and work on it. Instead, if you are looking for quick results you will become impatient and never achieve what you want in your life.
For example: If you want to lose 10 lbs in one week, that’s not going to happen. Instead, focus on 1lb in 1 to 2 weeks and 10 lbs in 2 or 3  months. So, in the long run, with patience, you will achieve what you wanted in your life.

My challenge for you today reflect on one area of your life where you might not have been as patient as you could be.  Think on how you will work on that.  Maybe setting smaller goals or checkpoints along the way to keep you motivated.
Aye?
Ended with prayer

For the COT today, I wanted to start with a quote
“If you are not where you want to be DO NOT QUIT, instead reinvent yourself and change your habits.”
I love this quote!  This is me and my life.  My journey over the past year has been an experience.  I have found myself reflecting on it over the past month or two a lot.  Simply put, I came out that first day because I was not where I wanted to be.  I wanted more out of life and could feel that parts of my life were “off”.  The past year has been hard in multiple areas.  First, from just getting back into shape and secondly, in my personal life.  Both areas were very hard but I did not quit and I chose to reinvent myself and change my habits.  Physically, I’m up to routine 6 PAX with EC runs and down 25 lbs.  Mentally, I have slowly been getting my self-confidence back which has led to my reinventing myself in my personal and work lives.  I can envision the man I want to be, the Dad to my girls, the senior manager at work, the friend, the sibling, and son.  I am changing my habits and following the path that I now have the self-confidence to realize that I can do it no matter how hard it will be and I will follow the path that I know is right to be the man that I want to be.  
My challenge to you is to think on one area of your life that you want to improve and set a goal.  Now, work toward achieving that goal.  Remember, you can and will do it if you simply DO NOT GIVE UP or QUIT.

Physical health
Stature
Eating healthy
Exercising
Our body, with all its chemical, parts, and systems, functioning properly together
Emotional health
Out mental well being
Learning to cope with the full spectrum of human emotions
Relationship health

Spiritual health

Requirements: Football field (sideline to sideline) or some other large area with two parallel lines measured out 160 feet apart. 1 Coupon (Cinder Block) per PAX.

_Round 1: Burpees & Sprinting_

Do 8 Burpees on the sideline, sprint to the far sideline and do 8 more. Continue until the 11th set of 8 Burpees are complete (88 total)

_Round 2: Squrls & Coupon Carries_

Do 8 Squrls on the sideline, coupon carry to the far sideline and do 8 more. Continue until the 11th set of 8 Squrls are complete (88 total)
Squrl = Squat while curling coupon up to chest.

_Round 3: Overhead Presses & Rifle Carries_

Do 88 Overhead Presses on the sideline, rifle carry to the far sideline, do 88 more (176 total). Rifle carries may be done holding the coupon horizontally or vertically, but the arms alone are holding it up. Rx = No resting it on your head.

_Round 4: X-Factors, Bear Crawl & Crawl Bear_

Do 88 X-Factors on the sideline, Bear Crawl to the far sideline. Do 88 more, then Crawl Bear back to the sideline (176 total) – PAX must cross the field once by Bear Crawling and once by Crawl Bearing. It is PAX choice which one they do first.
X-Factor = on your six, begin each rep by spreading your body out into an X, with the backs of your hands and your heels all touching the ground. Then with straight arms and your elbows locked, pick one hand reach up & touch your opposite foot (1 touch = 1 rep). Then alternate to your other hand and foot for the next rep. Repeat as needed.

Yesterday at 10:40am, 1040EZ reached out to me and asked if I could grab the Q at TW. I said Hell Yes! This gave an opportunity to practice a Thang I plan on using next Tuesday for BDQ.

Thank you for joining me this morning men. We don’t wake up for easy. Getting up ITG sucks, working out in the wet slushy snow sucks and 39° Sucks! Embrace The Suck.
“Embrace The Suck” military speak for “The Situation Is Bad, But Deal With It”
It’s a very Buddhist concept. When we deny what reality is giving us, what is really happening, then we create suffering. So life is a dance between minimizing expectations and surrendering to what our lives actually reveal to us.
By embracing our lives totally (even the stuff that “sucks”), we get through them.
The Armed Forces have no other choice. If they’re out in the Iraqi desert or in the mountains of Afghanistan, the only way they’re going to get through those challenging experiences is by embracing (rather than denying or ignoring) them.
But for us with our modern conveniences and propensity for denial, we can distract ourselves, numb ourselves, fool ourselves over and over to avoid, disconnect, ignore, postpone, procrastinate and put our heads in the sand when we don’t want to look at what is.

COT:
Told a story that occurred last week at the plant were I'm currently traveling to.  I identified a safety issue and communicated that we needed to find a solution before we could continue to do that activity.  The people there are great and quickly went to work to brainstorm different ideas.  A meeting was held the following morning to discuss options and align on a path forward.  The meeting was very productive and we all felt good leaving.  The next day I visited the affected area and talked with the Operations Technician working that job. The person brought up several concerns with the solutions we had implemented in the short term and the longer term solutions we were working on.  I let them vent for 5-10 minutes and then the real rub came out.  They told me " you know one of us should have been invited to the meeting yesterday."  It ended up that the frustration was less about the changes and more about not having a voice in the outcome.  I apologized to the Technician that they were not included.  I took responsibility for that as I knew better.  Once I said that, you could see the person visibly calm down.

My message is to always think about the stakeholders who are closest to the decisions that are made and make sure they have a seat at the table.  Not only will you likely get better ideas and results, the buy-in and ownership will be much improved.  This is a lesson that many of us know but unfortunately when we are trying to come to a quick solution it can be easily forgotten.  AYE!

When” The Goose” makes it to Station 9, he shouts “Goose” and “The Ducks” run to the other side of the parking lot, performs 10 Merkins, run back towards the pavilion to the second cone and performs 10 Mountain Climbers, and then returns to the next station, in a clockwise fashion.  “The Goose” from the last round goes to Station 1 and becomes a “Duck”.  “The Duck” at Station 9 becomes the new “Goose” and goes to the middle.  Hold squat until the 6 is back at their new station. The new “Goose” then gives a 10 count and then the next round begins.  Rinse & repeat.

COT  - Ball of Men

Are you being Vulnerable? If Not, Why Not?

Vulnerable meaning capable of being physically or emotionally wounded.   Open to attack or damage.   A state of emotional exposure that comes with a certain degree of uncertainty. It involves a person's willingness to accept the emotional risk that comes from being open and willing to love and be loved.  

Being vulnerable means there’s  a risk of you feeling some sort of pain.  As humans we are built to avoid pain.  This is not abnormal, it’s part of our DNA, it’s how we were made.

Being vulnerable means there’s a chance people will find out who we really are.  You know as men, we are not very good at being vulnerable.  I can certainly attest to that in my own life. I tend to hold things in.  I try and portray that I’m  strong and that very little bothers me. I tend to not want to burden others with my issues.  I believe I can deal with things internally.  I stray away from the touchy/feely things.  You know what is so ironic  and crazy about all this…most of you likely do some of the same things as me.  Why? because it’s how we are all built.  

All too often FEAR keeps us from being vulnerable.  FEAR of pain, FEAR of uncertainty, FEAR of the unknown, FEAR of what people will think of us, FEAR of being raw and letting people see who we really are.

Doing good deeds may also help encourage others to repeat the good deeds that they’ve experienced themselves in turn paying it forward and it all contributes to a more positive world.
My challenge to you is to do at least one act of kindness towards someone today. COT:
Men, for those of you who don't  know, I have 5 kids. I have three in college. My twins are 21 and a 19 year old and a 17 year old who is a senior in high school. I also have a 12 year old daughter. While I was preparing for this workout last night, my son, Evan, who is the senior in H.S. came home around 9:30- 10pm. He had just returned from the memorial service for his friend John Anthony (I'm holding the program from the service). This breaks my heart. We need to do something! We're heading into the holiday season which is a tough time for those struggling with depression and mental illness. We need to step up and talk more to the ones we love. This is the 5th young man I've heard of that took his life in the last few weeks. A couple boys from Oswego East HS, Minooka HS, Providence Catholic HS, Nequa Valley HS. How can we stop this? I reached out to all my boys, one on one and had talks with them. It's not easy. Nobody wants to talk about the important things and tough things like suicide. I, myself, get choked up and don't get what's in my mind into spoken words. I need to do better. We need to do better. We're getting right or have gotten right. We're living right. We need now, more than ever, to lead right. We need to step it up....NOW! I need to step it up....NOW! We need to have those tough conversations. (Holding the memorial program) I can't hug this piece of paper. I want to hug my boys!!! Let's get this right, let's step it up... today! AYE! Right

Run the length of the parking lot and back after each set of 25.  3rd man carries the wooden post from first lot to the second lot handing it of when he gets there. 

MARY:  Burpee ring of fire (1),  LBC's (50), flutter kicks (25)
ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT:  Every morning we end with the Circle of Trust.  My question to you is. What does that Cirlce of Trust mean to you and what can be gained or learned from the Circle of Trust? Often times its hard for men to express their feelings or thoughts. The CoT can be an open forum to express these feelings or thoughts without ridicule or judgement.  I personally feel there is a lot to be gained from the CoT regardless of wether you are Qing or just posting. There are opportunities to teach, learn and express yourself.  Here are a few things that I have gained or learned from the CoT. 

Authenticity- When we show up in the gloom we are whole and we are ourselves. Those who we work with are more willing to trust us in relationships and as leaders when we are whole. This contributes to the transformation of being the best versions of ourselves.  Be Honest, Be yourself. 

Diversity-- Diversity is a deeply valued source of strength and wisdom for us and the communities in which we live.  The capacity to welcome space for diverse voices and multiple perspectives is critical to any Circle of Trust. 

Community-- The Circle of Trust offers us an opportunity to become more aware of the connectedness we have with our families, friends and communities. The result is an ongoing sense of responsibility and stewardship of the people and concerns that matter most. 

Courage and Love-- It take courage to try and make a difference and often times thats done under overwhelming circumstances. Extending ourselves for another persons growth requires courage but also a tremendous amount of love. Our work within our family, friends and community allows us to understand, respect and support each other.  Love and courage are two of the most demanding disciplines to learn.  Learn them!!

Hope--I often times find lots of hope in the CoT.  I see and hear persistence when the odds are stacked against us. In the midst of so much despair and brokenheartedness in the world today, I see many of you living purposeful lives, doing meaningful work and contributing to succeeding generations. 

Renewal-- We as men experience all the natural cycles of engagement and withdrawal, love and loss, creativity and despair. We experience this in our personal lives and in the workplace. If we take the time to slow down, quiet ourselves and renew our commitments, then as leaders we can contribute to the renewal of our families, friends and communities. 

Big Thanks to @HappyCamper for leading us in prayer

Do 2 merkins and 2 WWI situps and then bear crawl to the next light, add 2 to each exercise so 4 merkins and 4 WWI, then lunge walk to the next, add 2 again and then bear crawl to the next station, then add 2 to each exercise then lunge walk to the far side and add 2 to each exercise.  Then run back to the beginning and add 2 to each exercise then bear crawl and so forth.  Always alternate bear crawl and lunge walk.
Thang 2 
Station 1 at Pavilion and Station 2 on far end of parking lot
Split into two groups – first group starts at pavilion and second group starts running to far end
Pavilion – 25 curls and 25 shoulder presses 1st time there
2nd time – 25 dips and 25 bent over rows
Station on far side of lot – always do 20 air squats, 10 leg raises and 50 jump rope
Rinse and Repeat OYO

MARY:  Big Boys 20, Pickle Pushers 21, Merkin 3 Ring of Fire

This reindeer games I look back on the conversations with Toby, Pull Up, Tobbogan, Mr. Belding, Cyclone, Jellystone and Bunker to name a few people and I enjoyed getting out in the gloom to accelerate my fitness with you guys as well as to get to know you a little more.  
My challenge to you is to keep the fire burning.  Keep doing the EC runs and rucks.  Do second F events together.  Let’s keep this growing.   Aye?

COT: CoT
What is Forgiveness ?  
1. It is not forgetting
   It is not a Forgive and forget
2. Is not reconciling
    Reconciliation is not forgiveness 
3. Is not condoning the behavior 
     They no longer owe you anything for           the pain/hurt they have 
4. Is not a feeling
     Forgiveness is a choice
5. Is not just about the person who hurt you
It more about you, than them they may never think they owe you but the longer you hang on to to it the more negative affect it will have on you.

A Good Exercise 
Think of it this way take a deep breath and hold it, how does it feel at 30, 40, 50 or 60 seconds? How is it affecting your thoughts? Taking your next breath is the only thing that consumes you Now exhale,  how do you feel now? Relieved?  Relaxed? Worry free? This is what forgiveness is like, no longer weighting you down, consuming your thoughts. 

At its most basic level forgiveness is the decision to pardon an offense and give up the right to be repaid.

COT:
Talked about my wife's weekend.  She is a musician and started playing the guitar again about 5 years ago.  She has always played the piano.  In the last couple of years, she started writing, playing, and producing her own songs.  Last April she accomplished a life goal but releasing her first EP.  The next leap for her was to perform live.  This past weekend she got an opportunity to perform with about another 25 musicians.  They ended up performing 45 songs over the course of the night and Erika played on about a dozen or so.  Here is her post from Facebook the following day:

Ever since I was a little kid sitting in front of MTV, I’ve been watching other people do this. Last night, I finally got my chance, and it was the best time ever. I had my fair share of screw-ups, but the more I looked around and noticed how much fun everyone was having, I realized that part only mattered to me. It matters less today, though, as I’m looking through everyone’s photos, videos, and really kind comments.

I’ve learned so much from everyone in this group. But I especially want to thank <https://www.facebook.com/mdermont?__cft__[0]=AZUWwt-NWrl6wYINrIGrClSSmm9Ti6NJIn1-SoY4oEZK2_e_DfRKikA00uC0nuDOaf7Zy_Dn7lrGwQlGElT9NDCzLuyuuRpK3ZZcN3WKhtzN6VO4R5hrbNKU6D06AG6p4qDxxNHdQ-HR9lW_Dyb9JdU7&__tn__=-]K-R|Mike Dermont> for putting it all together, and <https://www.facebook.com/liyabug1?__cft__[0]=AZUWwt-NWrl6wYINrIGrClSSmm9Ti6NJIn1-SoY4oEZK2_e_DfRKikA00uC0nuDOaf7Zy_Dn7lrGwQlGElT9NDCzLuyuuRpK3ZZcN3WKhtzN6VO4R5hrbNKU6D06AG6p4qDxxNHdQ-HR9lW_Dyb9JdU7&__tn__=-]K-R|Tamara Woodruff> and <https://www.facebook.com/dschoenbeck?__cft__[0]=AZUWwt-NWrl6wYINrIGrClSSmm9Ti6NJIn1-SoY4oEZK2_e_DfRKikA00uC0nuDOaf7Zy_Dn7lrGwQlGElT9NDCzLuyuuRpK3ZZcN3WKhtzN6VO4R5hrbNKU6D06AG6p4qDxxNHdQ-HR9lW_Dyb9JdU7&__tn__=-]K-R|Doug Schoenbeck> for your help and leadership in making this show a huge success, and being such great examples for me to follow.

This show has had a tremendous response, and I hope we’ll do it again someday. Thank you so much to all of our musicians and supporters who braved the elements last night and helped us make a difference by raising funds for <https://www.facebook.com/michaeljfoxfoundation/?__cft__[0]=AZUWwt-NWrl6wYINrIGrClSSmm9Ti6NJIn1-SoY4oEZK2_e_DfRKikA00uC0nuDOaf7Zy_Dn7lrGwQlGElT9NDCzLuyuuRpK3ZZcN3WKhtzN6VO4R5hrbNKU6D06AG6p4qDxxNHdQ-HR9lW_Dyb9JdU7&__tn__=kK-R|The Michael J. Fox Foundation for Parkinson's Research>. It was great seeing so many friends, and making new ones. You made our show the place to be, and for that, we can’t thank you enough.

Bringing this back to F3, I think there are lots of similar elements.  Through this group Erika was given a great opportunity to stretch herself and was given great mentorship from several seasoned musicians.  In addition, the event ended up raising well over $3000 for charity.  These are the types of opportunities that we provide for each other in F3.  I am grateful to be part of this group in the same way Erika was grateful to be part of her group.

COT:

Thank you all that came out!

Before anything great is really achieved your comfort zone must be disturbed.

If it doesn't challenge you it doesn't change you.

Great people do things before they're ready.

Step so far outside your comfort zone that you forget how to get back.

Embrace the suck and do hard things everyday.

We've had a lot of cold days the last couple weeks I have to tell you I didn't hesitate and was kind of excited about getting out for <@U02KRH34RCK>'s Ruck VQ. It's never too cold, rainy etc. My reasons for not getting out are gone, I look forward to it.!

What I'm trying to say is you can talk yourself into something or you can talk yourself out of something, do what's hard.

There is a book, one word that will change your life.

It's about choosing one word that will impact the six dimensions of your life, mental physical emotional relational spiritual and financial.

The concept is beautiful.

You don't have to have resolutions you don't have to set goals you only need to apply that one word to everything you do, sounds simple.

I've been thinking about one word that might help me accelerate or improve in all those areas. The first word that came to my mind was dig, as in dig deeper in every one of those areas.

I would encourage you to think about one word that you could use anytime, any place, for anything that might help you become a better version of yourself, aye?

Let’s meet Rich “Binford” Berti

Married with two kids, Binford found out about F3 via social media despite not being much of a social media guy.  About a year and a half ago, Rich said he saw the post (Credit and EH to Pi) about some dudes working out, Rich said to himself that looks like some hard crap, showed up for a beatdown on 8/19/2020 and he’s never looked back.  This HIM is closing in on 300 posts, makes some killer coffee, and loves this thing called F3.  Good to reacquaint ourselves and we’re stoked to have you out in the gloom with us!  

Food for thought - Most of us don't set out looking to fail at anything. And we especially don’t want to be labeled as a failure. But maybe that is a mistake.
Failure can be useful. We can learn from it, gain new insights, and do better next time. The right kind of failures give us new information and teach us something that gets us closer to our goals.
Some live by the motto: If you aren't failing you aren't taking big enough risks. Said another way, if everything you try turns out exactly as planned and feels very comfortable, you probably aren't stretching yourself. And if you aren't stretching, you aren't growing!

COT: For my COT today, I want to start with a quote “Do not judge only based on one thing.  Every coin has two sides.”  Reflection on my personal life after the latest mediation the other week, I remembered how a lot of people believed the lies that were spread about me during my first divorce.  I remember playdates that I set up for my kids being canceled numerous times or they would ask if my daughters could just come to their house instead.  False stories that ranged from drunken abuse to my being insane.  My reflection made me remember the pain that was caused by so called friends judging bases on one side of the story.  I heard another very similar situation to what I went through those 6 years ago.  Sometimes a divorce can bring out the worst in a person and they might not be entirely truthful when talking about it to others.  
My challenge to you today is to try to see both sides of the story the next time you might know a couple going through a rough time or a divorce.  See both sides of the story before judging and perhaps hurting and losing a friend over something that isn’t even true. 
Aye?
F3 is not a religious organization but we will end in a prayer.  You’re welcome to join or take a minute to connect with your sky Q.  Are there an intentions we can acknowledge? 

Prayed for people that don't have shelter during this cold weather.

COT: 
I spoke about the state of the world when it comes to the disparity in wealth and power, and how those that have tons of money and power are so out of touch with reality. It seems to be getting worse. This reminded me of a passage I have brought up during a few of my past COTs, the Paradox of our Time. I had planned to read this after this workout, but it was so cold my phone died while I was playing music. I have placed it below.

The paradox of our time in history is that we have taller buildings but shorter tempers, wider freeways, but narrower viewpoints. We spend more, but have less, we buy more, but enjoy less. We have bigger houses and smaller families, more conveniences, but less time. We have more degrees but less sense, more knowledge, but less judgment, more experts, yet more problems, more medicine, but less wellness.

We drink too much, smoke too much, spend too recklessly, laugh too little, drive too fast, get too angry, stay up too late, get up too tired, read too little, watch TV too much, and pray too seldom. We have multiplied our possessions, but reduced our values. We talk too much, love too seldom, and hate too often.

We've learned how to make a living, but not a life. We've added years to life not life to years. We've been all the way to the moon and back, but have trouble crossing the street to meet a new neighbor. We conquered outer space but not inner space.

We've done larger things, but not better things. We've cleaned up the air, but polluted the soul. We've conquered the atom, but not our prejudice. We write more, but learn less. We plan more, but accomplish less. We've learned to rush, but not to wait. We build more computers to hold more information, to produce more copies than ever, but we communicate less and less.

These are the times of fast foods and slow digestion, big men and small character, steep profits and shallow relationships. These are the days of two incomes but more divorce, fancier houses, but broken homes. These are days of quick trips, disposable diapers, throwaway morality, one night stands, overweight bodies, and pills that do everything from cheer, to quiet, to kill. It is a time when there is much in the showroom window and nothing in the stockroom. 

Remember, spend some time with your loved ones, because they are not going to be around forever. Remember, say a kind word to someone who looks up to you in awe, because that little person soon will grow up and leave your side.

Remember, to give a warm hug to the one next to you, because that is the only treasure you can give with your heart and it doesn't cost a cent.

COT: 
Honor Robbie Miller - See:
<https://youtu.be/8rF5cIU2X0Y>

After a few words about why we honored Sgt. Robbie Miller, I continued my CoT.  talking about how I have found some clarity through the completion of major physical goals these goals were large when they were originally set, but seem small when reflecting back.  I find myself seeking these challenges now.  I had no real understanding as to what this meant until I started reading The Comfort Crisis, By Michael Easter.  He describes how Shinto Monks in Japan, set out on cleansing ceremonies called Misogi's.  These are large challenges with failure rates up to and exceeding 50%.  These Misogi's, when completed provide the individual a sense of accomplishment and confidence that carries with them long after the task was completed.  When the individual fails, its a new source of fuel they can use to power their next attempt.  

I know we all challenge ourselves by setting weekly / monthly / yearly posting goals, maybe this year you train for a marathon, but have you ever set a goal so large your not even sure you can accomplish it?  If so what was it?  How did you do?  I'd love to hear about it.  Last year, mine was the all AO Ruck.  It was and still is the longest I have ever rucked.  Well this year my Misyogi was going to be GrowRuck.  Dont get me wrong, I am still excited about it and will certainly be there, but with the all the training we are doing, I feel more confident that my chances are much greater than 50% to successfully complete.  With that, I'm going to challenge myself with a much greater challenge this year, by setting my sights on another all AO Ruck.  However, this time we have two new AO's making the trek nearly 45 miles.  I'm still wrapping my head around this, and a little apprehensive in sharing this goal.  Without sharing, I could have quietly let this go cold, but now its out there and time to start planning.  If you have a goal, or Misyogi in mind, please share, and lets hold each other accountable and lift the ceiling as to what we believe is possible.  AYE!

For my COT today, I wanted to start with a quote 
“A dream does not become a reality through magic; it takes sweat, determination and hard work.”
We all have dreams like I want to lose 20 pounds or I want to move along in my career faster or I want to be closer to my M.  A dream first needs to become a goal and then goals only are met through the hard work.  It is very tough to keep pushing and pushing through to meet your goal.  Or if you meet your goal to set a new one that keeps you accelerating.
I ran into this over the past few months.  I wanted to lose weight and get down to 215 and busted my butt towards it for months.  But then I hit it and went into that maintain mindset .  What happened without a clear goal to keep pushing towards?  I gained 5 or 6 pounds after I stopped watching my calories and snacks.  I finally reset my goal to 210 and have lost most of the few pounds.  I’m pumped and am on track to hit 210.  When I do that, I will learn from my past mistakes and set a new one?  It can be for any area of your life and not just fitness.  If you are not happy in your career, brainstorm and come up with a goal or goals.  Work hard towards it and after you hit it set some more.  If you want to be closer to your M, sit down and discuss this with her.  Come up with goals mutually and work towards them.  
Never stop setting goals, never stop pushing yourself to be better, never stop accelerating.
Aye?

Thang 1 - Coupon Indian Walk – Split into two lines.
Walked to the pavilion to the north.  Started with right arm farmer carry,  then left arm farmer carry, then John Cusack, and then duck walk with coupon.  Person in back does blockee and runs to the front.  Went to pavilion and back.
Thang 2:
-Part 1 - Colts 45s, farmer carry coupon with right hand to cone (150 ft), Colt 45s, farmer carry coupon with left hand back to start.  Run to end of parking lot and back.  
Part 2 - Bolt 45s, lunge walk to cone, run the lot and back, bolt 45s, and duck walk back to the cone.  
Part 3 - Solt (shoulder) 45's - 15 shoulder press, 15 lion kings, 15 front pulls, John Cusack to the cone, run to end of parking lot and back. Repeat with 15 shoulder press, 15 lion kings, 15 front pulls, John Cusack to back to start, run to end of parking lot and back.  
-Part 4 - Baryshnikov 45s - Baryshnikov position with toes out and heels off the ground.  15 low squat pulses, 15 high squat pulses, and 15 full Baryshnikov squats.  Lunge walk to cone.  Run to end of parking lot and back.  Baryshnikov 45s and then duck walk to the start.  Run parking lot and back.  5:58, back to flags.

MARY: 
Leg lifts x 25

COT: 
I’m currently coaching my son’s basketball team.  Heading into yesterdays game we were 7-0 and had beaten all the other teams in the league.  We were going to play the team we faced in the first game of the year which was very competitive.  In the end we lost by 1 point in OT and took our first loss.  In the past I would have been stressed and upset by this similar to what I saw in my son at the end of the game.  He had a couple of attempts at the end of overtime that he missed and he felt like he let the team down. I asked him what he would do differently next time and his response was to “make the shot.”  I asked him what did he learn that will allow him to make the shot next time.  His response was “there was nothing I could do, they were in my face.”  I told him that if he doesn’t learn or change something that he should expect the same result and to not be upset when it happens again. I told him that this is no different from in basketball, schoolwork, relationships, or your job someday.  This situation really reminded me of Q Source and the concept of the Amateur vs a Pro.  The Amateur is a man ruled by reactive emotion rather than proactive preparedness while the Pro is a person whose focus is on preparedness.  Zach and I talked about some different things that he could practice when facing really tight defense.  When we got home, I started making dinner.  He decided to go out into the driveway to shoot which I thought was a positive.  We will see if his extra preparedness pays off next time…

My message this morning is embrace the tight games and the things that challenge you.  Beating teams by 30 points like we have doesn’t give you’re the perspective that we all need to understand our deficiencies and where we need to improve.  Seek out these types of situations, get comfortable with them, learn from them, and I guarantee the results will be different.  AYE!

Told the pax we are doing Chad 1000, half way through the step ups we changed it, then came back to it. The idea is that life changes in a instant once we our minds set on a plan the curveball comes and we have to learn to adapt/and over come then we can find ourselves on a new plan. Prepare for the unprepared and so you can be prepared when the unprepared happens.

What is our motivation?
What drives us to do the things we do?    Whether it’s Drugs, alcohol, pornography, eating disorders, gambling, impulsive purchases, starting a new business, starting a new diet, fitness routine. What ever it is there is core reason that initiates these actions. Before we do what we do ask yourself is this a emotional decision or a heart felt decision. 
If it is a emotional decision then it is probably not a good idea they usually start out on fire then eventually fizzle out once the emotional fuel is lost. COT:
  With the passing of Taylor Hawkins late last week I wanted to share the impact the Foo Fighters music has had on me
   When I was stuck in a rut and failing several times to quit drinking, my brother passed away from an incident where alcohol contributed to his own death.  He passed on 8-8-2013.  On 8-22 a few weeks later, my in laws and wife went to Home Run Inn for pizza and we ordered our usual and a couple of pitchers of Miller Lite.  I hadn’t had a drink since my brother died and I told myself I wouldn’t drink anymore because I wouldn’t let it effect my family the way I was seeing it effect his, but here I was again in a social position and back with a beer in front of me.  I took one sip of the Miller Lite put it down and said “I’m never drinking alcohol ever again”.  That was that.
     My wife had heard me say those words atleast a dozen times before, but when we got in the car after dinner she looked at me and knew that what was done was done.
     When I started the car, my usual 93.1 XRT was dialed in and “Times like these” was playing.  Anytime I hear a Foo Fighters song I have a little celebration of being sober and never looking back.  I’m not a crazy Groupie, they aren’t my favorite band, but the connection I have to their songs and especially that song is imbedded in me forever. 
     Dave Grohl, their frontman, said “thats the great thing about music, you can sing a song to 85,000 people and they’ll sing it back for 85,000 different reasons”

It's times like these you learn to live again
It's times like these you give and give again
It's times like these you learn to love again
It's times like these time and time again

For my COT today, I want to start with a quote “You do not find the happy life, you make it.”
We all can be at different spots in our F3 journey but we all came out for a lot of the same reasons.  One of the main things is that we are looking for something that wasn’t quite right or seemed to be missing.  For those of us who continued to come back after that first day, we are deciding to take control.  The sad clown will just sit there and go along with the status quo even if they aren’t happy.  The enlightened one trying to become a HIM will take control and make it happen.
I have dug deep into myself over the past 18 months and have reflected on some areas that I just accepted before as areas that just were such as a toxic personal life or going after unfilled life long goals.  I feel invigorated as I don’t ever remember and feel genuinely happy.  I don’t remember feeling this level of contentment ever.  I promise myself this and you this.  I will not stop setting goals and reaching for them.  I will not settle for mediocracy again.
My challenge to you is to ask yourself this simple question.  Are you happy?  If you are not happy reflect on areas of your life and what you can do to set a goal to accelerate that area.  Is there an unfilled dream of yours?  What is it? What can you do to achieve it?  Then put it in motion?  Come up with a plan and put it in action.  The greatest achievements in history have started with these simple words, “I WILL TRY”.
Aye?
F3 is not a religious organization but we will end in a prayer.  You’re welcome to join or take a minute to connect with your sky Q.  Are there an intentions we can acknowledge?

COT: For my COT today, I want to start with a quote “Life will always have its tides.  The more you can roll with them, the gentler they become.”
This quote strikes true to me this week.  Monday was a pretty good day.  Work went well and I had a nice dinner with Heather.  An all around good day.  Tuesday started well with a good EC run and great workout but work was one of those days where one thing after another kept going wrong.  I felt myself become more and more tense and frustrated.  But then I took a deep breath and started just addressing each thing one at a time and peeled them off the pile.  One involved a project with a drainage issue that I just wasn’t seeing the solution so I went and talked to my work mentor (and older engineer with 35 years of experience and he looked at it from a different perspective and there was a fairly simple solution.  I could have let series of mishaps take me down the spiral into a shitty mood but I was able to stop it before I went too far down that path and rolled with the punches as the day progressed.  
We talk in Q source about preparedness which is the way a leader becomes right in the four quadrants in his life.  Preparedness is built upon the bricks that form our guardrails that keep us from straying too far off our path to being the best man that we can be and are meant to be.  So, yesterday I was able to catch myself on the rumble strips along my path instead of going down into the ditch.  
My challenge to your today is to think of the last time that you veered off your path.  What happened?  Something at work?  Home?  Try to think of what you might have done differently so to avoid crashing into the ditch.  We own our mistakes and learn from them.
Aye?
F3 is not a religious organization but we will end in a prayer.  You’re welcome to join or take a minute to connect with your sky Q.  Are there an intentions we can acknowledge? 

Thanks to Burnt Ends for being my Site Q today and for Picasso and Dear Abby for posting this morning.  Great push guys!
On a side note, Foundation did not recognize Picasso until Name o rama which was embarrassing.  In Foundation's defense, Picasso shaved his beard.
