COT: 
The Best Things In Life Live on The Other Side Of Fear 
The Challenge is becoming mentally Strong Enough To Think Beyond The Moment

Everyone deals with being afraid.
It’s an integral part of our lives, it’s the very thing that tries to keep us safe.
The flip is that it also limits us
Fear is the source of everything that holds you back, everything that causes you to resist from moving forward.
In short, fear is what holds you back from experiencing those life-changing moments that shape your character.

Don’t fight your fears, face them. Acknowledge your fears — embrace them.
The thing you fear doing, is that exact thing you should be doing. You are more capable of conquering it than you realize. Think of all the things you’ve already overcome in the past. That power can support you in facing the next struggle. You are so much stronger than fear itself.

Backblast: Foundation's Beatdown at The Ridge
Date: August 9, 2021
AO: <#C02B4U0M71N|the-ridge-backblasts-only>
PAX: <@U01C516QSQZ> <@U01APFBACP8> @Rupaul <@U016W30QL1G> <@U016ZUU67BN> <@U0171KQRB6D> <@U016U07U2KV> <@U017DQX583C> <@U017HR90C3E> <@U02A96WLKRB> <@U02ADFBHJP8> <@U019TSFML4C> <@U016MKQUP29> <@U017X9WAQ9Y> <@U01E40PTNFJ> <@U016V6KHM36> <@U017HR8U5RS> <@U019Y7P6XPF>
FNGs: 1
Q: <@U019Y7P6XPF>
Count: 18
I arrived at 4:15 to set up and make coffee.  Then ran 1.5 miles.  Thanks to <@U017HR8U5RS> for having my 6.  Shout out to <@U02ADFBHJP8> who came out for his first workout today.  
I started with the standard wording.
It’s 5:15 so let’s get started.  This is a free, volunteer, peer-led workout.  I am definitely not a professional.  I have no knowledge of any injuries or fitness considerations that you might have.  It is each person’s responsibility to be safe and modify exercises if you need to.  We all do it, most important thing is that you don’t get hurt.  Do we have any FNG’s?  F3 has 5 principles to make sure that it is an F3 workout:  
1. Be free of charge
2. Be open to all men
3. Be held outdoors, rain or shine, heat or cold
4. Be led by men who participate in the workout in a rotating fashion with no training necessary
5. End with a circle of trust
 
Let’s warm up:
First exercise – Side Strattle Hops, ready position you are in it, in cadence, begin (DO 20)
recover
Second exercise – abe vigodas, ready position you are in it, in cadence, begin (10)
Recover
Third Exercise – Good Mornings, ready position you are in it, in cadence, begin (10)
recover
last exercise – Shoulder Circles, ready position you are in it, in cadence, begin (10)
Workout
Thang 1
Line up on the one side of the parking lot by the flags with coupons that is station 1
At Station 1 do 2 thrusters and 2 curls then bear crawl to station 2 on the other edge of the parking lot do 2 hand release merkins and 2 leg raises then lunge walk back to station 1.  Now add 2 to all of the exercises but do the rest the same and next time at station 1 add two more so 6 then 8 then 10 and so forth
Thang 2
Three stations
Station 1 with coupons is the pavilion
Station 2 is over by the edge of the parking lot by the playground
Station 3 is over by the south side of the parking lot next to the entrance driveway
Station 1 – alternate between 20 curls and shoulder presses and 20 dips and bent over rows each time you are at station 1
Station 2 – 3 burpess, 10 merkins, 5 WW1 situps
Station 3 – 50 jump ropes, 10 air squats
Mary
Big Boys – on my count (30-35)
Pickle Pushers – on my count (20)
Merkin Ring of Fire
NAME-O-RAMA and Announcements
COT
For my COT, I wanted to start with a quote,

“Lead by listening, to be a good leader you have to be a greater listener”

This is one area that I always need to take a step back and focus on improving.  Being a truly good listener is a tough skill to master and so many people overlook trying to accelerate in this area.  It’s so easy to get caught up thinking about how you are going to answer when someone is talking.  I call this listening with the motor running. That’s one thing that I have to keep reminding myself not to do.  I have to remind myself to face the person that is talking, make eye contact, have good body language that is telling them that I am listening to them.

It is such a basic skill but we all can keep striving to be a better listener to our friends, co-workers, M’s, 2.0’s or anyone that you may be having a conversation with.

My challenge to you is focus on trying to be a better listener today when you are talking to people today.  Don’t listen with the motor running.  Truly hear what they are telling you.

Aye?

Ended with Prayer

Thang 2: 50 Squats. Up hill murder bunnies. 10 Blockees on top. Rifle carry down. 50 Lunges. Up hill murder bunnies. 10 Blockees on top. Rifle carry down. 50 Jackhammers. Up hill murder bunnies. 10 Blockees on top. Rifle carry down.

CoT:With summer winding down, kids returning back to school and lots of obligations kicking in, I’ve been thinking of ways to help maintain a positive attitude in the face of added busyness and the accompanying stress. Trying to focus on the role of gratitude and being deliberate each days in thinking of things I am grateful for. Recently read an story of an American who had spent time working in remote African villages. When they returned stateside, every time they turned on the facet they felt a sense of joy and gratitude, as running water was something they had done without during their time in Africa. Gradually that sense of gratitude faded, but it is important that we be deliberate in noticing and appreciating the numerous blessings we take for granted, and in so doing create a continuous sense of gratitude

FNGs: 1

Count: 11
WoR:
Motivators IC:5
Mosey with high knees, butt kicks, shuffle, and karaoke

Goofballs IC: 10
Arm Circles front and back IC:10

Thang 1: Partner up and stay together the entire time. 100 yard football field marked at 10 yard increments with cones. Start at end zone with 11 burpees, run to last cone (100 yards) and back to 10 yard line, perform 10 burpees, run to last cone and back to the 20 yard line, perform 9 burpees, …. Continue until you get to the last cone and perform 1 burpee.  Pick up the 6 when you are done.

Thang 2: P1 performs coupon exercises, P2 goes up the hill, run down and switch. Going up the hill alternate between bear crawls and running (P1 and P2 bear crawl up hill, P1 and P2 run up hill, P1 and P2 bear crawl up hill….) 2 rotations up and down the hill and move to next exercise unless you finish the number of reps for that exercise beforehand.

Coupon exercises = 100 thrusters, 200 chest presses, 200 coupon swings, 200 curls, 200 goblet squats

Mary:
Big Boys 50
Big Boy Twists (Alternate right elbow to left knee and left elbow to right knee) 20
Low plank until 0600

CoT: Talked about my oldest daughter Sydney.  Sydney has always been a pretty shy and reserved kid.  We encouraged her to do sports as she has grown up.  Unfortunately there was a reoccurring theme where she would do one season of something and quit.  She had a tough time connecting that everyone starts a sport from scratch and then builds their skills.  Last year Sydney was starting high school at Plainfield North.  She and her best friend decided that they would try out for the tennis team even though they had never really played tennis as they heard it was a no cut sport.  Unfortunately this was the year of COVID and tennis was one of the only sports that girls were allowed to play in the fall.  As a result, a ton of girls tried out and there were cuts.  Neither made the team.  The coach encouraged the girls though to take lessons over the next year and try out again.  So they were up to the challenge and took lessons throughout all of last year.  Fast forward to this week and they started tryouts on Monday.  I received a phone call from Sydney on Wednesday morning that she made the JV team.  Her excitement over the phone was palpable.  She finally put her mind to sport, put in the work, and it paid off.  Now she will be able to experience what I think we get filled with F3.  F3 for me brings back both the fitness and fellowship aspects that we experienced playing on teams when we were younger.  I am just so excited that she will finally be able to experience this for herself!

Thang 1
I have three lines marked out behind the pavilion with cones.  Take your coupons out there.  At the first line you will do 12 curls then do murder bunnies to the second line.  You will do 12 skull crushers and then rifle carry to the third line where you do 12 gobblet squats then rifle carry back to line 2 for 12 skull crushers then do murder bunnies back to the starting line.  Subtract 2 from each exercise this time and rinse and repeat.  Next time you finish the cycle then subtract 2 more so you’ll do 12 of each, 10 of each, 8 of each and so forth.  If you get to 2 then start working your way up by 2.
Thang 2
Four stations (going counter clockwise)
Station 1 with coupons is the pavilion
Station 2 is over by the West edge of the parking lot
Station 3 is over by the south side of the parking lot next to the entrance driveway
Station 4 is over by the edge of the parking lot by the playground
Station 1 – alternate between 20 dips and bent over rows and 20 curls and 10 coupon swings each time you are at station 1
Station 2 – 20 merkins, 20 mountain climbers (10 w each leg), 20 LBCs
Station 3 – 50 jump ropes, 20 dips on curb, 10 leg raises
Station 4 – 3 burpees, 20 bobby hurleys, 10 merkins
Run between counter clockwise and rinse and repeat

Mary:
Big Boys 35
Pickle Pushers 20
Merkin Ring of Fire

COT: For my COT, I wanted to start with a quote,

“Leaders become great not because of their power, but, because of their ability to empower others.””

Being a good leader means being open to new ideas, possibilities, and perspectives, and understanding that there’s no “right” way to do things.  Leaders must be able to listen, observe and be willing to change course when necessary.

5 essential qualities of a good leader are communication, vision, empathy, accountability and gratitude.

I’ve talked about some of these other areas in past COT’s and wanted to talk a little bit about empathy.  An Empathetic leader is one who has a genuine interest in his team member’s lives, the challenges they face and their overall feelings.  This kind of leader makes an effort to understand their situations and what they are going through, in order to offer support and help.

My challenge for you to do today is to think about an M, 2.0, friend or co-worker that may be experiencing a bump in the road of life.  Try to experience it from their point of view and how you would feel in that situation.  Try to get into their shoes so to speak and walk around a little.  If you can experience how you believe you would feel in that situation then you a better suited to be able to help them or at least provide better support.

Aye?

Any prayer requests?

Im hitting the 2 year mark at F3 this month and am at the point in my F3 career that things are not necessarily as new and exciting as they were when I first started. The word Merkin doesn’t make me giggle much anymore and I’m running out of jokes surrounding Pickle Pushers and monkey hampers. When I have beers with Joe dirt we don’t even do motivators anymore. 

F3 has not lost its luster for me it’s just appealing to me in different ways. I’m finding that the 2nd and 3rd F is as important or more important than the 1st F. I have found myself setting personal goals trying to make positive changes to my family life outside of the workout as a result of discussions with the guys at Joseph and Jesus, Q source, coffeeteria or just hearing some motivating words during a COT. When I started F3 2 years ago I weighed about what I do now with some peaks and valleys, added some strength and cardio. There is no doubt fitness is and should be very important to all of us. When I look back at how my world has changed as a result of F3. I think more about the intentional changes I have made to be better dad, husband, son and friend. I still have a lot to improve on and want to continue to try to accelerate in all 3 F’s. 

If you have been focusing on your 1st and are finding yourself running out of monkey humper jokes and don’t burpee after beers with your buddies as much as you used too. Ask yourself What you can do to set some new goals and accelerate your 2nd or 3rd F. 

Ended in prayer

COT: Bit off a lot to chew on the CoT: Tried to convince all the PAX that they were in better shape than David Goggins... yes that it right. I hope I made my case. Basically no one can match David Goggins when it comes to training. We, however at F3 are about more than training, we are about TRANSFORMATION. When you put all that we do together (all 3 F's), I do believe we are in better shape to live our lives, lead our households, and influence the community. We don't just train, we are a community. We sometime say we get up at 4:30 A.M. because fitness is so important to us, but I believe it is really the community and accountability that we get up for. When we HC, we are telling our brothers that we will be there for each other ITG and help each other accelerate. I didn't share this during CoT, but wanted to drop it here for reference:

It's all you knuckleheads that make F3 so great and that is WHY we are in such great shape! Case closed!

COT:

I read the poem below

I really love this poem because it is a great reminder that there are people who are watching me, my actions, and my words. Not in a big-brother sort of way. More of a “I want to be like you” sort of way. As a dad it’s is a reminder that It doesn’t matter what I try to teach my kids, more is caught than taught. My actions are important. But so are my inactions. Most mornings when my oldest wakes up he asks me “Daddy, did you go to F3 today?” On the days I tell him yes, he is really happy for me. When I tell him no, he usually asks “We’ll, why not?” They see it. 

The same goes for our spouses. They see us waking up early to go workout. Or like my wife, she doesn’t see me leave. Hell she doesn’t usually see me get home since she is still asleep. But she knows. As time goes on I think they begin to realize that this is way more than just waking up early to workout. They see the dedication, they see the commitment, they see the friendships forming, they see a transformation. They see it. 

Next is your fellow pax. They see something your spouse doesn’t see. They see you putting in the hard work of each workout. They see the struggle. They see the looks on your face when you’re putting in 100%. They see the happiness when you know you’ve put in all you had and you still survived. The accomplishment. The vulnerability. They see it. 

Finally, our community. F3 is here to invigorate male community leadership. If you are trying to invigorate something, no matter what it is, how can you not be noticed? Our community sees a group of men gathering together. Supporting each other. Welcoming complete strangers; celebrating those who choose this path. Standing in front of our symbol of freedom. And finally ending by taking a moment to pray and give thanks to something that is bigger than us. They see it. 

There are a lot of people who see what we do. We are having a positive impact on so many people through the simple act of showing up. Good work today men. Keep Accelerating!

THANG 1 & 2 – MERRY GO ROUND OF PAIN
Set up 8 stations in the pavilion in circular fashion with an exercise at each station. One individual sits in the middle “The Conductor” & does 30 Big Boys. The Merry Go Round does not rotate until “The Conductor” finishes their Big Boys & then shuffles around the Merry Go Round. Once “The Conductor” taps your shoulder after shuffling around the PAX will sprint out to the first cones in parking lot & do 10 merkins, then will sprint to the other side of the parking lot & do 10 mountain climbers, & then finish by sprinting back to the pavilion. Upon return you hold squat or plank until the 6 is back. New “Conductor” gives a 10 count then rinse & repeat.  The list of stations (with coupon) below:

CoT – Embrace Change & Be the Change for Someone Else
·      F3 has truly impacted me on every level of the 3 F’s & that is why today I want to share maybe the 3 most impactful moments in my F3 journey that also coincide with the 3 F’s:
o  August 29th 2019 fitness. I struggled running across that field to that bridge where I completed a brutal partner workout. We then followed it up with partner push ups when I thought I was going to die but then I was told to run to the hill where we would proceed to run backwards. These are things that were out of my comfort zone & pushed me beyond what I though I could do. At that moment I knew I had found something special.
o  October 26th 2019 fellowship. After a Saturday beat down at BP a group of men encouraged me to go over to the Outpost b/c there was a special event going down for Bob Ross. A 66 year old man who had been color blind his whole life. The brothers of F3 Naperville all chipped in & with the help of Dr. Ralph the men purchased a pair of color blind glasses so BR could see color for the first time. Upon arrival there were probably 75 F3 brothers & BR’s family waiting for him to come in from the workout. He was shocked & the gratitude outpoured. I watched the men of F3 Naperville socialize & give praise & gratitude to the man they call The Lion of Naperville. It was that same man who pulled me aside not to long after that who told me I was a natural leader & it was time for me to step up & lead the men of Naperville needed me. Less than a month later on Nov 21st I did my VQ.
o  February 1st 2020 faith. This morning I watched over 100 men converge on North Central College to remember a fallen brother Noonan. Ironically enough I had just met him for the first time 2 days ago at my first time at The Citadel where they awarded him a bottle of whiskey for joining the respect club on his 50th birthday, then 24 hours later he was gone. In a short 24 hour time a group of men many who I barely knew gathered to honor him. If you were not there just imagine 100 men doing motivators in a tight circle with brick walls all around you, “shivers up your spine”. Then I watched men push through a grueling workout. Then it concluded with Noonan’s wife & kids showing up & few strong men honoring Noonan in front of the family. I watched grown men openly crying while other grown men some of whom did not know each other that well wrapping arms around each other. Faith.
·      That is what this is all about men. Embrace your time & embrace every one of the three F’s b/c this will give back to you more than you will ever get out of it if you embrace it. Aye

CoT 
For the COT today, I wanted to reflect a little bit on my F3 journey over the past year.  I showed up that first day a very sad clown that had absolutely no self-confidence.  I had reached out to Parks and Recreation the day before asking him if he still did that workout group thing.  I had lived near him for 10 years and still keep in touch through Facebook.  He told me that there was a workout at the Ridge the next morning and would meet me there.
It was Boston Butt’s one year anniversary and he put us through a hell of a workout with bear crawls over the bridge.  I was exhausted afterwards and thought that this was a good workout.   I didn’t really hear his COT because I didn’t start wearing my hearing aids to the workouts for another month or two.  Yes, that’s why I wear the headbands for those that don’t know.  To protect them from sweat.
But I began to realize that F3 was more than just the tough workout when we went to the Pavilion for coffee afterwards.  I talked with El Dingy and Den Mother that day but was still the quiet guy off to the side.  I looked around and just the joking and talking everyone was doing was pretty cool in my book.  I hardly ever see group of friends that I had.  Maybe once a year.  
I slowly began to open up over the next few months, started Qing and talking to people more and I began the journey to regain my self-confidence.  I have some good memories over the past year and made some really good friends.  I remember about a dozen of us trying to get into the Ridge parking lot during a blizzard in winter and just before calling it quits, Skinner flagged down the Village snow plow driver and he plowed us a land into the parking lot by the clubhouse.  We did a workout running in the snow with merkins, burpees and air squats.  We adapted and overcame.  The bond that you form out here in the gloom especially on the days with less than ideal weather conditions is amazing.
My biggest example of this is this past week.  It has been probably the toughest week of my life and I am at a loss for words at the support that I have received.  Losing my Dad suddenly on Wednesday has left me feeling so empty.  He was so much to me.  He was always there for me, through my very dark years from around 2009.  He would always make the time and meet up and listen.  Even if did didn’t know what to say at times, he would be there.  I could always count on him.  And in a blink, he’s gone.  I was the last one to speak to him, it was a simple conversation as we had many mornings before.  He was on the way to a jobsite and was asking how my divorce was going and making sure I was ok.  Then, we finished with him asking about the F3 workout.  He really liked hearing about it and then we ended with him telling me to give him a call after work and we’d grab a coffee probably on my way home.
Morning and late afternoon on Thursday and Friday have been very tough this week.  
These are the times when I would talk to him and usually meet up for a quick conversation over a cup of coffee or iced tea.  
The turnout on Thursday morning to the boot camp and then so many people coming over from the other AOs for coffee to give me support still chokes me up.  As the dust settles in a month or two after my divorce, my move and helping my Mom sort through all of the issues after Dad’s passing, I will begin to face the future which is uncertain.  At those times when I was feeling lost or sad, I could always count on him to talk, meet up and help out unconditionally no matter what I needed.  
After the support that I have received this week from you all, I know that I won’t be facing my future alone.  I have a great group of friends.  So I say to you all my F3 brothers, I am so grateful and blessed to have you in my life.  In one year, I have posted around 200 times, Q’ed 47 times.  I look forward to the next 500 posts.  I love you guys.
Aye?
Any prayer requests?  Please pray for my Dad.  I know he is looking down from heaven on us today.  And I know that he is proud of the man that I have become and you will help me to continue my path to be.

Do hard things.  Just this past weekend a bunch of PAX set out for a CSAUP (Completely Stupid and Utterly Pointless).  We marched from each AO for a total of 15 miles, crossed a river twice, carried heavy things, PT at each AO, and ended in extreme heat.  Why??  Because doing hard things is rewarding and makes your stronger.  I dont like to run, so I signed up for Ragnar (a 200 mile relay race).  Why, because if I don't do hard things I can't get better.  I am know learning how to run.  What is my pace for this distance, how do I overcome the mental battle of running, what gear do I need to be successful, running with another person is a game changer.  I would never of learned these things without pushing myself to do something hard.  In life, do hard things.  We come to avoid hard things.  Challenge yourself to do hard things at work and at home.  See what a difference is after you complete something hard to find it easier in the future.  The next hard thing will completed to pave the way for the next hard thing.  Life is as rewarding as you make it.

   5 years ago last Friday our nephew Anthony was born. Unfortunately, Anthony passed away on his day of birth due to complications on the delivery.  My Brother in law, Tony, and Sister in law, Kandice, host the family every year at the cemetery to celebrate Anthony’s birthday.  This year was a very hot day and my sister in law brought cupcakes that were melting in the heat. Kandice placed a cupcake for Anthony at his gravestone and passed the rest out to the family.  The frosting slid right off of Anthony’s cupcake. My son Jack noticed and his cupcake was perfectly fine.  Jack walked over to Anthony’s gravestone and swapped the cupcakes, looked at me and said “Anthony should have the nice cupcake on his birthday.”
    I feel like I stress out over simple things of parenting- tying their shoes, taking training wheels off, junk food.  We all want them to do well and sometimes all’s we have to do is show them.  Show them happiness, love, kindness, and empathy.  They’ll live with the love that their shown.

CoT:
•	I read this quote this week from Mayo Angelou, “Do the best you can until you know better.  Then when you know better, do better.”  To me this is all about 2 of my favorite things ACCELERATION & ACCOUNTABILITY.  Before many of us started F3 we were just getting through life the best we could in our Sad Clown costumes.  Then we found F3 which taught us how to be better.  This past week was a test of the 2nd part of that quote for me around “do better”. We had our national Beer convention with distributors in Vegas this past week where we spent 3 days with nothing but my jesters facing me at every corner with all you can eat free food & all kinds of free booze.  In years past I would be the guy who ate every item on the desert tray that was available, I was the guy who would be the first lined up at the bar for a beer & one of the last guys to shut it down at night.  In the mornings I would feel terrible the next day but do it all over again.  This year though I knew better based on what F3 has taught me so I decided to DO BETTER.  I found myself controlling my food portions & avoiding the sweets, I paced my drinking by forcing water in between beverages & most importantly put a midnight curfew on myself.  I was worried when I stepped on the scale Friday morning but was pleased to see I was only +1 lb prior to leaving.  I share b/c it is just another example of how F3 has changed me.  So my challenge to all of you is “now that you know better than actually apply that knowledge to do better”.  Aye!

ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: For today’s COT, a wanted to start with a quote
“Victory is always possible for the person who refuses to stop fighting.”
I had always heard variations of this quote in the various sports growing up and just thought ok whatever.  It can be in any aspect of your life.  It is the easiest to see the milestone results in a physical type thing such as working out but can be anything in our lives.
When things seem impossible and that there is no hope, it’s so easy just to roll over and give up.  I know.  I did that for years in my personal life.  When you get a string of bad things happening you can develop a feeling of hopelessness and can find yourself thinking, hell, nothing I can do will improve the situation.  For example, I had a bad situation in my relationship with my first M and I had the feeling that it was hopeless, nothing I did mattered, I was stuck.  It rolled over into all other aspects of my life.  My professional life suffered.  My physical shape and health suffered.  My mood overall suffered.  
Doing our workouts in the gloom, you can see how not giving up and perseverance can pay off with your physical condition.  I know I have.  That is an easy example to see the gains.  
Over the past month and a half, I have had several major bad things happen.  The passing of my Dad, divorce and moving.  I found myself allowing that sense of hopelessness creep back in but I fought through it.  I have had to remind myself daily of that quote and variations on it.  Think on those words.  Victory is always possible for those who refuse to stop fighting.  My Dad would always tell me one that was “When life is getting shitty and it seems impossible, pick yourself up by your bootstraps and get it done.”
So, now as I am “picking myself up by my bootstraps” daily, I am seeing myself starting to work myself through the bad things that seemed surmountable just a few weeks ago.  My house is under contract.  We are slowing going through the list of things that needs to be done after Dad died.  My M and I are talking through the final stages of the divorce and not fighting through them.  I’m getting caught up again after the time off from work when Dad passed.  I continually keep my eye on the goals and I know I have the strength to get the job done.
For any of you out there that may be going through something tough in your life, don’t give up and keep trying.  Nothing is impossible if you just don’t stop trying.  If you aren’t going through tough times, then I challenge you to reflect on and set a new fitness goal and keep trying to hit that goal.
 
Aye?
Ended with prayer

A common phrase heard during IPC is that it is "you vs. you." While that is true, being around other men pushes you to go beyond your limits. I came across an article on the Art of Manliness (thanks @Ozark for the reference to that site) that talked about this. Here is a snippet from the article:

"Researchers asked cyclists to pedal stationary bikes as fast as they could and recorded their personal records after several rounds of attempts. Despite the fact that the cyclists were sure, sure, that they could go no faster, once they were put in a simulated race against a supposed competitor — which was really just an avatar set to their own best time — nearly all of them were able to beat their previous PRs."

Source: <https://www.artofmanliness.com/character/advice/sunday-firesides-your-worst-competitor-is-you/>

We are fortunate to be a part of F3 that puts us next to other men that are bettering themselves, but also helping us to do the same.

Prayers were for @Skidmark 's brother-in-law and @Disco Ball 's sister.

“One kind act can change someone’s entire day.” 
Going to help out at Feed my Starving Children on Saturday got me thinking about this topic.  Just packing one bag of food there takes about 30 seconds but it has a drastic change on the day of the person on the receiving end of that food.   The act of kindness doesn’t have to be a huge earthshattering event but can be as simple as asking a friend that seems down if they are ok.  Or asking a co-worker if they need a hand when they are carrying something.  Or donating a $1 to a charity collection.  It may be a seemingly small thing to you but could have made a big difference.
An example for me was Saturday, I was feeling a little out of place at Feed my Starving Children as the only one there from our group without our families.  I felt self-conscious and missed my girls.  I started to let negative, feel sorry for myself thoughts creep in as I was helping at Feed my Starving Children.   Afterwards, Happy Camper invited me to come over and join his family for dinner at the nearby restaurant.  It brought me out of my thoughts to join them and get to know them a little more.  
My challenge to you is this.  Go do at least one act of kindness towards someone today without wanting something in return.  You never know what that person may be going through and that one very simple act of kindness may be the bright spot in their day that they needed.
Aye?

At the bottom of the path on the east side of the bridge: 10 Carolina Dry Docks, 10 Bonnie Blair’s (each leg = 1/2), 10 big boys. Run uphill to the bridge. Bear crawl across bridge. Mosey down path west of the bridge to the bottom of the hill. 10 Catalina Wine Mixers, 10 No Surrenders, 10 Big Boys. Sprint up path to the bridge. Broad jump across bridge, mosey downhill to where you started. Rinse and repeat. After two rounds, return to flags, one stop along the way (10 burpees in cadence).

ANNOUNCEMENTS: Seemed to be enjoyed by all. Nickelback was gassed, but pushed through. Had two familiar friends walk through our workout, but Bailout failed to EH them. We were all glad to have Better Call Saul join us, even though he was supposed to be at the BD workout. Second Best wore regular workout clothes.
COT: Little things done often. Little things done often can have a powerful effect. I take on a lot of responsibility around my house—I do the dishes, the laundry, the cooking, give kids baths and put them to bed every night. When somebody does little things (often) to help me out—emptying the dishwasher, bringing in the garbage cans from the curb—I appreciate it very, very much. By realizing this, I have been trying to pay attention to the little things I do (often) to help others. One of the things I have always done when putting my kids to bed is to blow them a kiss before closing their door. My son has reached an age where it has become fun to make fun of how dad isn’t cool (all in good fun). The other day I surprised him with a gift that I knew he would love…special Pokémon Oreos (yeah, I like Oreo’s too but I don’t care if they have Pokémon on them). Before showing him the surprise, his mom said, “Dad got you something and when you see it, he is going to be your favorite person in the world!” His reply was, “Like THAT will ever happen!” It was pretty funny. And it started a humorous conversation of listing different things I do, and him telling me if they are cool—the answer to each one was, of course, “No!” Except…when I said, “How about when I blow you a kiss every night when I put you to bed?” He replied, “Yeah, I like that…that’s pretty cool.” Little things done often. Pay attention to the little things you do for others, and start noticing the little things others do for you.

The same goes for raising a child. You need to love and nourish your child. You need to maintain communication with your child and you must protect your child from bad apples or weeds that influence your child. 
The message never changes through the years for raising a child. Do the right thing ,set a good example and be kind to everyone. Your child will roll their eyes at you or in one ear out the other it seems like you keep saying the same things over and over.

ANNOUNCEMENTS- Check the slack channel.  Lots going on! 

COT

What’s Your Numbers?

We all have numbers. Today mine are 53.  I’m 53 years old.  Each year we celebrate a birthday and each successive year our numbers increase by 1.  Men, let’s not fool ourselves, they’re just numbers.  Right?  Exactly!  Our age is often used as a qualifier for many things like for instance when we can legally vote, legally drive a vehicle, join the military, legally buy our first beer, and even when we qualify for AARP (apparently I’m eligible).   Our  numbers are often used by some to assume things about us like being more mature, being stronger, being faster, being weaker, being slower, wiser, more experienced,  being immature.  You know, I can't recall the number of times when someone has asked me how old I am, and I literally have to do some funny sort of math to come to an answer.  You know why?  I don't really put much stock into how old I am.  It’s not a big deal to me.  I know I’m older and I have used the term “old” “older” etc and my M always says you’re not old, don’t say that when I’ve used those words.  The thing is I use it merely as a term,  it has no real meaning to me nor defines me.  Everyone has their own definition for what old means.   For me when I do say I’m old, older, I think I’m subconsciously telling myself...damn you’re not the typical 53 year old.  Or maybe I’m trying to see how that excuse that many people use works, how it feels on me.  It doesn’t work nor suit me.  I have no idea what a 53 year old is supposed to look or feel like and to be perfectly blunt I don’t really care.  Why?  Because my numbers do not define me.  They are…just a set of numbers.  As I continually strive to be the best version of me some will mention those numbers.  We mention our numbers each time at the Name o Rama.  For some those numbers represent our diversity, they identify who might be similar to us, or to some those numbers may even serve as inspiration and motivation.  In the end, they are what they are… a set of numbers...today mine are 53.  I will never let my new numbers and any future numbers define me, Never!  So what are  your numbers?  Are you going to let them define you?  I say not today, not tomorrow, I say never! 

Ended with TAPS (Thoughts and Prayers)

Veterans Day is a time to honor all the brave men and women among us who, at one time or another, put on the uniform and served to protect our country, our liberty and our lives.
For those who never served in the military, it is impossible to understand the sacrifices that have been made for all Americans by those few brave ones; the time spent away from family or personal pursuits, the physical toll of training and fighting, the scars that remain when the battle is over. Every citizen owes a debt that can never be repaid, a debt to every veteran for their service and our freedom. And while we can never truly understand their sacrifice or repay their service, we can honor them, be thankful for them and remember them.

On Veterans Day we pause to make sure we are thankful for each and every man and woman who wore the uniform. For so many, those veterans are sons and daughters, siblings, parents, grandparents, relatives or friends.

Today we remember them all, and we express our gratitude for what they have done. We are also thankful to have them with us — whether or not we know them personally.

Thank a Veteran today.

Review: Choosing love, earning trust. I can choose love and earn trust by learning how to communicate effectively during conflict. 

Principal #3 - Keep Talking
Communication is key in marriage, during good times and bad times. Let’s talk about the bad times, because we all have them. 
Conflict is not bad, it’s inevitable. How we deal with it makes it Good or Bad. 
Me and my wife are a team, yet often in my communication I forget this,  and I’m defending ME, not US. 
• Avoid the three unhealthy “Fight Languages”: escalation, withdrawal, and invalidation. These habits become the issues that derail you from talking about the issue you’re trying to solve.
• Healthy communicators use “I feel…because” statements instead of pointing fingers at their spouse. Learn to be an active listener (“what I hear you saying is…”) and work together (“Let’s try this…”) to find solutions.
Let’s learn how to deal with conflict in a loving, US centered way - for the good of our marriage.

COT
I recently took a training class at my company called Ignite Inclusion.  This is part of the journey my company is on to improve Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion.  The training was very good, super dynamic speaker.  My biggest takeaway was how we can both intentionally and unintentionally exclude people.  Intentionally is fairly obvious (don't want to get into that here) but unintentionally can and is very subtle.  Humans have developed to be naturally inwardly focused.  We are psychologically programmed with a constant assessment of fight or flight.  This can lead to a unintentional exclusion of people you interact with that can make others feel very uncomfortable.

After the training, I found myself in the break room with 4 other people.  Three of us tend to be more outgoing while the other two less.  Having just taken the training I was hyperaware of this situation and did my part to try to include the two other people in the room and make them feel comfortable.  Unfortunately I realized that I have not always done a great job of observing this and filling this role.  One conclusion that I've made is that I need to continue to become more comfortable with myself to make others more comfortable.  This is something that I am going to try to focus on going forward.  I encourage us all the have the courage to stop, listen, and engage others as we go throughout our days.  This can be at home, social situations, or at work.  There is power in the many.  Lets all do our parts to unlock this.  AYE!

<@U016V6KHM36> interjected when I was finished.  He asked us to look around and asked what most of us had in common.  We were basically 100% middle aged white men.  To truly set a fire and achieve the expansion goals F3 has across the nation we need to do a better job recruiting those that don't look like us.  Great point and agree 100%.

COT: For today’s COT, I wanted to talk about my journey.   I have experienced so much since I started in August 2020.  I showed up that first day looking for that thing that was missing in my life.  I showed up the quiet, fat, nice guy who kept saying he’s sorry because he couldn’t hear or was pulling up the 6 bigtime. My Jester’s which I let control me and my life are lack of self-confidence and anxiety.  
I was two years into a rebound marriage after I had finally drawn up the courage to stand up to my first wife and divorced her in early 2017 after 17 years together.  She was not a nice person and I dealt with manipulation, gaslighting, severe emotional abuse and infidelity.  I had not mentally/emotionally dealt with that and dated immediately and was married in May 2018 to my 2nd wife exactly one year from the day we met.  I still allowed myself to be used and walked on because of my Jester’s controlling my life.  I had many anxiety attacks even had another trip to the ER in 2019 with “heart attack” type symptoms that were deemed to be entirely stress/anxiety related after the full battery of tests.  
I needed something drastically to change in my life.  The only reason I wanted to wake up was my daughters and parents and siblings.  My stepsons did not respect me nor listen to me.  I did not get back up from their mother.  I remember being told by her that “she would divorce me if I ever talked to her children like that again” after I yelled at them because they were acting terribly and told me that they didn’t have to listen to me while I was watching them and she was at work.    They did whatever they wanted and I remember how they would run to their room and call her to tattle if I corrected them while watching them when she was at work.  It would end up in a fight every time.  We did not sleep in the same room for almost the entire 3.5 year marriage.  We were intimate only like a half dozen times over our “marriage” and not even on the wedding night.

I reached out to Parks and Recreation in the end of August 2020 and asked him if he still did that “workout thing”.  I had lived a few doors down from him for 12 years and stayed friends.  He told me where the Ridge was and go there at 5:10am the next morning.  I went and was destroyed physically by Boston Butt’s one year manniversay that day but felt a spark.  As I began to come more frequently, I began to have breakthrough therapy sessions with my counselor who I began to see back in 2018.   She told me that she loved this new workout group thing which was so much more than a workout group and don’t stop whatever I do.  My 2nd wife did not like me going and would give me a hard time and I would hear “You are tired at night” or “you wake me up when you put up the garage door at 4:30 am”.  I would skip Saturday workouts in order to not be tired but she would find other things to fight over and find fault with.  In January 2021, I vowed to keep accelerating and started going to Q-source and went to like 10 black diamonds in a row.  Over 2020, I continued to “get right” and becoming more self-confident and finally stopped making excuses to myself for the crappy marriage I was in.  She was unhappy and unwilling to put any effort in really working on it.  We attended couples counselling twice in a year, she refused to go to a church marriage workshop, she told me repeatedly that she liked it better when my daughters weren’t at our house, and the kicker that she didn’t love me and would have divorced me in 2018 but she couldn’t afford to.  I paid the mortgage and all of the bills myself even though we made the same salary.  I heard so many times how our marriage is bad and this sucks and we should get divorced.  I always talked her off the ledge.
The final fight occurred in end of July when I came back from a workout one morning.  She was upset and seemed very out of sorts that morning.  I asked her what’s wrong and if I could do anything to help her.  She told me how her life sucks, no one ever helps her and that she wishes that she could go workout like I did.  I said that we could alternate mornings if she wanted and she said “you know that I don’t do mornings” and I told her that I go before everyone is up so I can help with the kids, cooking, etc.  She told me that F3 should stand for Fitness, Fellowship and F_ck your wife over because you don’t give a sh_t about them.  That started the last fight and when she said that our life and marriage sucked and that we should just get divorced, I said you know what you are right.  I filed for divorce a week later.
My dad passed away suddenly two weeks after I filed for divorce.  He was my rock.  I would meet him for coffee and lunch just about every day for years.  We would talk on the way to and from work every day since I got out of school.  He was the one constant in my life.  A week later, I remember standing at the balcony in the office building at work and seriously considered ending it and jumping.  I had hit bottom.  But I pulled myself up and have vowed to be the best father, son, brother, friend and worker I can be.  I have cranked up the dial on my accelerating in all aspects of my life.  I focused on the light at the end of the tunnel and am taking it a small goal/task at a time.  Made it through the divorce, moved into a new house, sold all of dad’s equipment, cleaned out his old shop building, did the estate planning with my mom and her lawyer.
I am seeing more clearly that I have in decades. From a fitness perspective, I’m fairly certain that I haven’t missed a post since the morning of his funeral and have done EC just about every morning as well.  I’m down to lowest weight since 2006.  I’m stepping up my A-game as a senior manager at work and accelerating there as well taking on tasks that normally would have scared me off with that lack of self-confidence.  I have taken over the role of the leader in my family and stepped up to handle all of the estate planning for my Mom, closing out my Dad’s business, selling his equipment and clearing out his shop.  I have been the rock that they can lean on and rely on.  My relationship with my daughters is in the best spot that it has been in years.  
The big catalyst in my life has been that fateful day in August 2020 when I showed up to the Ridge.  I’m not telling you this for pity.  I’m telling you because you never know where someone might be at or what they have gone through.  The old adage “What doesn’t kill you makes you stronger” is right.   I have had such amazing support from many of you throughout my journey.  Nothing is that bad and can not be overcame.  We are badass and are capable of so much.  If any of you need anything or need someone to talk to, reach out to me, call me and I will be there.  I promise you this.  
So, on this Monday after Thanksgiving, I want to say what I am thankful for.  I am thankful for all of you and for F3.  I love you guys.
 
I challenge you to reflect on one thing that you are thankful for in your life on the way home.  If you can’t think of one or are in a dark place as I was, then message or call me.  Remember – you are not alone.

Aye?
Ended w prayer

Preface this with I’m not an expert in the field of running.   The stuff I’m going to go over has improved my running.  Maybe a few of these will help you become a better runner as well.  Lastly, this is not all encompassing I’m just scratching the surface regarding running and technique.  

First part I’m going to cover some high level points of performance, running position/perception, running warmup/drills,  then put what you learned into practice by running.  Finish off with some Mary.  

Concept
What is running?  How do you run? Demo with PAX.   Running is falling, falling forward. 

POSE Method
Overtime and with practice you will be able to run more efficient, run faster, run longer distances, less stress on ligaments thus avoiding injury

POSE Running Method makes efficient use of body weight and body position with a force known as gravity.  Running is falling forward.

All runners repeat the same thing in every stride regardless if you’re a casual runner, sprinter, endurance athlete, they all:

-Pass through a Running Pose
-Fall from support
-Pull foot off the ground 

Invariable elements
Pose, Falling, Pulling 

Variable elements (unnecessary and make us inefficient)
-Foot impact- Heel, mid foot, forefoot 
-Paw back, Knee drive 
-Push off/arm pumping 

Specific Focus

To Avoid Injury- Focus on the Running Pose and how quickly you pass through it-  more time on ground creates excessive load on joints ligaments and tendon.   Initial contact with ground can reduce injury.  foot strike (heel, mid foot , fore foot) - further out in front of body or behind the body the longer it takes for you to get back into running pose. 

To Run Faster - Focus on falling  - after running pose you begin falling  Fall forward from supporting leg, the faster you fall forward the faster you run.  Falling is like a gas pedal.  Stride length is an effect not a cause.  You run faster by falling further 

To Run Longer - Focus on pulling. Cadence must increase and that’s a result of pulling.  Avg  runner cadence is 165 steps per minute(spm)  POSE cadence is around 180 spm. Faster cadence can increase mechanical efficiency and oxygen consumption.  To run longer you have to pull more frequently.

Position

Springness

Bend at knees

Keeping everything in same plane (head, shoulders, hips, feet) 

Pull foot up under hip body is now in equilibrium 

Now Bring knee down until both are even (hamstring tightness and out of balance) 

Bring knee up and level with hip.  (Quads right and out of balance ) 

Running Pose
Focus on pulling foot up versus raising your knee.  Use support leg as a guide.  support leg is slightly bent.  Weight is in front of foot, but use heel for stability (demonstrate also hold foot down and have Pax lift to feel the pull)

Body Weight Perception
Goal to perceive pressure along bottom of foot, balance 

-Shift to front hold
-Shift to back hold
-Shift side side to side
-Shift in circular motion

Running Warmups/Drills

Two Leg Hop
-Rhythmic hops 
-Break contact with ground as little as possible, light heel touches
-Proper body alignment 
-Fall forward, hop for 10yds, then jog for 10 yds

Rinse/Repeat

Toes In/Out
-Toes forward, toes in, toes forward, toes out
-fall forward and continue for 10yds then jog it out 

Rinse/Repeat

Pony Drill
-Subtly pull heel off the ground. 
-Shift weight to other foot.  Slight bounce as you go foot to foot.  
-for 10 secs then fall forward and continue for 10yds then jog it out

Rinse/Repeat

Foot Tapping

•	Today I want to talk about FAILURE. This past Thursday I interviewed for a new role with my company.  It was a role that would have been a great opportunity for personal & professional growth.  It was a long process leading up to the interview where I had to complete a case study & spent many a hour prepping.  This Wednesday night I got the call that I did not get the role & needless to say I was extremely disappointed. COT: I made a startling confession. Read on:

Honesty. Let's be honest and talk about honesty. Honesty is one thing we have control over. In a world out of control, it's nice to know we can impact such an important thing. Honesty can be hard, it can be freeing, liberating, painful, hurtful, it can cut to the core like a hot knife while at the same time bring no better sense of relief. It can be the solid footing under our feet that enables us to stand.

I was once told by an elderly gentlemen, the father of my b-school's dean oddly enough, that the success to business is to never, never, never lie.

Speaking honestly, I wish I could say I honored that. I haven't. And that needs to stop, right here. Amongst my brothers. To come clean. You see, I've been living a lie for 3 years with all of you - and it's time it stopped. Brothers, I'm sorry. But my real name isn't TPS Report - it's Jason.

There, I said it. Now take this example - sure laugh - but take the example. Do not lie. Not even white lies. Just be damn honest in everything - starting with yourself. Then tell others. Let us hold each accountable to being honest. Take that step, get yourself right, get control of what you can, and be honest, starting right now.

COT:As the holiday season of 1938 came to Chicago, Bob May wasn’t feeling much comfort or joy. A 34-year-old ad writer for Montgomery Ward, May was exhausted and nearly broke. His wife, Evelyn, was bedridden, on the losing end of a two-year battle with cancer. This left Bob to look after their four-year old-daughter, Barbara.
One night, Barbara asked her father, “Why isn’t my mommy like everybody else’s mommy?” As he struggled to answer his daughter’s question, Bob remembered the pain of his own childhood. A small, sickly boy, he was constantly picked on and called names. But he wanted to give his daughter hope, and show her that being different was nothing to be ashamed of. More than that, he wanted her to know that he loved her and would always take care of her. So he began to spin a tale about a reindeer with a bright red nose who found a special place on Santa’s team. Barbara loved the story so much that she made her father tell it every night before bedtime. As he did, it grew more elaborate. Because he couldn’t afford to buy his daughter a gift for Christmas, Bob decided to turn the story into a homemade picture book.
In early December, Bob’s wife died. Though he was heartbroken, he kept working on the book for his daughter. A few days before Christmas, he reluctantly attended a company party at Montgomery Ward. His co-workers encouraged him to share the story he’d written. After he read it, there was a standing ovation. Everyone wanted copies of their own. Montgomery Ward bought the rights to the book from their debt-ridden employee. Over the next six years, at Christmas, they gave away six million copies of Rudolph the Red Nosed Reindeer to shoppers. Every major publishing house in the country was making offers to obtain the book. In an incredible display of good will, the head of the department store returned all rights to Bob May. Four years later, Rudolph had made him into a millionaire.
Now remarried with a growing family, May felt blessed by his good fortune. But there was more to come. His brother-in-law, a successful songwriter named Johnny Marks, set the uplifting story to music. The song was pitched to artists from Bing Crosby on down. They all passed. Finally, Marks approached Gene Autry. The cowboy star had scored a holiday hit with “Here Comes Santa Claus” a few years before. Like the others, Autry wasn’t impressed with the song about the misfit reindeer. Marks begged him to give it a second listen. Autry played it for his wife, Ina. She was so touched by the line “They wouldn’t let poor Rudolph play in any reindeer games” that she insisted her husband record the tune.

My M did say to me a few times that it could wait until she got done working out and we could work on it together.  At the time , my thought process was this was a task that needed to get done otherwise it might be a late night project for everyone in addition to all the other stuff going on like dinner, etc.  So my 2.0 and I ended up finishing  it.  When my M got down working out she seemed upset.  Come to find out that she really wanted to work on it together.  We both sort of got upset with each other as my M really wanted to work on it with my 2.0 and I wanted to help out so she could go workout.  Lack of communication on our part was the cause for the anger.  Interesting enough I ran across this quote below on social media later in the evening.  I brought it up to my M and we both hugged it out and agreed it wasn’t worth being angry about and we just needed to communicate better.  

“Every time you get upset at something, ask yourself if you were to die tomorrow, was it worth wasting your time being angry?”   Robert Tew

We all have different times when we get angry about various stuff.  Sometimes the anger may be justified, but just keep things in perspective and ask yourself is it worth wasting your time being angry.  Aye!

ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: I wanted to talk about something that I have been reflecting on lately.  I have been making a point to spend time on my hobbies and try and discover new ones too.  Currently, my only active hobbies are exercising and the piano.  I have been making a point to play the piano more and have been trying to find new hobbies.  Hobbies are great for your mental well being.  Hobbies help you unwind from your day and lets you do something that helps you feel happy or more relaxed.  Recovering from my dark period of depression and not healthy relationships for most of my adult life, hobbies are a great way to help me rediscover who I truly am.  I have tried doing some new hobbies or ones that I haven’t done in years on nights I don’t have my girls lately.  One night I made a small scale doghouse out of wood and painted it while watching old TV shows.  Another night, I went to Topgolf with a few F3 guys and played some golf which I haven’t done in a few years.  I also have been playing the piano a few times a week now.  I had only done like once a month for the past year or two.
My challenge to you is to make a point to engage in a hobby this week.  It can be a hobby that you already do or it can be something new.  Don’t lose sight of who you are.  Aye?
Ended with prayer

COT:Occasionally when I don’t have something specific I deem worthy of sharing as part of a COT, I will do a quick check to see if there a significant person or event on our around that day that I can draw inspiration from. This being one of those days, I was pleased to learn that today is actually the birthday of one of my favorite writers, Jack London. During his life Jack London was quite a successful author. His most famous works include The Call of the Wild and White Fang. Anyway, I came across this quote or credo that is attributed to him: “I would rather be ashes than dust!
I would rather that my spark should burn out in a brilliant blaze than it should be stifled by dry-rot.
I would rather be a superb meteor, every atom of me in magnificent glow, than a sleepy and permanent planet.
The function of man is to live, not to exist.
I shall not waste my days in trying to prolong them.
I shall use my time.”

The way you handle, analyze, and overcome the unplanned is so key to success.  Your first gut feeling maybe to get upset, think to quit, but you need to take that energy to understand why this situation happened.  What can i learn from it to do better next time. After a few recents deaths of people I know and attending the F3 Naperville Memorial for the fallen F3 PAX, the following poem struck a chord with me having heard it this past Saturday at the memorial so I thought I’d repeat it again, 

The Dash Poem (By Linda Ellis) 

I read of a man who stood to speak
At the funeral of a friend
He referred to the dates on the tombstone
From the beginning...to the end

He noted that first came the date of birth
And spoke the following date with tears, 
But he said what mattered most of all
Was the dash between those years

For that dash represents all the time
That they spent alive on earth.
And now only those who loved them
Know what that little line is worth

For it matters not, how much we own, 
The cars...the house...the cash.
What matters is how we live and love
And how we spend our dash.

So, think about this long and hard.
Are there things you'd like to change?
For you never know how much time is left
That can still be rearranged.

If we could just slow down enough
To consider what's true and real
And always try to understand
The way other people feel.

And be less quick to anger
And show appreciation more
And love the people in our lives
Like we've never loved before.

If we treat each other with respect
And more often wear a smile,
Remembering this special dash
Might only last a little while

So, when your eulogy is being read
With your life's actions to rehash...
Would you be proud of the things they say
About how you spent YOUR dash?
————-
Thanks to the PAX for showing up, putting in the work, trying to get better!  Keep it up!

Lastly, if another man has not told you today, I love you! Aye!

As part of the circle of trust we often times invite everyone to join in a moment of silence, or a prayer, today I’m going to take a knee and pray with my Lord and savior, Jesus Christ  and I welcome you to join me.  If however that’s not your thing then please take a moment of silence for reflection……….Amen

THE THANG: 
Thang 1 – around 10 minutes until 5:30
Two stations about 200 feet apart at either end of aisle in parking lot
Split into two groups and started at each station.  OYO
Station 1 – 20 curls and 20 shoulder presses
Station 2 – 10 bobby hurleys and 10 leg raises
Side shuffle between stations always facing same direction so lead leg switches each time
  Thang 2 – 4 corners
  Station 1 – pavilion – 20 dips and 20 derkins
  Station 2 – West end of parking lot – coupons – 20 bent over rows & 20 gobblet squats
Station 3 – South side of lot by entrance driveway – 20 merkins and 20 donkey kick with each leg (on one knee and kicking backwards with other leg)
Station 4 – East end of parking lot by playground – 80 jump ropes and 40 LBCs
Run between stations.  Split so half started at a station and half at another so wouldn’t run out of jump ropes at station 3.  Rinse and repeat.  OYO

MARY: 
Big Boys, Pickle Pushers, American hammers, freddy mercuries, merkin ring of fire
ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: For my COT today I wanted to talk about something we discussed in Q-source yesterday.  Q-source was about the three types of groups – community, organization and team.  Community is two or more people that voluntarily live in close proximity.  An organization is two or more people that voluntarily combine for the accomplishment of an articulated purpose.  They differs from the community because the members of an organization are defined by they shared mission and not their proximity.  The final group is the team which is two or more people who combine to perform a specific mission for the benefit of a community, and organization or both.  The team is different than an organization because the members also are in close proximity.
We had a good discussion if our families were a community or a team.  Does your family have a mission.  Most families are communities where you are in proximity but you don’t have a mission.  Living in the same house but everyone basically doing mostly their own thing. 
We talk about always accelerating in F3 and if you aren’t accelerating then you are decelerating.  There is no maintaining.  The foundation to the family is your relationship with your M.  You two have to be in a good point first.  My challenge to you is to reflect on this and talk with your M come up with a shared mission for you two.  Nothing crazy here.  Just get on the same page of how you and your M will work towards your shared mission.   Maybe to get that spark back that may have dimmed over the years together.  How will you do that?  Maybe a simple goal or two at first like one date night a month?  Or maybe picking a simple topic and exploring it for like 10 minutes at some part of every day.  Such as “what was your strongest feeling today?  Then describe it using shared experiences so the other person can “get” your feeling and empathize with it.   I’m saying that it can be like 5-10 minutes a day and if you can have that simple conversation where you two can experience the shared feeling then you have grown closer than you were before that short conversation.  Then you keep it up and make it a habit.  You will continue to accelerate your relationship.  Keeping your relationship with your M a priority is so important. I know you are probably thinking something like Foundation is the last person who should be giving advice about relationship with your M.  Yes my marriages ultimately failed but I busted my ass trying everything in my power to make them work.  I did over 10 years of research involving attendance in marriage seminars and over 20 weekend getaway couple sessions, therapy,

•	Today I want to talk about Failure.  While the Challenger is an extreme example of failure it also represents a great example of learning & forging forward.  In an instant the dream of a nation became a disaster all b/c the small details were not taken care of.  Ultimately the space program was shut down for 3 years.  If you will also remember this was going on during the time of the “Space Race” with Russia.  What we saw at this time was actually a coming together of Russia & the US to collaborate on solutions to make space travel safer actually helping to unite the 2 countries.  Following that 3 year period the space program launched over 88 successful missions the next 14 years.  So while failure at the time of impact can be crushing & defeating if you have the fortitude to learn & persevere the ultimate outcomes from that failure can accelerate you way beyond where you would have been if you would have never experienced failure at all.  AYE!

You have probably heard me talk about the book "The 5 Love Languages".  If not, stop what you are doing and order this book.  It is a game changer for how you and your M communicate.  

Being in the Health Care Industry we have seen a lot of clinicians burn out, extreme staffing challenges, and many policy changes during the pandemic.  We spent 2021 with a Growth mindset.  We spent a lot of time, money, and resources on recruiting with poor outcomes (it is so hard to find good staff).  We decided as a management team that it is time for a new mission; "Get back to basics and employee appreciation".  We are pumping the breaks on growth, focusing on process improvement (what is the underlying cause?  How to fix the initial problem that started at the beginning of the pandemic and has only had bandaid like solutions to address it), and most importantly Employee Appreciation.

We always strive to support our employees but are we doing it in a manner that they feel appreciated?!  Here comes the book "The 5 Languages of Appreciation in the Workplace".  My M and I are now listening to this book on our rucks to create a plan to truly understand our employees and appreciate them in a way that makes them feel appreciated.  The generic "Employee Appreciation Week" is so canned and not personalized that most employees almost resent the idea.  I'm very excited to get our business back to basic and create a replicable blueprint to start our expansion into other states by 4th quarter.  Most importantly, I am excited to create an even better workplace for our employees to feel appreciated and have the ability to grow.

COT: For my COT today, I wanted to talk a little about an area that I have been thinking about a lot lately.  We as Dad’s have such an impact on our kids.  As I have less time with my daughters, I want to make sure to provide as much support as possible during my time with them.  I thought I’d share something that I read.  
It’s the 8 things that every daughter needs to hear from her Dad:
1.	I love you
2.	You are beautiful
3.	You are a wonderful person
4.	I really like spending time with you
5.	I’m there for you
6.	I will protect you
7.	I will provide for you
8.	God loves you and has given you many special abilities and gifts to fulfill a special purpose.
Notice it didn’t have on there about giving her the latest I-phone or taking a vacation to Hawaii.  Your daughters’ self-confidence and self-esteem is related to the amount of praise, unconditional love and support that she gets from you.  There are so many negative things out in the world but she can and will overcome them if we just give them our love, support and praise.
For those of you out there with daughters, I challenge you make a point to do something with your daughter this week.  It doesn’t have to be earth shattering.  She just wants to know you care and be with you.  Ask her what she wants to do and do it.  Last Friday night I asked my 14 year old what she wanted to do and she came out of her room and said that she wanted to play some duets together with her on the oboe and me on the piano.  We have never played together before but we did that for about an hour and a half.  It was an awesome time.  So, I repeat my challenge.  Just ask your daughter what she wants to do.

COT: I remember when I was still in college, and I was working with a large church in Southern California. It was big - had like 6k members. I was part of the Jr High ministry - they were on the 3rd floor. (that's how big it was).

Anyway, I was asked to share over the summer, and the topic was "faith". I knew exactly where I'd go to get some good insight: my father. My dad has been in ministry for over 50 years, as a pastor, church planter, youth worker, and now a pastoral counselor. He's been studying the bible his whole life, has gotten multiple degrees in the field, helped write books about our faith and walk in life, saved lives (literally), served as chaplain, and considered an expert in his field. I figured if anyone could lay out a theologically ground shaking interpretation that rocked the interpretations of holy writ of what faith was... it was him.

So I get on the phone, I ask him - what's the definition of Faith? His response... "mmm... Hebrews, chapter 11, verse 1: Faith is being sure of what we hope for and certain of what we don't see".

It was so simple, and so right and so true that I missed the obvious. I had overlooked that the answers to questions were in the Bible, the book that tells me the story of my God. Not a man, who despite his amazing work, was still a man, and still fails. This simple answer comes from a place that doesn't fail. A place that gives hope.

For me the "Faith" in F3 is personal. And not just because of my beliefs. It's because we all have faith that what we do here this morning, most mornings, outside, volunteering - that it will deliver what we hope for. We are sure of what we hope for - and certain of what we can't see right now. We will change because of what we are doing. We are certain of that - even if we don't see it right now.

So I encourage all of you - keep coming. Keep inviting your buddies. Keep the faith. It'll pay off. But understand - F3 will fail. It won't be forever in our lives. So I want to personally encourage you, take the example of our faith this morning, and put it in something that won't fail.

COT:Born of fire!
Began by showing the PAX a pic of seed on my phone.
This is a picture of a giant sequoia seed, the largest tree on earth. They can grow up to 30 feet in diameter, 250 feet tall and live for over 3000 years! 
However in order to grow they first need fire. Fire is necessary to punch a hole in the forest to provide more light and water. The second thing fire does is to heat the mature cones without harming the trees, the cones then open up and drop their seeds. The fire also clears away the leaf debris from the forest floor so the seeds can germinate.
I think the same can be said for our growth and development.
Struggles are a part of life.  We don’t have to like them, we  may even attempt to avoid them and continue trying to minimize their impact. Or we can allow the challenges and difficulties we encounter to expose any unhealthy patterns. In so doing we will likely reveal opportunities for new growth and development. 
99% of the time you are the only person that can ruin your day. Don't let that happen.  Lean into your struggles today and the growth that can result.

COT: 
Everyone around you; the people you share the grocery store line with, pass in traffic, sit next to at work, encounter on social media, and see across the kitchen table—they’re all experiencing the collateral damage of living.

Every single human being you pass by today is fighting to find peace and to push back fear; there are wounded, exhausted, pain-ravaged people everywhere, everyday stumbling all around us—and yet most of the time we’re fairly oblivious to them:

Parents whose children are terminally ill.
Couples in the middle of divorce.
People grieving loss of loved ones and relationships. 
Kids being bullied at school.
Teenagers who want to end their lives.
People marking the anniversary of a death.
Parents worried about their depressed teenager.
Spouses whose partners are deployed in combat.
Families with no idea how to keep the lights on.
Single parents with little help and little sleep.

Everyone is grieving and worried and fearful, and yet none of them wear the signs, none of them have labels, and none of them come with written warnings reading, I’M STRUGGLING. BE NICE TO ME.

And since they don’t, it’s up to you and me to look more closely and more deeply at everyone around us and to never assume they aren’t all just hanging by a thread. Because most people are hanging by a thread—and our simple kindness can be that thread.

We need to remind ourselves just how hard the hidden stories around us might be, and to approach each person as a breakable, invaluable treasure—and to handle them with care.  AYE?

COT: For my COT today, I want to talk about something that I was thinking about yesterday after talking with Gopher on a ruck.  We were talking about being a dad of teenage daughters and he shared how he had some great daddy daughter time with her. I reflected on my journey with my daughters who are no 17 and 14.   I had struggled with connecting with them about 2 years ago.  My marriage was in a bad place as I was and I couldn’t figure out why I couldn’t connect with my daughters.

I challenge you to reflect how you are doing with making quality time for your 2.0’s and then do something today with them. ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
COT: For my COT today, I want to start with a quote, “Be honest about your expectations with everything.  You never want to build any type of relationship on lies.  That foundation will always fail.”
The old me used to be always worried about what the woman he was with would think and ended up not truly being himself at times  This will only lead to unhappiness when one person’s expectations for the relationship are not met in the long run.  It’s not fair to both people.  As I move forward I will strive to always be open of my expectations and to be myself which allows for deeper relationships.   I am applying this concept in my professional life as well with my work colleagues.    
Being honest with your expectations in your personal relationships is so important but it also applies to more than with your M.  It can be with your work colleagues or friends.  Whatever relationship it is, you need to both be on board with each other’s’ expectations or you are setting one side up for disappointment.  I have seen how my failure to communicate my expectations and to truly be myself in the past marriages has contributed to the poor relationships.  I accept that and have learned from it.  I am trying to be open about my expectations in all areas of my life.  Dating, interactions at work, or with friends.  I had a good example of my progress of this at the workplace yesterday.  The two senior staff that are my supervisors at work both were in very bad moods yesterday and were really crappy with me in interactions at work yesterday morning.  One got really shitty over something minor and the other is always very condescending.  In past years, I would have just taken it at face value and taken it and not stood up for myself and then been upset and anxious about it.  Yesterday, I stood my ground and explained myself and could realize that he was dealing with something above and beyond the minor thing.  I let him cool off and came back later and told him how I could have done the minor thing better and owned it.  Then I asked him if he’s ok and if everything is ok.  He apologized for his outburst earlier and he is going through something and is really stressed out.  I reiterated how I’m here for him to help out at work or if he needs to talk.   I didn’t become upset over this and become all anxious for days and I helped him.  It was a win-win.  I love accelerating in all aspects of my life. 
My challenge to you is to reflect if you are honestly communicating your expectations in your personal and work lives.  If not, then make a point to work to accelerate in this area too.
Aye?

COT: I have been listening
to a Bible study of 1 Samuel and in particular, looking at King Saul. Saul was
outwardly quite kingly- physically larger, better looking, and smarter than
most… However, he inwardly he was quite insecure and ineffective as a leader.
This led to the concept of insecurity vs. humility. God made us to be exactly
who we are. When we battle insecurities (and we all do to some extent)- we are
selfishly believing we can improve on what God has already decided on for us. However,
when we can show humility and accept the areas in our lives that we are falling
short, through our Faith and hard work we can work to close those gaps through
