I think it is important for our kids to get involved with organizations that help to improve them in all aspects of their life especially in life skills.  For my daughter that has been the Girl Scouts.  Late last year she learned how to sew b/c of course she wanted to sew her patches on her vest.  This evolved into her getting a sewing machine for Christmas & since then she has been making silly little trinkets like iPhone blankets, etc.  Now let me back up to a couple weeks ago when I was having a bad week.  Some things were going on at work that were frustrating, a tough situation was involving here with in our region that I cannot help feeling responsible for, & my dad’s birthday who passed away 27 years ago was looming a couple days away.  To top it off the wallet my dad gave me that I have been carrying around for over 30 years & had been holding on by a small piece of leather finally snapped & my wallet was not functional anymore.  As the years pass & I lose more memories of my father that wallet was a daily reminder of him every day & why I have had a difficult time retiring it but here I was face to face with that reality.  As I am sitting in my office finishing out a crappy day at work my daughter walks in & says “Daddy, could I have your wallet to try & fix it?”  My immediate response was “that is really sweet baby but how are you going to do that & why?”  She responded, “I am going to sew it back together b/c I know how much it means to you”.  At that point I had no expectations that she could actually do it b/c really who sews leather back together, but my heart overflowed with happiness on the gesture.  Wouldn’t you know it she was able to sew this stupid wallet back together.  In F3 we talk about the 4th quadrant to leadership as leaving a legacy.  At that moment in time my heart was bursting b/c I could see my legacy & my more importantly my father’s legacy living out in my daughter.  My father had always raised me to be humble, kind, caring, & have a willingness to help others.  I have attempted to install those same characteristics in my kids & in that moment my daughter was representing all those characteristics I have been trying to install.  I encourage you men get your kids involved in different organizations that can teach them life skills & no matter if you see it every day or not continue to install your legacy in your children b/c you will have moments when that legacy shows through b/c “The Simple Things, Make the Biggest Impact.”  AYE!

COT
Servanthood is infectious. When I was in Argentina I stayed at a self-sufficient Bible College. Kids from all over South America were studying to become pastors, and it was a low budget operation. The students were also the staff - from prepping food to clean up to laundry, even butchering the cattle - everything was done by students. Could you imagine a system like that in our schools, or even our home? The amazing thing was - I didn’t once hear anyone complaining about their chores. In fact, many chores came up that were not “scheduled” and yet someone always happily volunteered for it. It made me want to volunteer, just because I knew how much some of these kids were pushing themselves to the limits. I realized quickly where this behavior started, and why it continued. It started with Jesus washing his disciples feet. That was the chore no one wanted to do. So when their master did it willingly and happily, the soon-to-be-viral-trend started. And it’s still going today. F3 is built in this Kingdom way. Every time you Q, you’re not just leading, you’re serving as well. Let’s keep this trend going, Aye?!

COT: I heard somebody say the sign of a good leader is asking how somebody is doing, and then waiting and listening to the response. I realize how often I walk past people and quickly mutter, “How are you?” as I keep walking. No matter how friendly I sound, my actions speak louder than my words—by not stopping and giving that person my attention, I am effectively telling them I do not care. You do not need rank or title in order to be a leader. A leader is one who cares about the people around him. A leader is one who understands he can create an environment where others feel cared for and supported. Even the simplest act of asking how somebody is doing—and then waiting for and listening to their answer—can create such an environment. The next time you are at work, or the next time you walk by somebody in the gloom before warm-a-rama, and you ask, “Hey, how’s it going?” stop and listen for the answer. Show that you care. March 14th 2020, I had been doing classes at the gym by my work for a couple years, 2-3 days a week and running about the same. I threw in some weight training once in a while and felt like I was in good shape.. sure I had a spare tire but who didn’t at 51.. 

A friend of mine that I’ve known for many years had just come over to pick up a freezer from us and started talking about this group of “crazy” sometimes intense guys that workout at 5:15, use these things called coupons, and have funny odd names for everything, even each other and asked if I would be interested… for those of you that don’t know me well, I’m and adventurer and this seemed like an adventure, so my plan was to come check out this F3 thing and hopefully find another workout that I could do on Wednesday’s, when I worked from home and maybe some Saturdays once in a while,  you know, when it was nice out. 

Well the first workout showed me that I was not as in shape as I thought I was… I remember thinking how in the hell are these guys moving that fast, lifting that coupon over their heads that many times.. doing that many burpess , and that fast…how in the hell is this guy bear crawling faster than he can walk… this is hard, this sucks.. and I loved it!  It was exactly what I was looking for…

What initially was to be a 1-2 days a week slowly turned into 2-3 days a week, thanks to some make believe contest and not long after anything less than 4/5 seemed out of sorts, while I wasn’t expecting that level of involvement I was fine with it, but what I wasn’t expecting was the other 2 F’s. The beer rucks, first Friday’s, coffeteria..every one of them provided the opportunity to get to know the other guys, hang out and have some laughs… It was odd, this felt like a little high school football and college all rolled into one.  But Probably the most surprising was the 3rd F.  What the heck was Q source and why did this workout group care about me becoming a better man, father, husband, leader…

who knew what I thought was going to be just a place to work out 1 or days a week would be the very think I needed to become the man God intended me to be,, keep pushing men.  If you haven't been to a 2nd For 3rd F event, try it you won't regret it!!! AYE

COT
A couple weeks ago our schools allowed the masks to come off, and I was relieved! I couldn’t wait to breath fresh air and not have to scream through a muffler to teach my students. So I was surprised when very few of them took off their masks when given the chance. Last week while talking to a group of kids, I asked them why they still had their masks on. Did their parents make them? No. Were they afraid of getting sick, or spreading the virus? No. Almost all of them said they were “used to it”, and embarrassed to take off their masks. What if their friends made fun of their big nose, their acne, their teeth? For these kids, it was easier just to hid behind their masks. Some of them don’t even take it down during lunch, they just stuff food in under their protective barrier. 
I am disturbed to know this is how many kids feel. What does that say about them? About others? About our future? How long will this last. Pretty ridiculous, huh?

But there’s a deeper truth here. How many masks do I hide behind? Who really knows me, who has really seen the true me? What features of me am I embarrassed to let the world see? What does this say about me, about the people in my life, about my future - and how long will this last? Let's take our “masks” down, allow our faults to be seen and help each other be the men we want to be.

Yes, do some things go your way & others do not…absolutely but there is a core F3 concept that removes “luck” from the equation & that is, PREPAREDNESS.  People who claim to be unlucky in my humble opinion are not spending enough time preparing for the expected while staying ready for the unexpected.  The more you do “hard shit” by callousing your body & your mind you are getting ready for all those moments in your life.  When you are lucky it is not b/c something just happened to you it is b/c you put the work in & some things fell into place3 while the opposite holds true for the “unlucky”.  Men, keep putting in the work, keep grinding, keep preparing, & create your own circumstances & don’t be controlled by the things you are not preparing for.  AYE!!

Dilly mentioned the other day that he doesn’t believe in luck, that through being prepared we make our own luck.  I tend to agree.  I’ve thought a lot over the past several years about what my family would be like if I lost my M.  Would I know how to check their grades for school?  Could I help fix their hair, make their lunches?  What about cleaning bathroom, the proper way to mop a floor or do the laundry.  I was lucky that I lived on my own for awhile before I met my M, so I knew most of these things.  But did she know how to the start the snowblower?  Could she go get an oil change or put air in the tires?  I may be more prepared than her, and I need to help her with that.  If I wanted to show her some of the things I do, in case I was sick or gone, I can’t just put more on her plate, I need to trade off with her to keep the balance.  That means I fold some more laundry, make a few more meals, do the grocery shopping and follow up on homework.  In other words, there isn’t man work or woman work in my house, it’s our work to do together.  The more we “cross train” our skills, the more prepared we are for the unexpected. COT: 
Today's Q Source topic is Shorties, or our kids. To stay on that same topic for my COT, I found and read the poem "If" by Rudyard Kipling. In it, he is providing parental advice to his son. The advice correlates to a concept we often talk about in Q Source, which is walking the straight line in life. The concept is to focus on staying even-keel throughout life. No one will ever always stay completely on the center line, but the idea is to keep crossing over it as often as you can. Don't let your lows get you too low, and don't let your highs get you too high.

If you can keep your head when all about you   
    Are losing theirs and blaming it on you,   
If you can trust yourself when all men doubt you,
    But make allowance for their doubting too;   
If you can wait and not be tired by waiting,
    Or being lied about, don’t deal in lies,
Or being hated, don’t give way to hating,
    And yet don’t look too good, nor talk too wise:

If you can dream—and not make dreams your master;   
    If you can think—and not make thoughts your aim;   
If you can meet with Triumph and Disaster
    And treat those two impostors just the same;   
If you can bear to hear the truth you’ve spoken
    Twisted by knaves to make a trap for fools,
Or watch the things you gave your life to, broken,
    And stoop and build ’em up with worn-out tools:

If you can make one heap of all your winnings
    And risk it on one turn of pitch-and-toss,
And lose, and start again at your beginnings
    And never breathe a word about your loss;
If you can force your heart and nerve and sinew
    To serve your turn long after they are gone,   
And so hold on when there is nothing in you
    Except the Will which says to them: ‘Hold on!’

If you can talk with crowds and keep your virtue,   
    Or walk with Kings—nor lose the common touch,
If neither foes nor loving friends can hurt you,
    If all men count with you, but none too much;
If you can fill the unforgiving minute
    With sixty seconds’ worth of distance run,   
Yours is the Earth and everything that’s in it,   
    And—which is more—you’ll be a Man, my son!

Q ten times in a month.  Become closer with my girls and be a good example to them.  16 weeks of not missing to post.  Get down to 215 lbs.  Get down to 210 lbs.  Now working towards getting down to 200 lbs.
I also have decided to step up my goals and have signed up for the Chicago Marathon and have signed up for a certified personal trainer online course.  I decided that it was time to go after a goal that I’ve had for like 30 years.  What am I waiting for?  Life is too short.
My challenge to you today is to reflect on that first quote.  Are you bored with life?  Do you have that burning desire to do things when you wake up?  If not, what is something that you have always wanted to do?   Set a goal and work towards it.

COT: 
As I stated in my PreBlast April 2nd is Autism Awareness Day, and April is Autism Awareness month. We are planning on doing something bigger later this month but for now, lets bring awareness to this disability.

What is Autism:
Autism, or autism spectrum disorder (ASD), refers to a broad range of conditions characterized by challenges with social skills, repetitive behaviors, speech and nonverbal communication. According to the Centers for Disease Control, autism affects an estimated 1 in 54 children in the United States today. Hence the 54 reps in my beatdown.

We know that there is not one autism but many subtypes, most influenced by a combination of genetic and environmental factors. Because autism is a spectrum disorder, each person with autism has a distinct set of strengths and challenges. The ways in which people with autism learn, think and problem-solve can range from highly skilled to severely challenged. Some people with ASD may require significant support in their daily lives, while others may need less support and, in some cases, live entirely independently.

So how can we help?

Be Inclusive
Being inclusive is an important part of being an ally to minorities of all types. If you know someone that has an autistic child invite the parent and their child to activities and encourage them to participate.  This hits home for me as my sister in-law has an autistic son and I have seen the looks people given them when they go out to dinner or anywhere for that matter.

Don’t Judge
It’s hard enough being a parent. It’s even harder being a parent to a child with autism. Do not judge a parent for any perceived lack of control over their children or how they choose to raise their autistic child. They are likely struggling and just as frustrated as an observer may be.  Remember, we don't know what is happening in the lives of the people we come in contact with everyday. Give people the grace!

Understand Autism
The most important step to supporting parents who have autistic children is to learn about autism and understand it. Autism manifests itself in different ways. There are many resources on the web to help you understand autism.. see the links below for more information.

Maintain Confidentiality
Parents may sometimes choose to confide in those they feel are close friends. However, that does not give permission for someone to spread private information about a parent’s struggles with their autistic child. Parents of autistic children can be supported by keeping everything they say confidential unless otherwise stated. In some cases, breaking confidentiality might not only be rude but also harmful. This can include the loss of opportunities because of the disclosure of private medical information. Respect both 
the parent’s and the child’s right to privacy.

Here are some links to learn more about Autism or to support organizations. 

<https://www.autismspeaks.org/>

<https://autisticadvocacy.org/>

<http://miracleleagueofjoliet.com/>

Rules for a Good Future (borrowed from a graduation speech Matthew McConaughey did at the University of Houston in 2016 related to 5 Rules For A Good Future). I chose to repeat one of the five.  

Never say anything is “unbelievable”.   

‘Unbelievable’ is the stupidest word in the dictionary. Should never come out of our mouths.”
When you say, “What an unbelievable performance!” all you’re really doing is placing something out of your own realm of possibility that’s actually already proven to lay inside it.
“Give others and yourself more credit. It just happened, you witnessed it, you just did it, believe it.”
The same goes for the “other” side of ‘unbelievable,’  We shouldn’t be naïve about the bad actions humans and nature are capable of, whether it’s terrorism, needless disease, your house being finished a year later than originally planned, or your best friend lying to your face.

COT: 
Last week during Q Source the group talked about Shield Locks which is the horizontal relationship between men.  These are men of similar skill that band together to protect and enrich one another.  During Q-Source today we will be talking about the concept of a Whetstone.  A Whetstone is the vertical relationship between men.  The analogy used here is a Blade which is the mentee and a Whetstone who is the mentor and sharpens the Blade.  These are not men on equal footing but ultimately both benefit from the relationship.  The Blade receives the edge or wisdom of the Stone while the Stone accelerates their own pursuit of proper personal alignment and closes his hypocrisy gap.  

The definition of hypocrisy is the practice of claiming to have moral standards or beliefs to which one's own behavior does not conform.  The reality is that none of us are perfect but by talking the talk to our Blade it helps the Stone get closer to walking the walk.  It is very hard to give your Blade advice in an area where your own personal practices don't conform to what you are teaching.

I challenge you to think about the areas where you could extend the wisdom that you have gained in life.  Are you being purposeful about giving this wisdom to someone else or are you keeping it for yourself.  The Virtuous Leader is always looking to turn Blades into Shield Locks and turn that vertical relationship into a horizontal one.  AYE!

COT: I want to start my COT with the F3 motto, “Leave no man behind, but leave no man where you find him.”
When I showed up on August 28, 2020 to the park I used to refer to as the park in the middle of Grande Park subdivision, I had no idea of what I would find.  Boston Butt Q’d and I felt like my body was going to fall apart.  But I drank the punch just after one workout.  Like 370 some workouts and now my 100th Q.  
That first day I was a serious sad clown.   Shitty 2nd marriage, ongoing constant battles with my 1st ex over the kids, out of shape, not happy at work, didn’t have any real close friends that I saw on a regular basis.  Basically miserable.
I saw something special with this group and I wanted to make the transformation that Boston Butt and others had done physically  At first it was the once a week but gradually built up to where I am posting and doing EC runs 5-6 days a week now.  I strived to become emotionally healthy as well and have accelerated in all areas of my life. 
As I reflected on my journey, I thought of some of my milestones and special memories over the past year and a half:
•	When I posted at the Ridge the morning after my Dad passed away last September and everyone came over from the other AOs to have coffeeteria at the Ridge and be there to show and give support to me.  
•	When over 50 of my F3 brothers showed up at my Dad’s wake throughout the day to provide support.  
•	The kindness of 5-Putt, Fish Sticks, Cyclone and Nickleback for the amazing funeral lunch at Mistwood.  
•	The support and conversations that I had during my divorce and grieving in the fall of 2021 saved my life and has led to deeper friendships.  The EC runs, rucks and conversations over coffee meant so much and let me know that I was not alone even though it felt like it mattered if I lived or died.  Your support helped get me through that time at rock bottom.
•	When I found out about having to tell someone when you had to leave to use the bathroom during the early bootcamp before the January 2021 Convergence.  I disappeared to LAF in the woods and had headlamps searching and can distinctly remember hearing Foundation, Foundation called out by Disco Ball and I yelled out I’m ok.  Then What’s wrong are you ok Foundation?  Then, I’m good.  Just taking a crap.  It was not too soon thereafter, Sparkler created the lexicon of the LAF or lay a foundation if a PAX had to use the bathroom during a workout.
•	Not missing a post for 16 weeks in the fall/winter of 2021/2022 and doing EC every day was something big for me since I could barely do a single workout once a week the year before.
•	I remember a certain winter workout on a Saturday at the Ridge that had four corners in the snowy field (I believe a Dr. Fauci Q) and I somehow managed to get lost and was stumbling around in the snow going to stations out of order.  I remember Vern and Joe Dirt finding this funny.
•	Getting under 210 pounds and going from a tight XXL to an athletic fit Large and going from 40 pants down to 34s.

COT
Forgiveness?
When someone does something wrong to you, forgiveness is appropriate if and only if the person recognizes what they did was wrong (repents) and asks for forgiveness. To forgive someone who is unrepentant does not reflect the love of God; in fact it takes away for the message of the Gospel (good news) of Jesus. So when someone wrongs you and doesn’t repent, what should you do? 
1. Forebear (be patient with the wrongdoer) - after all, God was patient with us. Turn the other cheek.
2. Don’t hold a grudge - that only hurts you and innocent people in your life. 
3. Love your enemies, pray for good in their life. The hurt they caused probably came from a deeper hurt in their own life.
4. Be ready and willing to forgive. They may recognize their wrong. Pray for that, and accept it when they recognize their error. Then work toward regaining the trust that was lost.

COT: 
Patriot or Mercenary 

There is a question that is often asked when building a team and it is “What Matters Most: Talent or Drive?” The obvious answer is of course we need both. However, one is significantly more important than the other. 

Talent – Proven skills and a track record of success 
Drive – Motivated and possess the right attitude 

Steve Jobs is quoted saying “When I hire really senior people, competency is the ante. They have to be really smart… but the real issue for me is are they going to fall in love with Apple? Because if they fall in love with Apple, everything else will take care of itself.” So, we must ask ourselves when hiring someone to the company or forming a team of colleagues, “Is this the kind of person who will fall in love with what we do here, with who we are, and how we operate?  This is called hiring “Patriots” not “Mercenaries”.  Patriots fight for the cause. Mercenaries fight for money.  Patriots fight with their heart and are loyal to the end. Mercenaries fight for the paycheck and can be bought away by the enemy at any time 

Wars are won by patriots, not mercenaries. Thus, missions and big goals are achieved by patriots. You are not only looking for a skillset. You are looking for a heart set.  The question to ask yourself is are the people you’ve surrounded yourself with in love with what you do? Do they care about what you care about? Are they Patriots or only Mercenaries? 

This article relates to the business world and who you have on your team to achieve your companies vision and mission, but we can relate this to our personal life also.  Who have you surrounded ourselves with?  Do their values align with yours?  Are their motivations for the benefit of a mutual vision or just to benefit themselves.  I feel we are blessed as members of F3 to be surrounded by men who truly want to make differences in the communities they live and support one another in this pursuit.  Aye!

CoT:  Don’t Take Things for Granted
•	In F3 we learn of the concept called the Concentrica.  This concept is built like a bulls eye teaching us that the most important relationship in your life should be at the middle of that bulls eye & you should be attempting to shoot as many of your arrows towards those inner circles.  At the middle of my Concentrica is my Wife, the most important relationship in my life.  Tomorrow my wife & I will celebrate our 17 year anniversary.  I am proud to say that we are a couple who rarely fights, believe in the same values, have the same vision for raising our kids, & generally have a great relationship.  What I am not proud of is I tend to take a lot of that for granted & the arrows in my quiver take more aim at some of those outer circles on of my Concentrica particularly with Mammon (work) & our 2.0’s.  While the 2.0’s are extremely important just b/c you are doing family activities does not necessarily mean you are strengthening that relationship with your wife/significant other.  In Q1 I had a goal to read the “5 Love Languages” together with my wife but I constantly kept pushing it off b/c I did not prioritize or I set some dating goals only to find myself dating my kids more than my wife.  For me I need to refocus & not take that relationship for granted, honor the commitments I make, & do the small things that add up to big things.  My challenge to all of you is to do some reflection on the “m” in your life.  While you may be doing things together are you truly being intentional about that relationship.  If not then put together a plan to be more intentional.  AYE!!

COT:
The paradox of our time in history is that we have taller buildings but shorter tempers, wider freeways, but narrower viewpoints. We spend more, but have less, we buy more, but enjoy less. We have bigger houses and smaller families, more conveniences, but less time. We have more degrees but less sense, more knowledge, but less judgment, more experts, yet more problems, more medicine, but less wellness.

We drink too much, smoke too much, spend too recklessly, laugh too little, drive too fast, get too angry, stay up too late, get up too tired, read too little, watch TV too much, and pray too seldom. We have multiplied our possessions, but reduced our values. We talk too much, love too seldom, and hate too often.

We've learned how to make a living, but not a life. We've added years to life not life to years. We've been all the way to the moon and back, but have trouble crossing the street to meet a new neighbor. We conquered outer space but not inner space.

We've done larger things, but not better things. We've cleaned up the air, but polluted the soul. We've conquered the atom, but not our prejudice. We write more, but learn less. We plan more, but accomplish less. We've learned to rush, but not to wait. We build more computers to hold more information, to produce more copies than ever, but we communicate less and less.

These are the times of fast foods and slow digestion, big men and small character, steep profits and shallow relationships. These are the days of two incomes but more divorce, fancier houses, but broken homes. These are days of quick trips, disposable diapers, throwaway morality, one night stands, overweight bodies, and pills that do everything from cheer, to quiet, to kill. It is a time when there is much in the showroom window and nothing in the stockroom.

Remember, spend some time with your loved ones, because they are not going to be around forever. Remember, say a kind word to someone who looks up to you in awe, because that little person soon will grow up and leave your side.

Remember, to give a warm hug to the one next to you, because that is the only treasure you can give with your heart and it doesn't cost a cent.

Remember, to say, "I love you" to your partner and your loved ones, but most of all mean it. A kiss and an embrace will mend hurt when it comes from deep inside of you. Remember to hold hands and cherish the moment, for someday that person will not be there again. Give time to love, give time to speak, and give time to share the precious thoughts in your mind. And always remember, life is not measured by the number of breaths we take, but by those moments that take our breath away.

MARY:  Captain Thors 
ANNOUNCEMENTS:  
COT: Lately, I’ve thought a lot about what’s important in my life. I came up with these three basic areas:
•	Family and friends – M, 2.0’s, parents, siblings
•	Happiness and enjoying life
•	Work
I’ve reflected on this and tried to figure out why my journey has been a really bumpy ride. Shit, it’s been a road full of potholes that would break most cars axles not just a flat tire. I’ve realized that I’ve gotten so caught up in just one area and focused so much in one area that I’ve neglected almost completely other areas. Example, My trying so hard to please M’s has left me neglecting other family members, my own happiness and my work life. Poor self-confidence/image and some other factors played into this and I’ve been working on these areas and have made great strides. The areas that suffered were relationships with other family members and friends, my jobs, and my happiness.
My epiphany was that in order for me to be the best man, best Dad, best spouse that I can be then I need to have a good balance through all of these areas. As I am at the threshold of the next phase in my life, I am trying to be mindful of my past mistakes in my life and find a good balance between all these areas in my life.
My challenge to you is to reflect on these three areas – family and friends, your happiness and your work life. What is one area that you feel needs some improvement? Maybe reconnecting with your M? Spending more time with your 2.0’s doing something that is important to them? Maybe it’s your happiness – have you lost track of doing things that you enjoy regularly? Pick an area and then do something about it. It doesn’t have to be something huge but movement in the right direction. Every marathon or half marathon that I ran over the years always started with a single first step and it built from there.
 
Aye?
 Ended with Prayer

Quote- “When we are no longer able to change a situation, we are challenged to change ourselves.”  Victor Frankl

Austrian psychologist Viktor Frankl is known for developing logotherapy, a psychological approach based on the idea that humans are motivated primarily by the search for purpose and meaning. Frankl developed the theory largely as a result of his experiences as a concentration camp prisoner during World War II, where he was part of an effort among the prisoners to prevent suicide attempts. Frankl’s work has informed many modern trauma therapies, and his words still ring true to anyone who feels trapped in their circumstances. Even in the most difficult situations, we have control over ourselves and how we respond to adversity.  

Having a conversation with my M about how we’ve always been sort of uptight about stuff.  Always needing things to be perfect.  Like when you have guests over and always worried about how the house looks, if the furniture is dusted, etc.  Recently I’ve found that this is a very normal response/mindset for others.  Maybe this need to be perfect comes from how we were raised or maybe it’s a result of us trying to portray ourselves a certain way or maybe it’s just that we want to keep things nice since we paid a good amount of money to have nice things.  My M and I have decided to be less uptight about things because in the end other people don’t really care or notice all that stuff we get so uptight and worried over.  We put all this pressure on ourselves and for what?   In the most adverse times of our lives and in those times where we make  situations more difficult for ourselves then they really ought to be, if you feel trapped always remember that you have the power to control not only yourself but also control how you respond to adversity

TAPS (Thoughts and Prayers)

Salinger’s eloquent prose captures the daydream of youth being awakened by the reality of what true strength looks like—the ability to live every day, day-in and day-out, consistently holding a core value in sharp focus and using it as one’s north star versus the shooting comet of a single act. My son plays volleyball and at their game this past Saturday, his team got their butts kicked the first two games. I could tell Timmy was getting frustrated; his team is full of younger players and they were playing a good team. I grabbed him before the third game and told him he needed to be a leader and step up for his team. He channeled his frustration and had the best game of his life, leading his team to win the last game.

Afterwards, I asked him what was going through his mind when they were losing. He said he was ready to just give up because he felt like that is what his teammates were doing. Then he got mad and decided to be aggressive.

We talked about how a few of his teammates don’t want to play volleyball and are only there because their parents make them. I struggled with how to address that with him. And it reminded me of the Accountability Q Point from Q Source. Dredd talks about the difference between men who can’t and men who won’t meet the standard. With men who won’t, the only option is to persuade them to want to. But for the men who can’t, the Q does not give up on a Member willing to Accelerate as long as it is possible that he might meet the Standard if he continues to work.

I love that each of you came out this morning in this brutal weather to keep accelerating. I won’t ever give up on you!

I want to read a passage from the Minivan Centurion book that Dredd wrote & this is from the chapter called 3 Dots.  I like this chapter b/c it makes us rethink the true meaning of some core essentials.

The creator endows men with three unique characteristics: courage, strength, and commitment. Courage is not fearlessness, but rather the setting aside of fear to turn hardship into grace. Strength is not just the physical presence, but the emotional durability required to resist great force or pressure. Commitment is not just unwavering loyalty to others but the unflinching determination to place their needs above one’s own. 

Together, courage, strength and commitment form the essential package of manhood that is hardwired into every male of the species. Like the sliding doors on a minivan, it is our standard equipment. A child is born as a boy, but it is through the Three Dots of courage, strength, and commitment that he may flourish into a man in full capable of discharging the primary purpose for which his creator formed him from mud.

COT: 
I spoke about mindset. I have been coaching my son's volleyball team, and I have noticed the kids will do great during practice and then fall apart during games. As I tried to figure out what the problem was, I finally asked during one of our games if they were getting nervous. They all emphatically said they were. I explained to them they have control over that, and they should focus on playing the game and shake the nerves. I have seen the progression as they individually make a play during a game and gain confidence, and they are all getting more comfortable on gameday.

This correlates to what I see in the gloom, to include myself. So many times PAX are limiting themselves with their mindset. "I can't run that far, or at that pace." "I can't keep up with a Black Diamond." "I could never run 5 miles." "I can't...." "I can't..." "I can't..." I have also seen the flipside of this. PAX cast their self-doubt to the side and all of the sudden begin to accelerate beyond what they thought they were possible of.

Find someone that is limiting themselves and help them get out of their own head. And work on doing it for yourself too, in all aspects of life.

COT:  You do THIS between 10-200 times a day 
One night four college students were out partying late at night and didn’t study for the test which was scheduled for the next day. In the morning they thought of a plan. They made themselves look dirty with grease and dirt. Then they went to the dean and stated that they went out to a wedding the night before and on their way back the tire of their car burst, and they had to push the car all the way back. Thus, they were in no condition to take the test. The dean thought about it for a moment and responded that they could retake the test in three days. The students thanked the dean and said that they would be ready by that time. On the 3rd day, the students appeared before the dean to take the test. The dean explained that there was a special condition for the test. All four students were required to sit in separate classrooms for the test. All students agreed as they had prepared well over the last three days. The test consisted only of two questions with a total of 100 points. The 1st question asked “YourName” for 1 point. The 2nd question asked “Which Tire Burst” for 99points. 

Lies tax your brain, cause stress, and harm your body. When you lie, you create what is called “cognitive dissonance”, which describes the discomfort you feel when holding two or more conflicting thoughts. Lying requires a lot of effort. When you tell the truth, you simply remember what happens. When you lie, you must consider what you’re trying to hide, figure out a believable version of the opposite, give a convincing performance to sell that lie, and then remember it for the rest of eternity so that you never get caught. Even if you’re pretending to enjoy a loved one’s unpleasant meal or gift, it creates a lot of pressure. Furthermore, it builds and builds each time you lie. According to Deception Experts, the average person lies3 times within the first minute of a meeting with a stranger and between 10-200 times a day. :astonished:

Commitment – noun
com·mit·ment
: the attitude of someone who works very hard to do or support something
 
I didn’t write the following, but wanted to share:
When it comes to a commitment, it will often call you to a greater sense of purpose while demanding that you remain determined to follow through on your decision and your commitment all the way to the end. We will often be judged by the quality and consistency in which we make and keep our commitments.
 
A few steps to consider when we want to make a difference and are choosing to be invested so our commitment is something that moves us from being ourselves:
 
Prioritize: Commitment takes time and effort. If we don't prioritize these two things, we will always struggle to keep meaningful commitments.
Be Proactive: Commitment isn't a passive process. We need to be proactive in our commitments. This means giving more effort than what is expected.
Right Attitude: So much about how we approach life has to do with the attitude we hold. The more positive an attitude we take the more energy and enthusiasm we give.
Aye?

Four stations set up in parking lot, each cone has three rounds of exercises shown.  Pax start at one cone, do Round 1 exercises and then have to run to the middle and do 4 Blockees, then rotate to the next station/cone.  Rinse and repeat.

Announcements

COT
I was with a different group of men a few weeks ago and one of them out of the blue asked us all these two questions:  1)  Do your kids have a good life?  2)  Do your kids have a life that is at least as good or better than yours when you were growing up?  These two simple questions started a good conversation of how we all grew up in different ways and what we thought the definition of "good" was.  A bit different for everyone.  But it also served as a reminder for all of  us that not all kids are living well - not half way around the world or in bad neighborhoods in Chicago, etc - but maybe right down the street from us, or the next town over.  We can't take for granted that everyone has a happy and solid home life and we need to remind ourselves of that in our every day life.

Prayer
We prayed for quite a few people and for the people of the Ukraine.

I'll share a story.  A man was travelling down a highway in his car when the semi-truck ahead of him loses a tire.  The man did his best to avoid it but he was unable.  The tire hit the windshield head on and it shattered.  The man was able to control the car though and safely park the car on the shoulder of the highway.  Once he was settled he picked up his cell phone and called his wife.  He told her about the tire and the broken windshield.  His wife was immediately concerned that he was badly cut from the glass.  He reassured her that he was fine because the glass was tempered.  When it broke it failed as designed into many small pieces instead of larger jagged pieces.  Tempered glass is glass that has been heat-treated to make it harder, break safely, and limit the potential injury.   Similar to tempered glass, if we as people employ temperance we are much less likely to inflict pain when we break.  Aye!

COT:
Thomas Jefferson said: “Nothing can stop the man with the right mental attitude, and nothing can help the man with the wrong attitude.”
Don’t wait for motivation to come knocking at your door because know it’s never knocks. Go confidently in the direction of your goals and live your life the way YOU want to.
But, to do this, you need courage. Courage isn’t the absence of fear. Rather, it is conquering your fears and moving ahead.
Leave your fears behind. Don’t be afraid of stumbling and falling. Failure isn’t falling down; it is staying down. If you fall, get up and move on. Never let your eyes move away from your goal. Forget about obstacles. 
As Henry Ford said, “Obstacles are those frightful things you see when you take your eyes off your goal.”Example: I was running the other day and my cadence seemed good, my breathing was in rhythm then I lifted my head looked off into the distance distracting me from my purpose, I lost my cadence, my breathing rythmn and I began to let my mind take over and I suddenly had to stopped catch my breath. It was so much harder To get my rhythm back. This only took about 2 minutes. What would have happened if I allowed it to take over and last 5 minutes, ten minutes or even 15? It would of  made it even harder to get moving again and possibly made it harder for me to even think about trying again l. So Know your goal, Keep your eyes ahead just enough to know where your going, be in the moment because the finish line will always come when you least expect it.
Prayers
We are not a religious organization but a faith based one. I find my faith in Jesus and if you do as well please join me and if you do. It take a moment of silence/appreciation to a power higher than yourself. Father God we lift up Picasso in his job search(he did state that he needed to hear the first pet of todays cot) we lift up the unimaginable war going on over seas and the people who are effected from the soldiers to the families who have their sons and daughters fighting and the surrounding countries. Please keep our us and our family and friends safe in our travels through the weekend. Amen

COT

Rules for a Good Future (borrowed from a graduation speech Matthew McConaughey did at the University of Houston in 2016 related to 5 Rules For A Good Future).

“A Roof Is A Man-Made Thing”

You ever choked? You know what I mean, fumbled at the goal line, stuck your foot in your mouth once you got the microphone, had a brain freeze on the exam you were totally prepared for, forgot the punchline to a joke in front of 4,000 graduating students at a University of Houston commencement speech?
The reason we sabotage ourselves right before the finish line is that we put artificial limits on ourselves. Ceilings that keep us tied to the familiar. Roofs. But they’re just in our heads.
“We shouldn’t create these restrictions on ourselves. A blue ribbon, a statue, a score, a great idea, the love of our life, a euphoric bliss. Who are we to think we don’t deserve or haven’t earned these gifts when we get them?”
It’s true. There is no golden ticket to success. In a chaotic world like ours, nothing is. All there is to do is the work itself. The work of doing a great job, regardless how menial the task. The work of deserving the accolades and riches you desire. The work of building a life you love. To do this work, all we need are five rules:

Accept that life’s not fair.
Never consider anything to be impossible.
Find joy in what you do instead of chasing happiness.
Create your own definition of success.
Make decisions that’ll give back to you tomorrow.

This may not be the recipe you’d hoped for when you set out on this thing called life, but it’s the recipe you, and I need. No more ceilings.
Whatever limits may have been there to what you want to be, who you want to become, the internet has destroyed them completely. You get to invent yourself. You, and you alone. But in order to do this, we have to play like there are no ceilings. Set our sights on the highest heights we can fathom.
“Bo Jackson ran over the goal line, through the end zone, and up the tunnel.
We do our best when our destinations are beyond the measurement, when our reach continually exceeds our grasp, when we have immortal finish lines.
When we do this, the race is never over. The journey has no port. The adventure never ends because we are always on our way.
Do this, and let them tap us on the shoulder and say, “Hey, you scored.” Let them tell you, “You won.” Let them come tell you, “You can go home now.” Let them say, “I love you too.” Let them say, “Thank you.”
Take the lid off the man-made roofs we put above ourselves. And always play like an underdog.”
Always play like an underdog. Run right up the tunnel. I like that.
This attitude won’t guarantee you’ll always succeed, but when you do, you’ll exceed everyone’s expectations — including your own. You won’t play just to play or to satisfy other people’s rules. You’ll always be playing to win.

TAPS (Thoughts and Prayers). Amen!

COT:
A man has four options when anxiety threatens to overwhelm him. He can 1) surrender to it; 2) confront the emotion himself; 3) seek help in battling it from another man; or 4) Pray.
Option one doesn’t work at all. Men who surrender to anxiety as a permanent condition of their lives are the Amateurs who end up as Mascots with their boats capsized in the river. They cannot hope to be Right. At best, they can only do their best to seem Right.
Option two is only marginally better. Unlike the surrendering Mascot, the man who confronts his anxiety by himself has at least joined the battle. However, he is unlikely to succeed. Anxiety is a powerful emotion. How can a man alone be sure that his fear and worry is not warranted by his circumstances? A man alone cannot provide himself with the objective counsel required to determine whether his emotions have crossed the line from healthy self-preservation into unhealthy anxiety.
Option three, seeking help from another man to battle anxiety, is far better. It is a major Advantage arising from the Shield Lock–one may be overpowered, but two can defend themselves. However, if that is all a man does then he is still acting like an Amateur rather than a Pro because he will continue to try to Control his anxiety rather than getting ready for it through Preparedness. To truly overcome anxiety, he must also Pray.
Anxiety is an emotion that all men can expect periodically–it is part of the Flux. What is unexpected is the timing of it and the degree to which it will hinder Acceleration. As a result, anxiety is a condition that has elements of both the expected and unexpected. We can get ready for some aspects of it but must be ready for others. When anxiety arises unexpectedly it is the man who is in Right relationship with his Creator who is best able to withstand it because he will be equipped with Hope.
Hope is not self-generated. It starts with a firm belief that some force outside of oneself is directing Events and that the force has our best interests in mind. Through Prayer, the HIM builds his relationship with that force, the Creator, to disabuse himself of the fatuous notion that the force is distant, uninvolved or capricious.
To have Hope in the Creator, a man must speak to him every day through Prayer. It is a positive Habit, one of the Bricks that comprise a HIM’s Guardrails–the foundational precepts that protect and incentive his Acceleration to Advantage. They make the difference between the Pro and the Amateur.
We are not a religious organization but we are faith based. Please join me in taking a knee in giving thanks as we lift lifting up plungers father in law who lost his wife,, my brother in law fight addictions. 
Father,  I thank you for giving me the opportunities to make it out in the gloom, thank you for our Q source as it allows us to assemble in a small group setting to grow stronger in our our abilities as fathers , husbands, sons friends and co workers. I pray that when we continue to be your hands and feet today and tomorrow. In this we pray.

THE THANG: 
A new AO deserves to be launched with some classics so we went back to basics with 11's and a little Dora 1-2-3

For the 11's we covered both lower and upper body starting with 10 hand-release merkins, and 1 jump-squat, and just for fun we showcased one of Da Grizz's many hills for a little running in between.

Next was a Dora 1-2-3 of 100 merkins, 200 dead bugs, and 300 squats, while one partner ran the parking lot with 10 lunges at the turn around, and dang if there wasn't still a noticeable grade on that run too....

MARY: 
We may have done some more dead-bugs, because they are awesome, and Captain Thor also made an appearance because Captain Thor is also awesome. There may also have been some shoulder taps.... (Pro tip - write this stuff down so you don't have to speculate when you do your backblast or better yet don't make a big deal out of writing you backblast and post it while you still remember exactly what you did :facepalm:

ANNOUNCEMENTS: 
PSA - Don't agonize over your backblasts - just get 'em posted.

COT: 
I could go on for longer than anyone has time for about what F3 has done for me, my mental health, my physical health, and my relationships with my wife and kids, but I won't. I will say a big thank you to all the pax that have been posting with me, a hearty welcome to the pax who are just now joining us, and a hell yeah and congratulations to everyone whose time and effort has and continues to grow this thing. We don't do this for ourselves, though we do benefit. We do it so that we can give our best to our family's, our community, and leave this world a better place for those who come after us. To be the leaders that that the world needs right now. So keep being awesome and I'll see you all in the gloom.

Tour Da Grizz

COUNT: 8
WARMUP: 
SSH IC x 20
Abe Vigodas IC x 10
Goofballs IC x 10
Good Mornings IC x 10
Arm Circles IC x 10 (front and back)

THE THANG: 
Mosey the .5 mile to the Dam, carrying one 40lb sandbag that was rotated through the group.

At the Dam, all PAX did 10 reps of each exercise of BLIMPS (Burpees, Lunges, Imperial Walkers, Merkins, Plank Jacks, Squats) on repeat, while PAX individually took the sandbag and carried it down the stairs of the Dam and performed 10 thrusters with the bag, then moseyed back up.

Mosey the .5 mile to the field at the base of the stairs. All PAX continued BLIMPS while PAX individually took the sandbag and carried it up and down the stairs.

Mosey the .5 mile to the base of the hill. All PAX continued BLIMPS while PAX individually took the sandbag and carried it up and down the hill.

Mosey the .5 mile back to the flags.

MARY: 
Captain Thors IC to 6x24
Morty's Ab Routine: 10 second high plank to Big Boys, back to high plank (Big Boy reps go from 10 to 9 to 8...)

COT: 
The first principle of F3 workouts states they are free of charge. That doesn't mean their isn't a cost for admission. That cost is that PAX take their turn in LEADING.

F3 is so much more than just coming out for a workout. The purpose of our mission is to invigorate male community leadership. And the world is in dire need of leaders right now. Dredd, the founder of F3, authored the field manual for leadership, called Q Source. In it, he outlines 4 quadrants of leadership: Get Right, Live Right, Lead Right, and Leave Right. If you haven't taken a look at Q Source I implore you to do so. The leadership, and life, principles it contains transcend leading out in the gloom and will make you a better leader in all aspects of life.

THANG 1.0 - Partner Farmer Carry: 

PAX broke into Teams of two.  1-PAX carried both coupons up trail, while second PAX did 10 Merkins.  Once Merkins were completed, PAX would sprint to partner and they would switch.  Rinse and repeat until YHC stopped them.

THANG 1.1 - Eleven's - Lt. Dan Style
In order to give PAX a break from the farmers carries, we stopped and did Eleven's on the trail.  We stood in one spot and did 1-Air Squat and 10-Lunges (each leg 1/2).  Once all PAX finished, we continued THANG 1.0 to Pull-up bars.  Here we took another break...

THANG 1.2 - Seven's
Since it snowed, PAX were saved multiple trips up/dwn the stairs, so we did Seven's instead with Burpees and Pull-Ups.  Once all PAX were completed, we continued with THANG 1.0 and headed back to flags.  Strava was showing about 1.5 miles of farmer carries.  Nice work fellas!

MARY: 
Captian Thors upto 6/24
Pretzel Crunches 15 each leg IC
Merkin Ring of Fire, Speed round w/ 2 Merkins each

Recover / Recover

COT:
If you google the word temperance it is defined as abstinence from alcoholic drink. If you look at the origin of the word it derives from the Latin language as restraint and moderation.  I think this word has a ton of significance right now in our society in that it doesn't feel like people of showing the correct level of temperance when dealing with others that differ with their personal views.

I'll share a story.  A man was travelling down a highway in his car when the semi-truck ahead of him loses a tire.  The man did his best to avoid it but he was unable.  The tire hit the windshield head on and it shattered.  The man was able to control the car though and safely park the car on the shoulder of the highway.  Once he was settled he picked up his cell phone and called his wife.  He told her about the tire and the broken windshield.  His wife was immediately concerned that he was badly cut from the glass.  He reassured her that he was fine because the glass was tempered.  When it broke it failed as designed into many small pieces instead of larger jagged pieces.  Tempered glass is glass that has been heat-treated to make it harder, break safely, and limit the potential injury.   Similar to tempered glass, if we as people employ temperance we are much less likely to inflict pain when we break.  Aye!

Started off by commemorating Raven’s birthday 6/10/09 with 6 burpees, 10 Bobby Hurleys, 9 calf raises.

I then challenged each pax to name a person(s), a SPECIFIC person who they would reach out to in the following days. I went around the whole group, one by one, while each guy called out which family member or friend they were planning to reach out to. I then told them I would put out a blast in about a week, asking for an update on their calls, to hold them accountable.
